<h2><Center>Managing INFOWAR in the Future
by<BR>
ARNOLD E. DONAHUE<BR>
</H2></Center>

</table>
<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<td width=440>
<P>
<BR>
Download the entire<a href="arnold.doc">Word Document</a> (38K)

<P>

INTRODUCTION
	
<P>	I have been asked to address the future management and organization of the federal government for information warfare.  Where should the leadership and stewardship of the multi-faceted efforts that make up the offensive and defensive parts of INFOWAR be housed?  Who should be the head honcho of these efforts?  What should be the heads authorities and responsibilities?  Who should conduct R&D on information warfare?  Who should initiate acquisition of defensive and offensive capabilities associated with information warfare? If multi-service or multi-agency procurement is required, how should they be coordinated and facilitated?  Who should have operational control of these activities? Should one or more subentities be empowered to initiate operations?  These are questions we will explore together in the next few minutes. 	

<P>	Let me begin by postulating a number of models of US government executive branch organization and provide some preliminary views on the appropriateness of these models in performing the tasks associated with INFOWAR.
</P>

</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
