Author:	Infowar.Com
-->
<HEAD><TITLE>

Managing Information Warfare with The WarRoom

</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffFF">


<!-- Header/Nav-Bar Table -------------------------------------------->

<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td valign=top width=48>
<a href="mil_c4i.html-ssi"><img width=48 height=68 border=0 src="../../images/back.gif" alt="Back"></a>
</td>
<td valign=top width=48>
<a href="http://www.infowar.com/index.html-ssi"><img width=48 height=68 border=0 src="../../images/home.gif" alt="Home"></a>
</td>
<td valign=top width=48>
<a href="http://www.infowar.com/search_reg.html-ssi"><img width=48 height=68 border=0 src="../../images/srch.gif" alt="Search"></a>
</td>
<td valign=top align=right width=236>
<img border=0 width=236 height=68 src="../../images/line.gif">
</td>

<td width=200>
<img vspace=3 border=0 src="../../images/dot_spac.gif"><br>
<A HREF="http://www.infowar.com/sponsors/sponsors.html-ssi
"><img width=200 height=68 border=0 src="http://www.infowar.com/sponsors/ad6.gif"></A>
</td>
</tr>
</tr>
</table>
<br>
<IMG ALT="[Bomb2]" SRC="../../images/bomb2_li.gif" width=580><p>


<!-- Article Body Table ---------------------------------------------->

<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<img border=0 width=43 height=43 src="../../images/pent.gif">
</td>
<td valign=middle width=440>
<center><h2>
Managing Information Warfare with The WarRoom<BR> 
by Steven Shaker &amp; Mark Gembicki
<I>WarRoom Research, LLC</I>
<BR>
</B>
<P>

</h2>


</Center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>

<P>
<B>INTRODUCTION</B>
<P>
Maximizing the flow and control of information is key to competitiveness,
whether it be on the battlefield, in the marketplace, or on the
campaign trail.  An innovative tool and approach to planning and
managing intelligence or information in these very intense, time
sensitive environments is the &quot;war room&quot;. 
<P>
General Norman Schwarzkopf had a war room when he implemented
an end run around the Iraqi front lines and routed Saddam Hussein's
prized Republican Guards.  James Carville had one when he mapped
out Bill Clinton's strategy to win the Electoral College.  Ford
had one when they made the Taurus the best selling car in America.
 What they had in common was a central meeting area in which to
prepare, organize, and implement their efforts by having the decision-makers
visualize the situation (thus converting boardrooms into war rooms).
 Traditional war rooms are generally thought of as a conference
room dedicated to a group of individuals who are frantically pursuing
the solution to a difficult problem or engaged in a level of intense
activity.  Although useful, these rooms are not truly optimized
to their greatest potential and miss utilizing the symbiotic collection,
analysis, and dissemination components in a situation awareness
framework.  Moreover, they place a higher weight on technology
in formulating actions and narrowing decision gaps instead of
using human factors (i.e., experience, intuition).  This over
reliance increases the chances that wrong decisions will be made
if technologists are removed from the process and clearly identifies
key technology targets for adversaries.
<P>
<B>THE WARROOM</B>
<P>
The WarRoom  is basically an information-driven planning, presentation,
and edutainment facility designed to enable the most effective
and accountable decisions as possible from a variety of information
sources and virtual locations.  It supports an endless array of
domains and applications for government, commercial and educational
organizations.
<P>
The WarRoom has an embedded information processing capability
that permits a variety of multipartite information sources comprised
of textual, numerical, graphical, multimedia, and intelligence
formats for inter- or intra-organizational use.  This information
is routinely fused with other sources and displayed so as to not
<U> </U>influence a decision, but rather to present as much relevant
information as possible without the information clutter that is
experienced in typical government C3I facilities.  This is accomplished
using multivariate displays, texturizing techniques, and visualizing
information adjacent in space as opposed to stacked in time. 
This information design and display component of the WarRoom is
critical to the decision-making process, simply because default
briefing standards drive information dequantification (i.e., chartoons,
slideshows) and do not account for information causality.
<P>
Every WarRoom is divided into separate areas called 'caves' and
'commons' where specific synergistic functions are conducted.
 Each of these areas has multiple safeguards for ensuring appropriate
quality, relevance, and integrity of information.  At minimum,
caves are divided by collection, analysis, dissemination, and
security, but can be augmented for particular domains or applications.
 Commons are where self-directed work teams, or other work group
structures, collaborate to formulate proactive or reactive actions
based on the information 'piped' by each of the caves on density-rich
displays and printed materials.  This unique display approach
supports a variety of configurations based on the application
domain and physical constraints of the facility.  For example,
some WarRoom designs have three visualization walls per cave,
which are used to display and manage information, while other
designs have as many as ten.  Information can be manipulated via
several preferred interfaces (i.e., touchscreens, pointers, data
gloves) and is represented by domain specific graphical language
structures.
<P>
Considering that a WarRoom is a decision-support hub containing
sensitive information and processes, the security cave is responsible
for monitoring internal and external issues to ensure compartmentalization.
 Moreover, robust Information Systems Security, Operations Security,
and Competitive Intelligence programs have been developed for
WarRoom efforts and are highly recommended for implementation.
<P>
<B>HUMAN ELEMENT</B>
<P>
The human element is the most important factor in a WarRoom. 
This is why each WarRoom is ergonomically designed in order to
&quot;bring out the best&quot; in each of the team members.  WarRoom
Research is also developing technology associated with their Virtual
WarRoom  design.  It enables an individual operating from a small
office or home office (SOHO) or from some other remote location,
to be able to obtain three dimensional imagery, associated visualizations
and binaural sound which will replicate the information and information
flow and linkages derived from the confines of the other WarRoom
designs.  Interestingly enough, the security is not compromised
in this example, but does require expanded security measures.
<P>
Teams of creative, energetic people are the best possible tool
for which a company or governmental organization can tackle a
difficult problem.  The challenge is how to harness the synergy
of such people and maximize their potential as a group.  An initial
difficulty, is to give the group a common reference point as to
the nature of the problem or challenge.  To convey information,
teams traditionally use view graph presentations, or  project
information from a computer screen.  This mode of information
communication is serial in nature, enabling the viewer to consume
only one frame at a time. The beauty of the human mind is that
it allows for parallel thinking.  Although slow when compared
to the number crunching capability of the computer, the organic
brain can examine multiple discrete bits of information simultaneously,
and form various linkages and connections. Thus thought can lead
to learning and additional thought can be transformed into creativity
and inventiveness. The WarRoom enables an entire process to be
laid out in a framework which could never be captured on one screen
or slide.  The WarRoom provides a format for individuals within
the team to follow the whole process and logic train.  It enables
the linking of the myriad of different data sets depicting a complex
program or process.
<P>
<B>APPLICATIONS</B>
<P>
There are numerous applications for which a company or governmental
organization would use a WarRoom.  A team utilizing groupware
and various collaborative tools can lay out a WarRoom to reflect
a specific process, approach or activity.  Developing a strategic
plan and monitoring its implementation is one of the most useful
functions for a WarRoom. 
<P>
In addition to using a WarRoom for corporate business intelligence,
WarRoom Research is utilizing Portable WarRoom designs at conferences.
 These are set up in hotel rooms and are used to orchestrate what
is known as the Quarterback technique, which is a systematic and
focused collection at a conference from a well coordinated team.
 The WarRoom is used for command and control of the collection
efforts.  A WarRoom can also be used for mergers and acquisition
research, and for investment analysis.  For example, a government
organization trying to determine where it should invest its limited
resources in information warfare research and technology would
find the WarRoom of immense help. 
<P>
WarRoom designs enable individuals and teams to examine the totality
of the process and activity.  They can quickly follow the logic
train, find strengths and flaws.  If someone new is brought into
the room, and finds a certain shortcoming or gap, their input
or suggestion can be inserted on the wall, and find its place.
 Thus, the WarRoom can become a powerful advocacy tool, bringing
in others, co-opting their support by making them part of the
process.    
<P>
<B>INTELLIGENCE</B>
<P>
The old adage &quot;knowledge is power&quot; has never been more
true than in the so-called &quot;information age&quot; of  today.
 Information warfare is the means by which this power can be either
obtained or denied.  There is both a &quot;Yin and a Yang&quot;
side to harnessing information..  Success for large and medium
sized companies and agencies alike is increasingly dependent on
a timely awareness by key executives of rapidly changing events
outside the organization.  This is particularly true for organizations,
which are in the midst of a period of great transition, occurring
within a rapidly changing market, business and technological environment.
<P>
Most organizations are caught in a &quot;Catch-22&quot;.  To raise
their intelligence about opportunities, they become so involved
with gathering information that they're swamped by facts and figures.
 They have a hard time winnowing the important from the trivial.
 With this in mind, a growing number of companies are developing
a new management tool called &quot;Business Intelligence Systems&quot;
(BIS).  Business intelligence is not industrial espionage.  It
is a legal, ethical and smart approach to collecting, analyzing
and disseminating information which influences senior decision-making.
 Some companies refer to a portion of this activity as &quot;competitor
intelligence.&quot;  Business Intelligence is more inclusive and
takes into account competitors as well as collecting and analyzing
on customers, emerging technologies, regulations, budgets and
funding, etc. (i.e. the total environment impacting business).
<P>
Foreign competitors who are either owned or subsidized by their
national governments as well as the national governments who support
them, know full well the competitive advantage of an organized
intelligence program.  American firms are only beginning to discover
the powerful knowledge based management tool of a business intelligence
system.  Those corporations that are willing to take on the challenge
of developing and using their own business intelligence system,
are most likely to be the successful companies on into the 21st
Century.
<P>
In most corporate settings, executives are working with massive
amounts of raw data, small amounts of value-added information
derived from analysis, and very little intelligence.  A BIS reverses
this by shifting the focus from data to intelligence to support
the senior management.  Developing a BIS for a company involves
a form of &quot;intelligence engineering&quot;.  If one envisions
a pyramid hierarchy of information, the bottom level would be
considered data.  This information often is well known and often
&quot;stale&quot;, (i.e. too late to capitalize on).  The next
level is information, which has the value added by being analyzed
data.  At the apex of the pyramid is intelligence.  Intelligence
is information which is &quot;actionable&quot; by the key decision-maker
and has foresight.  It responds to the executive's informational
needs and leads to a decision.  Executives should be working primarily
with intelligence and less with raw data.<HR>

<P>
&#169; 1996, WarRoom Research, LLC.  All rights reserved worldwide.

<P>
WarRoom Research, WarRoom, and Quarterback are trademarks of WarRoom
Research, LLC.
<BR>

</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
