<IMG ALT="[Bomb2]" SRC="../../images/bomb2_li.gif" width=580><p>


<!-- Article Body Table ---------------------------------------------->

<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<img border=0 width=43 height=43 src="../../images/pent.gif">
</td>
<td valign=middle width=440>
<TT><B>UNCLASSIFIED</B></TT>
<center><h2>
The Electronic Battlefield:<BR> 
<BR>
</B>
<P>

</h2>


</Center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>

<B>The Strategic Implications of Information Operations</B>
<P>
<I>An advocacy for further professional examination of the new
and unconventional military environment that knows no limits</I>
<P>
SUBMITTED for CONSIDERATION
<P>
The Admiral Richard G. Colbert Memorial Prize
<P>
sponsored by the
<P>
 United States Naval War College 
<P>
<B>RICHARD F. FORNO</B>
<P>
Strategy and Policy, Washington Navy Yard
<P>
13 May 1996
<P>
Copyright &#169; 1996 Richard F. Forno
<P>
___________________________________
<P>
<TT><B>UNCLASSIFIED</B></TT>
<P>
<I>To my family and friends.</I>
<P>
<I>And especially the cadets.</I>
<P>
<B>Special Thanks</B> to: Robert D. Steele, President of OPEN
SOURCE SOLUTIONS, for providing me the three-year opportunity
for first-hand interaction with information  professionals at
his annual symposia; Zhi Hamby and the National Military Intelligence
Association for their guidance and support with my research; Professor
Jack Kramer, Professor of Strategy and Policy at the Naval War
College Seminar Program in Washington, D.C. for working with me
on this paper; COL John Macartney, USAF (Retired) for providing
me a great foundation in the field of intelligence and subsequently
information warfare; and the men of 2/2/H Company for teaching
me to think critically but in an objective manner.
<P>
We are at a crossroads in time. As the next century approaches,
new challenges face us both as a nation and as part of the global
community. Definitions of how people and nations relate, communicate,
and conduct daily business are being redefined at the most fundamental
levels. What once could only be achieved through the labor of
hundreds backed with government financing can now be accomplished
by a skilled individual supported by the commercially-available
and affordable technology of today. Indeed, the technological
revolution of the past twenty years has positioned the United
States as one of the key leaders of the technological charge into
the next millennium.
<P>
 Almost century ago, this same situation faced European nations
regarding the conduct of war. New technology brought war to a
higher level of destructiveness and expanded the battlefield far
beyond the soldier's line of sight. However, the critical shortcoming
during the years of the First World War was the inability of each
side to improvise, adapt, and replace their failing war plans
with a new doctrine that reflected the offensive potential of
emerging technologies and tactics <I>and</I> provide for the defense
of friendly forces against similar technology and tactics used
by the enemy. The result was a traditional General Staff mindset
on all sides of fighting the current war based on the successes
of the last. 
<P>
Like World War I, contemporary military technology moves the application
of force on the battlefield to a new level of destructiveness
through the improved communications technology of today. However,
unlike World War I, the impact of technology on war today - and
the creation of a new military environment - changes the very
nature, conduct, and fundamental definition of war. In these last
remaining years of the twentieth century, there are sweeping changes
in global society resulting from advances in technology and information
management. Of a singular significance is the INTERNET, the 1967
Department of Defense computer network that evolved from a United
States government network to an anarchic worldwide commercial
&quot;network of networks&quot; with no controlling authority.
This single piece of technology has given the general public the
ability to exchange instantly detailed amounts of information
anywhere in the world - a capability formerly held exclusively
by the military. Ultimately, such increases in communications
technology (the &quot;Communications Revolution&quot;) creates
substantial problems for the military planners. This paper will
examine this new threat and highly unconventional military environment,
discussing the challenges facing the tactical and strategic military
environments as they conduct operations in the Fifth Dimension
of Warfare.
<P>
Information has always been a two-edged sword. It can help allies,
confuse enemies, and yet backfire on both. The past twenty years
has seen fantastic innovation in both battlefield and warroom
communication technologies. Commanders at all levels are now being
provided instant access to increasing amounts of information,
including near-real-time intelligence, manning rosters, weather
forecasts, and battlefield targeting data - in addition to remote
communication down to the individual soldier level --  through
the use of miniature computers, remote sensing, and the constantly-evolving
products of military engineers from the industrial base. This
rapid and direct nature of battlefield communication allows commanders
to sustain the momentum of the attack and subsequently attempt
to direct the Clausewitzian dynamic of war in ways previously
thought impossible. One example is the U.S. Army's Advanced Deep
Operations Coordination System, or ADOCS. This is a major communications
component that corps commanders use to coordinate the combined
operations of Army and Air Force units in conducting deep operations.
<P>
Electronic materials and mediums such as the INTERNET, on-line
databases, telecommunications, and other such services drive the
modern world. Such instant-communications technology also drives
large business. The &quot;virtual office&quot; lets five people
over a scattered area do the work of twenty. This technology allows
students and authors to research papers or books via any of several
on-line resources and databases.  This technology allows banks
to instantly transfer money between accounts. This technology
allows private individuals to communicate so securely that even
the National Security Agency and Federal Bureau of Investigation
are concerned about their ability to respond in the interest of
national security and law enforcement. It is also this technology
that allows people - criminals, drug dealers, intelligence organizations,
among others - to communicate with their associates around the
world in the latest plot to achieve their illicit goals.
<P>
Just as the combatants of World War I faced the new threats of
 emerging military technology and had to redesign their strategic
and tactical doctrines to meet these challenges, the same circumstances
exist today - and the enemy is far more dangerous, devious, and
clandestine than simply a new piece of military hardware on the
battlefield. The threat today descends from the Communications
Revolution of the 1980s with the advent of instant-communications
and data-retrieval technologies. Now, the line between military
and civilian information technology has become blurred, and a
race is on to determine the size, complexity, and ramifications
of this global, electronic, civil-military information environment.
<P>
<B>FOOD FOR THOUGHT:</B>
<P>
<B>TOP INFORMATION INFRASTRUCTURE TARGETS</B>
<P>
 
<OL>
<LI>Culpeper Switch - in Culpeper, Virginia, this electronic switch
handles all federal funds transfers and transactions.
</OL>

<P>

<OL>
<LI>Electronic Switching System (ESS) - Nationwide system that
manages all telephone communications.
</OL>

<P>

<OL>
<LI>INTERNET - the communications backbone of science, industry,
and society.
</OL>

<P>

<OL>
<LI>Time Distribution System - all major events depend on accurate
time as recorded by government atomic clocks.
</OL>

<P>

<OL>
<LI>Worldwide Military Command and Control System (WWMCCS) - particularly
vulnerable to an electronic attack. With over twenty million lines
of programming code, it would not be difficult to insert a few
malicious lines.
</OL>

<P>

<OL>
<LI>Big Blue Cube - just off Moffett Field in Mountain View, California,
this is the Pacific clearinghouse for satellite imagery.
</OL>

<P>

<P>
Most of the men and women who create policy in government are
not of the computer generation. They don't understand code, or
the fundamental value of data, or the inherently &quot;soft&quot;
way the world works. No one is planning for the grand scale attack.
No one is planning for the grand scale defense. No one is planning
for the &quot;soft kill.&quot;
<P>
The attack will come. The defense will be necessary.
<P>
     
<P>
      ... Peter Black
<P>
      WIRED Magazine
<P>
      July/August 1993
<P>
<B>Battlespace:</B>
<P>
<B> Tactical Considerations of Information Operations</B>
<P>
<I>&quot;Information-based Warfare is an approach to armed conflict
focusing on the management and use of information in all its forms
and at all levels to achieve a decisive military advantage especially
in the joint and combined environment. Information-based Warfare
is both offensive and defensive in nature -- ranging from measures
that prohibit the enemy from exploiting information to corresponding
measures to assure the integrity, availability, and interoperability
of friendly information assets.&quot;</I>
<P>
<I>- National Defense University (Excerpt of Working Definition)
</I>
<P>
The ability to disseminate and exchange information anywhere in
the world instantly has brought war to a new, more abstract and
challenging level.  The &quot;battlespace&quot; replaces the &quot;battlefield&quot;,
a term that encompasses the physical environment of war and includes
the newly-found (but barely-charted) zone of C4 warfare or &quot;cyberspace&quot;.
War plans -- Command and Control - are now instantly Communicated
via Computers to their destination. This provides a commander
the ability to react instantly to new changes, Murphy's Law, and
the Fog of War  from anywhere in the world, thus directing the
war's dynamic and hopefully sustaining the momentum of the engagement
toward victory.
<P>
Information has always driven a war -- campaigns waged by two
or more entities on a battlefield with heavy weaponry, many casualties,
and reliance on the wisdom of the commanding general. War is still
the movement of forces to engage and overcome the enemy, [with
the overwhelming application of firepower] however, today's military
environment is driven more by information exchange at all levels
of battlespace command than by tactics or the wisdom of a single
general or his staff. Even the very essence of war - <I>battles
</I> fought by soldiers with <I>weapons</I> - has evolved to a
highly unconventional environment that knows no limits or boundaries;
an environment where &quot;force&quot; or military-initiated efforts
can be directed to a specific target (military or civilian) at
a specific time and with a new series of weapons designed specifically
for this new threat.
<P>
Disruption of the battlefield C4I infrastructure would most likely
create sufficient havoc to allow an enemy the advantage and possibly
achieve victory. Disruption or (preferably) denial of service
of key information services is the primary goal of information
warfare. Naturally, both sides will attempt this action, and the
first to do so successfully gains the tactical advantage. In the
opening rounds of Operation DESERT STORM, a successful 'communications
attack' against Iraq resulted in both the enemy's inability to
detect and coordinate a defense against the first wave of Allied
strike aircraft and our subsequent first-strike successes on 16
January 1991. This was done with specially-modified weaponry that
physically destroyed the internal circuitry of Iraqi C2 systems,
thus preventing enemy defenses from both detecting and responding
to the coalition air attack <I>and</I> from warning Baghdad. Thus,
Saddam Hussein was seriously hindered from coordinating a strong
Iraqi defense (rumor has it that he did not know where his forces
were, let alone those of the coalition!) by forcing him to use
sub-normal modes of communication.
<P>
Even during the American Civil War, the wide-spread use of, and
reliance on, the  telegraph by the Union for tactical communications
required sizable resources to protect the 15,000 miles of cabling
from attack by the Rebel forces. By the end of the war, over half
the  Union Army was deployed in defensive positions around such
vital lines of communication. Had these telegraph cables - carrying
some 3,300 coded messages daily - been severed, there would have
been an unprecedented level of C2-related confusion at all levels
in the Union Army, and the outcome of the war might have been
drastically altered. This was defensive information warfare waged
over a hundred years ago, with inferior and less reliable technology
than today's modern systems.
<P>
This radical change in the battle environment creates a major
issue in establishing an all-encompassing definition for this
new type of warfare. In the past, &quot;warfare&quot; connotated
physical violence against two opposing combatants using military
weaponry - gunpowder, tanks, or missiles - to win a battle through
the effective use of force and maneuver. This is most evident
in the writings of the leading scholar of the military arts, Prussian
Karl von Clausewitz. His opus <U>On War</U> describes in painstaking
detail how to wage a war of industry - where such war materiel
mentioned above were the primary tools in achieving a decisive
victory. It is his doctrine that permeates and dominates many
Western military schools of thought, including the United States.
Unfortunately, in an information operation, the definition of
a &quot;war&quot; expands to include a larger spectrum of conflicts,
complete with many new combatants and the application of new weaponry
in a non-physical military environment. Soldiers are now faced
with the challenge of applying conventional information technology
- computers and keyboards - in an unconventional military environment
to counter traditional military technologies and tactics.
<P>
Secretary of the Air Force Sheila Windhall and USAF Chief of Staff
General Ronald Fogelman describe this essence of war in their
shared publication &quot;Cornerstones of Information Warfare&quot;.
They see information warfare as means to an end for both strategic
and tactical purposes. While published from an Air Force perspective,
the logic and examples are applicable to all military services
and civilian organizations:
<P>
<I>Information warfare is any attack against an information function,
regardless of the means. Bombing a telephone switching facility
is information warfare. <B>So is destroying the switching facility's
software</B></I><B>. </B>(Author's emphasis)
<P>
<I>Information warfare is any action to protect our information
functions, regardless of the means. Hardening and defending the
switching facility against air attack is information warfare.
<B>So is using an anti-virus program to protect the facility's
software. </B></I>(Author's Emphasis<I>)</I>
<P>
Conducting information operations using conventional military
weaponry and doctrine worked well in the past, during situations
where the available technology did not allow a &quot;softer&quot;
method of attack, such as destroying an enemy's communications
facility by air attack. A computer virus that causes an enemy's
military C2 systems to falter achieves the same result as a bombing,
but without physical violence or destruction. Thus, a<I> </I>&quot;soft&quot;
attack provides the same result but with a noticeable absence
of violence, physical harm, or destruction. This subsequently
brings war - the application of force - to a new level of effectiveness
through the use of non-lethal technology, a by-product of information
warfare. 
<P>
<B>Infrastructure Attacks:</B>
<P>
<B>Strategic Considerations of Information Operations</B>
<P>
<I>&quot;While ultimately military in nature, Information-based
Warfare is also waged in political, economic, and social arenas
and is applicable over the entire national security continuum
from peace to war and from 'tooth to tail...'</I>
<P>
<I>- National Defense University (Excerpt of Working Definition)
</I>
<P>
The ongoing threat lies in the strategic implications of Information
Warfare. During World War II, the conduct of strategic bombing
operations against Germany's industrial complex undermined their
war effort at home - now the government leaders contended with
civil unrest, failing industry, and food shortages in addition
to their already complicated war efforts against the Allies on
two fronts. Likewise, the German V-series of  &quot;terror bombs&quot;
showered random destruction on the innocent civilians of England.
Later, in the Vietnam conflict, the Vietcong used hidden agents
to wreak social havoc and create social unrest in the South Vietnamese
civilian population. Since these &quot;plants&quot; could not
be easily distinguished from the natives and appear at any time,
this hidden threat remained an effective terror weapon during
the war. In the continuing saga of Middle East relations during
the 1980s, hijackings and aircraft bombings prompted the civilian
populace of the West to pressure the government for action and
defense against these indiscriminate acts of violence or war.
In today's information society, a logic bomb placed on a key information-processing
system is an effective method to cause civic unrest and function
as an Information Age terror weapon.
<P>
Clausewitz's Trinity of War describes the role of the People -
civilians and society at large - in the overall national security
effort. With civil unrest, a government will be unable to devote
full attention to an external military action as it must also
contend with an internal and quite angry civilian populace. As
stated, computers, information, and the speed by which it is communicated
in that void known as cyberspace drives today's society. This
new environment encompasses the military and civilian C3 infrastructure.
Phone and television services, traffic signals, subway systems,
financial institutions, and government communications - to name
a few - are now run by computers in a semi-autonomous manner.
However, this electronic Maginot Line of internetworked systems
that provides critical strategic services to the nation will grind
to a halt if a key electronic artery is cut or attacked. Jamming
one of the dozens of communication satellites that supports the
world information infrastructure is one example of such activity.
Along the many roads in America, one can see a sign that reads
&quot;CAUTION - BURIED CABLE&quot;. To a hostile information warrior,
this sign is a welcome sight and just as easily reads &quot;BURIED
CABLE -- CUT HERE.&quot;
<P>
Renowned author Tom Clancy's book series included a novel about
just such an event. In <U>Debt of Honor</U>, a virus was released
into the financial network of America with disastrous results
to the stock market and global economics. While fictitious, such
a situation could be created by a foreign nation, organized crime
group, or terrorist organization as a tool for blackmail or a
prelude for a larger, more widespread aggression. In a 1993 lecture
in France, Robert Steele, the leading world advocate of Information
awareness programs remarked to a collection of French military
leaders that 
<P>
I can destroy any major nation in 24 hours with one platoon of
knowledge warriors and make billions of dollars on the international
market by doing so, because I will know when this is going to
happen and invest accordingly.
<P>
Winn Schwartau, author of <U>Chaos: War on the Information Superhighway
</U>, is the leading civilian thinker on the subject of information
warfare and offensive information operations. His detailed discussions
about such attacks and our current inability to defend against
them bring shocked looks to his audiences' faces. His testimonies
on Capitol Hill have been met with equal disbelief. He sadly -
but correctly -  observes that today's world seems to dictate
that &quot;the computer is right&quot; - and whatever information
the computer presents - credit reports, school or police records,
 and financial portfolios - is taken as fact. Imagine the chaos
caused by a hostile organization conducting this type of offensive
information operation on a broad-scale. This has been dramatized
in recent movies and books, but this is a real threat - and does
not happen only on the battlefield operation between opposing
military units, but from one or more private individuals against
others from anywhere in the world.
<P>
 Crashing the stock market is a favorite strategic &quot;what-if&quot;
by amateurs attempting to describe the potential of offensive
strategic information warfare (OSIW), and will not be discussed
here - the global implications of a breakdown in financial information
systems are fairly well-known. Furthermore, a public misperception
is that information warfare is limited to computers, and conducted
<I>only</I> by computers. I propose the following hypothetical
situations demonstrating five OSIW attacks, some of which are
not solely computer-based (Author's comments in italics):
<UL>
<LI><B>Train Derailments or Air Traffic Control Mishaps</B>: 
In February 1996, a commuter train collided with an Amtrak passenger
train just outside of Washington, D.C. The current analysis points
to faulty signals that gave a &quot;false proceed&quot; message
to the conductor of the commuter train, who proceeded on the assumption
that the signal was correct and he was clear to speed up. This
particular railroad signal system was controlled from a nationwide
control center in Tampa, Florida through the use of high-speed
computer networks. The result of this faulty signal were twelve
passengers killed by fire, many more injured, the repair costs
for the trains involved in the collision, and the time spent on
the federal investigation of the crash and signal system. Likewise,
western air traffic control systems are computer-controlled to
relieve the work burden of human controllers. Seeing the problems
associated when these systems fail because of mechanical reasons
raises some interesting questions. <I>We're scared enough when
something breaks down under normal circumstances. What if such
computer-control systems were infiltrated, destroyed, or changed
in an intentional nationwide OSIW attack?</I>
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI><B>Traffic Signals and Power Grids</B>: In the latter part
of 1995, a school bus in Illinois was damaged by a speeding freight
train and several elementary school students were killed. This
time, the cause was  a faulty traffic signal on the road crossing
the railroad tracks, which the school bus driver naturally followed.
<I>We use the roadways to commute and travel. Millions of innocent
people are exposed and are potential targets to an OSIW attack
on local traffic-control networks</I>.  Blizzards, hurricanes,
and tornadoes cause power outages each year, and we all know how
annoying, troublesome, and in some cases, life-threatening they
can be. <I>An OSIW attack could bring down power grids down and
paralyze a city. Simply bomb the power plants and a few substations,
and you've effectively shut down a metropolis - along with its
computers, most communications mediums, and a majority of economic
resources; shops, businesses, corporations, and government buildings
would close. Such a circumstance is what I refer to as &quot;Functional
Paralysis&quot;, or a sizable Denial of Service.</I>
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI><B>Mass Media</B>: We read the paper and watch the news daily.
Through the use of a personal computer and some common commercial
software, an information warrior can electronically edit (morph)
pictures and video. Imagine the many implications if Saddam Hussein
was portrayed on Iraqi television sitting down to a state dinner
with a glass of wine, roast ham, and buxom women surrounding him?
<I>All it takes is video editing equipment to receive the actual
signal and broadcast the doctored one on the same frequency in
real-time. My mother always told me to &quot;believe half of what
you see, and absolutely nothing that you simply hear&quot;. </I>This
is sound advice for a society that can alter reality (<I>or, given
the media-driven world today, the &quot;perception of&quot; reality
</I>) with a keyboard and mouse. Edited pictures of the President,
First Lady, and other public figures in compromising situations
have already circulated around the world on the INTERNET. <I>How
many edited pictures have appeared on the front page of leading
Western newspapers already -- and subsequently accepted as &quot;fact&quot;?
</I>
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI><B>EMP Attacks:</B>  During the Cold War, there was substantial
civil defense preparation for potential Soviet attacks that consisted
of atomic devices detonated at a certain altitude over the United
States. The resulting blast of electromagnetic energy would literally
and physically &quot;fry&quot; electronics, circuit boards, computer
chips, and any other electronic item. Such weaponry exists today
in terms of a directed-EMP that can be focused on a certain target
within a certain range. <I>Given the many instances of suicide
bombings associated with terrorism, using trucks (or even remote-controlled
rockets and aircraft), picture a situation where a hostile organization
was able to physically destroy a regional electronics infrastructure
by using only a few precisely-placed atomic weapons. The result?
Functional Paralysis through Nuclear Terrorism.</I>
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI><B>Electronic Assassination</B>: Picture the surprise - you
attempt to get a new drivers' license or open a bank account only
to find out the computer has you listed as having been dead for
five years! Or that you have been arrested for prostitution, drug-related
crimes, and are badly in debt. Perhaps your employment record
shows you having never graduated high school, but yet you are
working as an engineer for a major corporation? &quot;<I>Sneakers&quot;
was a good movie, but presented some interesting and very real
threats. Anyone with a computer, modem, and some common sense
can do some very real damage to others. Again, I agree with the
&quot;old timers&quot; who still keep receipts, invoices, and
other important documents in the family safe  - not that they
don't trust computers, they don't trust the data on them or how
it's used. Today's large corporations and banks rely on computer
databases for record-keeping. Modify that information, and you've
changed the electronic life of a living, breathing person.</I>
</UL>

<P>

<P>
 The threat is real and quite verifiable - just not seen as 'practical'
for anything but the silver screen. It has many components - computers,
modems, networks, hackers/crackers, cypherpunks, the new professions
of Information Security, and prompted a revision of the aging
Telecommunications Act (recently passed by Congress amid controversy
over free speech and public assembly rights.) The harbinger of
this threat might be another country, intelligence establishment,
terrorist group, organized criminal activity, or it may be the
young professional across the hall in your apartment complex working
for such an entity. &quot;Knowledge Warriors&quot; are those who
have been reared during the Communications Revolution and are
able to navigate the endless numbers of networks and databases
with ease. Information Warriors, Knowledge Warriors, Competitive
Intelligence Specialists - the names are relatively the same.
All are able to find whatever they seek. Some are able to carry
out successful OSIW operations at the request of their employer.
All seem to make good money doing it.
<P>
During my last undergraduate year, I witnessed the ease of information
exchange and how it might benefit the intelligence community.
From my dormitory room, I was using a real-time &quot;chat&quot;
service on the Internet known as IRC (Internet Relay Chat) to
converse with a sixteen-year-old student in Sarejevo who watched
&quot;tanks rolling down my [sic] street...lots of soldiers walking
and shouting outside...&quot; Those of us on this particular &quot;chat&quot;
service felt as though we were reading a modern techno-thriller
instead of participating in an online discussion. Perhaps during
future conflicts, this type of real-time information will prove
vital in an unconventional information environment. -  conducted
by those on-site and <I>without military training or experience.
</I>
<P>
 The key problem with strategic information warfare is that <B>it
is easy to do</B>. As noted, anyone with a computer or access
to a network can search for, retrieve, or delete data on another
network from anywhere in the world using any number of techniques
ranging from on-line tools such as viruses, Trojan Horses in addition
to traditional weapons like bombs, and jamming devices. And since
the global information infrastructure has redefined the concepts
of a &quot;border&quot; and national sovereignty, a Knowledge
Warrior can easily cross into another nation electronically to
accomplish what formerly had to be done in person at great risk.
Further, since there 
<P>
are no front lines or &quot;areas of (information) operations,&quot;
anyone from anywhere can conduct information search, retrieval,
or destroy operations. Indeed, the Shakespearean paradox has come
true, for today, &quot;all the world's a stage&quot; upon which
IW operators act.
<P>
<B>AN AGENDA FOR ACTION</B>
<P>
<I>&quot;War, in common with sport, has the characteristic that
what worked well yesterday may not work well tomorrow, precisely
because it worked yesterday.&quot;</I>
<P>
<I>--Edward N. Luttak, <U>Strategy: The Logic of War and Peace
</U>(1987)</I>
<P>
 Based on the reliance on information and information technology
to drive both our military and civilian environments, there currently
is a concerted effort to design, implement, and coordinate an
Information Strategy that provides for a strong defense of national
information interests. In my judgment, there are three key areas
that must be addressed by leadership in both areas with regard
to the security of information.
<P>
 <B>Operation</B>: Implement INFOSEC measures and provide systemic
and infrastructure redundancies at all levels in the event of
an offensive information attack. This needs to be done in both
the military and civilian arenas. As noted, each of these two
areas is information-driven and subsequently vulnerable to intentional
&quot;accidents&quot; or mishaps.
<P>
 <B>Legislation</B>: Congress and the Executive Branch must agree
on formal regulation and definitions of Information Warfare and
Security. Funding and political support must be allocated to those
organizations charged with designing information safeguards for
our military and civilian environments. Organizations - both defense
(such as NSA and the individual service organizations working
the IW issue) and civilian (such as NIST) - must be comfortable
in communicating openly between each other, with a minimum amount
of &quot;required&quot; classification. (As information technology
becomes even more available and essential to the private sector,
there is less disparity between &quot;military&quot; and &quot;civilian&quot;
information assets, products, and capabilities.)
<P>
 <B>Education</B>: Common sense and user awareness drives information
security. Unfortunately, while one cannot mandate common sense
as a national agenda, there can be measures taken to improve the
situation/technological awareness for the legislators paving the
way for the development of an Information Infrastructure, the
leaders in both military and civilian sectors responsible for
coordinating these information operations, and the end users -
military specialists, civilian office workers, and John Q. Public
- who are responsible for day-to-day information operations and
who stand the most to loose if subjected to an information attack.
Education and knowledge are paramount - given the &quot;virtuality&quot;
of today's society, its members must be able to separate fact
from fiction by their own intuition and sense, and not from the
overtly-misleading media of today. What people see must not always
be taken as &quot;fact.&quot; As was commonly heard in Washington
during the Reagan-Gorbachev years, &quot;Trust, (or believe) but
verify.&quot;
<P>
 As a descriptor in the opening paragraphs of this paper, I refer
to Information Warfare as a form of <I>unconventional warfare
</I>. It is. Not only is it a new type of offensive tactic we
must defend against and develop our own offensive tactics for,
but it is not fought in the &quot;conventional&quot; method with
tanks, bullets, and ships in a theater, in a traditional military
environment on a &quot;battlefield&quot;. The IW theater is the
world, with no front lines, trenches, or advances. It is fought
primarily with keyboards, computers, networks, and information
against not simply a military targets, but strategic, civilian
ones as well. Operations are conducted in the realm of cyberspace
- in a military environment this is called &quot;battlespace&quot;.
This new environment includes foreign relations, communications,
domestic law enforcement, and military organizations as key players
in this new cyberspace environment. The leaders of this new type
of warfare are the young specialists - civilian and military -
who have grown up among this explosion of information technology.
It is only recently that our traditional thinkers in the military
have begun seriously devoting resources to examining the threat
of information warfare in an effort to determine the size and
complexity of this new environment.
<P>
 As members of the most elite military in the world, we must continue
to harness this new technology and consider the military implications
this new environment brings to our current doctrine. We must insure
doctrine remains dynamic - ready to change and adapt to emerging
trends in technology, tactics, and thought. Remember the history
associated with new technology and both sides' inability to adapt
existing doctrine to meet the new threats on the battlefield during
World War I. This is a singular lesson we must not forget as we
approach the new century and this new battle environment. As members
of the most information-driven society in the world, we must guard
against the misuse of information technology in a strategic information
attack against civilians in general. We are living and working
in  a dynamic, new, world - as its leaders, we have an interesting
and challenging job in charting and exploring this new environment.
<I>Onwards!</I>
<P>
<B>REFERENCES</B>
