<tr>
<td width=440>

<h2><Center>The UK High Level Wargaming Facility</h2>
G J Burrows  and P Wearing<BR>
Centre for Defence Analysis<BR>
Defence Evaluation and Research Agency<BR>
DERA Portsdown, Cosham, Hants  PO6 4AA, UK<BR>

Paper for presentation at the NATO Defence Research Group 36th Seminar<BR>
IDA, Alexandria, Virginia, USA,  on 6 September 1995.<BR>

(c) British Crown Copyright 1995/DERA<BR>
Published with the permission of the Controller of Her Britannic Majesty's Stationery Office.</Center>

<BR>


<H4>1. 	Introduction</H4>

Changes in the world political scene, a requirement to reduce military spending and consequential changes in force structures are identified as major factors leading to a reduction in the number of major military exercises. The resultant problems appear to be particularly acute for Higher Level Commanders. Hence, it is necessary to review training requirements and the current and future facilities to meet these requirements. Two parallel research studies, sponsored by the Deputy Chief Scientist within the UK MOD, have been initiated to address: the training requirement of 4* Joint and 2/3* Joint Force Commanders; and the development/utility of High Level Wargaming of joint and combined operations in establishing operational and equipment concepts, training Higher Level Officers and the derivation, exercise and assessment of operational plans, concepts of operation and doctrine. This Paper provides an overview of the development and application of the UK High Level Wargaming Facility (HLWF) to meet the requirements for this latter study and it also provides an indication of future research required to support high level wargaming and Synthetic Environments (SE's).<P>

<h4>2.	Background</H4>
2.1 	A research area has been initiated by the UK Ministry of Defence to define more precisely those military functions or areas in which wargaming, at the higher level of command, could be best employed and the nature and size of gains to be obtained. The research study is sponsored by Deputy Chief Scientist with associate customers of  Director Joint Warfare (DJW), Directorate of Naval Staff Duties (DNSD), Director General Development and Doctrine (DGD&D) and the Director General Air Force Staff Duties (DGAFSD). The study is addressing the following key areas:<P>
a. Human Factor Aspects of Wargaming. This forms the major scientific focus within the study, and is divided into a number of main areas - investigation and analysis of the higher level wargaming process, execution and assessment; higher level decision making, performance influences and effectiveness of teams.<P>
b. Development of a Research Facility. Wargaming can provide the opportunity to study issues in a controlled, reproducible environment, if supported by an instrumented  facility. The High Level Wargaming Facility  is being developed to :<P>
-  Support the seminar method of wargaming and Mission Rehearsal for higher command (4*) and their support staff.<P>
- Allow the research programme to determine more accurately the requirements for Higher Command Wargaming.<P>
-  Assess the utility of wargaming in both joint and combined operations.<P>
- Assess the impact of operational effectiveness on higher command and control training.<P>
c. Interoperability. This part of the study is designed to demonstrate tri service and combined capabilities and interoperability with our allies.<P>

<h4>3	Development/ Utility of the High Level Wargaming Facility</H4>
3.1	Overview of The UK High Level Wargaming Facility - Figure 1<P>
	The High Level Wargaming Facility  is being developed within the Centre for Defence Analysis of the Defence Evaluation and Research Agency at Portsdown, UK. An initial set of requirements for the High Level Wargaming Facility have been determined and the following approaches have now been adopted to meet these requirements:<P>
3.2	Approaches to Meet HLWF Requirements - Figure 2<P>
3.2.1	The UK HLWF primarily comprises two elements:<P>
A Wargame Design and Planning Tool<P>
-	A computer IT system for the rapid design and evaluation of wargames.<P>
A Wargame Information System<P>
-	Developed on Sun SPARCStations in C++ code according to the principles of object orientated programming. <P>
-	Encyclopaedic/Geographic databases. Global geographic data is available from an augmented and rendered version of the commercially available Digital Chart of the World. A major encyclopaedic database provides the game designers and players with platform, sensor and weapon data. To aid the game designer in Wargame scenario generation, the encyclopaedic database includes information on nations orders of battle, political data, religious data and social data. The database is being trial populated as part of a UK/USA collaborative agreement.<P>
-	User-friendly Graphical User Interface to provide human interaction with the system through a graphical interface built with Xview routines.<P>
-	Message handling facility which incorporates a full audit trail.<P>
-	Integrated maritime, land and air simulations are planned to be included which will provide comprehensive modelling of platform behaviour and the incorporation of models of the lower level command decision making process in order to reduce the number of human operators necessary for game play.<P>
-	Networked using the Aggregate Level Simulation Protocol (ALSP). The  provision of a flexible, multi-warfare capability can be obtained by linking the HLWF to other detailed simulations in the land, air and other warfare areas using ALSP.<P>
3.2.2	The HLWF is being built to a Quality Plan (based on BS 5750/ISO9000), is under configuration control and is subject to a defined and phased Validation and Verification approach.<P>
3.2.3	Figures 3 and 4 show a number of windows of the HLWF which illustrate the type and format of information which can be made available during the wargame design and execution process or in the Military Crisis Management process<P>
3.3	Wargame Training/Simulation Hierarchy - Figure 5<P>
3.3.1	Distributed Interactive Simulation (DIS), the Aggregate Level Simulation (ALSP) and the supporting technologies now provide a capability for simulations to be linked to provide platform/weapon system evaluation, training and wargaming facilities from the strategic to the operator level and to accurately represent the human dimension in warfare.	<P>
3.3.2	The provision of a powerful, flexible Tri-Service facility can be obtained by networking the core of the UK HLWF to other detailed maritime, air and land simulations/wargames via the ALSP protocol, as illustrated in Figure 5. These simulations/wargames can be part of a UK confederation or networked to USA or NATO/European confederations They can comprise live, constructive or virtual elements and operate at the strategic, operational or detailed tactical level. In practice, it is considered that only two different levels of command are likely to be exercised or trained simultaneously. However, this approach provides flexibility and the ability to train sequentially different command levels to a common basis.<P>
<h4>3.4	Collaborative Programmes - Figure 6</H4>
	In order to investigate and demonstrate the advantages and technical requirements of networking the UK HLWF to simulations and wargames at different levels of command and across different warfare areas, three collaborative programmes have been initiated.<P>
3.4.1	Internal DRA Interoperability Programme<P>
	This programme involves the DERA sites at Portsdown, Fort Halstead and Malvern in the UK and will network the HLWF to a research version of ABACUS (a training simulation which is being procured for the UK army) and an air simulation called the Total System Model.<P>
3.4.2	UK/USA Collaborative Programme<P>
3.4.2.1	A UK/USA Memorandum of Agreement, the High Level Simulation Protocol (HLSP), has been initiated. This MOA involves DERA Portsdown, the USA Naval Command, Control and Ocean Surveillance Centre  at San Diego and the USA Naval War College at Newport. The MOA provides the umbrella for two networking experiments (the first experiment was undertaken in May 1995 and the second experiment is scheduled for 1996), the phased evaluation of the UK HLWF and the population/maintenance of encyclopaedic databases.<P>
3.4.2.2	Objectives of the DRA/NRAD HLSP Collaborative Programme<P>
	a. The specific objectives of the DRA/NRAD HLSP Collaborative Programme are:<P>
-	To investigate the use and application of ALSP for networking heterogeneous wargaming simulations.<P>
-	To establish ALSP confederation/s for networking USA and UK wargaming simulations.<P>
-	To demonstrate the technology for conducting Tri-Service strategic and tactical wargames at a classified level.<P>
-	To investigate sharing of UK and USA resources to populate/maintain the HLWF database.<P>
3.4.2.3	The UK/USA Phase I  Experiment, May 1995 <P>
	a. A schematic of the UK/USA HLSP Interoperability Experiment that was conducted is shown in Figure 7. The experiment consisted of linking the HLWF to NRAD's Research Evaluation and Systems Analysis (RESA) maritime simulation via ALSP and using RESA's Message Generator to network to a UK Aircraft Carrier via JOTS terminals. A Video conferencing facility was also set up between the UK Aircraft Carrier and the wargaming centre at DERA Portsdown to investigate how the Military Crisis Management process could be conducted using this networked facility.<P>
b. The experiment consisted of demonstrating how the Military Crisis Management process could be conducted, monitored and controlled using information supplied from  a system such as the HLWF. The Military Crisis Management process and the role of a system such as the HLWF is shown in Figure 8. In conducting the Military Estimation process, information from the HLWF could be supplied on Aims and Factors to assist the high level commander and his team in determining Considerations and arriving at a Command Decision. Lower Level Models, Planning and Analysis Tools and What-If Capabilities networked to the HLWF can also a provide detailed information to assist in this task. Military plans can then be developed with this information and disseminated to other HQ's, Command Centres, Platforms or Wargaming Centres and then interactively monitored or controlled by these Centres and Platforms during the operation.<P>
	<P>
3.4.2.4	The UK/USA HLSP Interoperability Experiment, 1996 - Figure 9<P>
	a. A more ambitious experiment is scheduled under the HLSP collaborative programme for 1996. The HLWF will be networked via ALSP  to the USA Marine Tactical Warfare Simulation (MTWS). It is proposed also to link the HLWF to a confederation of other UK simulations/wargames (ABACUS and TSM) and to other live/constructive elements of  Trainers/Simulators and to the Operational Centre at Northwood.<P>
	<P>
3.4.3	The UK/NATO CAX Collaborative Programme<P>
3.4.3.1	The requirement for computer support for exercises by NATO forces was highlighted for the first time during the ACE 89 exercises which demonstrated the advantages of exercises in a simulated dynamic and interactive environment. ACE 89 exercise also showed the need for the capability to link simulations to the Command and Control Information System, to enable staffs to work in their command posts with their usual tools. SHAPE initiated the Computer Assisted Exercise (CAX) project in 1991 at the STC which was asked to prepare computer assisted exercises and to specify the tools to meet CAX requirements for the Allied Command Europe as described in the Military Requirement for CAX.<P>
3.4.3.2	To enable the currently available simulation models to be used to meet the CAX requirement, SHAPE has initiated a Multinational Working Group and has initiated a Multi-National Test Bed (MNTB) of operational environment simulations to study existing simulation models and how far they complement each other, to identify necessary developments and to suggest an approach to support model interoperability. The DRA at Portsdown is playing an active role in the development of the MNTB. The UK HLWF has been chosen as the maritime component of the MNTB.<P>
3.4.3.3	Figure 10 shows the confederation of simulations forming the MNTB. The UK HLWF  interfaces with the Joint Theatre Level Simulation JTLS model (Supply), MOVESIM (operational movement of forces), KORA (which simulates the direct and indirect fire of troops, helicopters and air defence) and KIBOWI (a battalion/brigade level training wargame).<P>
3.4.3.4	The High Level Wargaming Facility has been successfully integrated into the Multi National confederation of five models/simulations to form the Multi National Test Bed for NATO CAX at the SHAPE Technical Centre. The first Multi National Test Bed Experiment (MNTBEX 95/1) was held over the period 22 May 1995 to 1 June 1995. This demonstrated the potential of a coalition of models to provide cost-effective computer support to multi-national exercises for NATO CAX.<P>
<h4>3.5	Supporting Strategic Research</H4>

3.5.1	Specific strategic research programmes have now been initiated by the UK MOD which provide support to the development of the HLWF. In 1994 a strategic research  study was initiated to identify and solve the challenging technical issues associated with synthetic environments and networking real time man-in-the-loop simulations. The  programme was structured initially to provide the infrastructure for and to open up UK research into Advanced Interactive Simulation (ADINTSIM). This was achieved by creating a research network across the main DRA sites as a test bed for investigation and demonstration of ADINTSIM techniques, and identification of those areas requiring priority research under the programme.<P>

3.5.2 	The following five priority items of research, illustrated in Figure 11, are now being pursued under this programme: <P>

- Parallel Multi-Agent AI Simulation. To investigate and develop an integrated intelligent object orientated simulation environment capability with high performance parallel machines.<P>

- Future Networking Technology. To investigate and develop future networking and networking technology requirements for distributed simulation in the UK.<P>

- Aggregation/Disaggregation of Simulation Entities. To develop AI techniques for aggregation and disaggregation, building from advanced entity-level rule bases.<P>

- Database Correlation. To investigate and develop novel methods of manipulating photograph source data to ensure that captured cultural information is correlated with standard source databases.<P>

- Verification, Validation and Accreditation of Networked Simulations. To investigate the advanced specification of remote access simulator interfaces, in order to; improve the verification, validation and accreditation procedures for DIS systems, and to provide multi-level access interfaces which address the issue of aggregation within DIS systems.<P>
<h4>4	Advanced Interactive Simulation</H4>
	<P>
4.1	Research in the Short, Medium and Long Term<P>

Wargaming for the Higher Command has many potential uses. It can be used as a campaign planner, as a training aid, to exercise plans, concepts and doctrine and to exercise command and control decision making. Further research is planned using the HLWF to determine the applicability and cost effectiveness of wargaming. The following areas of research have been identified by UK military customers as being important and will be addressed over the next few years:<P>

4.1.1.	 Research in the Short Term<P>

- Determine the effectiveness of military decision making<P>

- Determine the role of IT for High Level Wargaming<P>

- Development of a high level integrated land component<P>

- Development of an integrated  high level logistic model<P>

- Investigate the automation of  wargame design<P>

4.1.2.	Research in the Medium Term<P>

- Model and investigate the high level decision making process<P>

- Determine the effectiveness of command team members individually and as a team<P>

- Model casualties, deaths, battle damage and NBC<P>

- Investigate human performance degradation<P>

- Interoperability studies<P>

4.1.3	Research in the Long Term<P>

- Development of the HLWF to support campaign studies<P>

- Cost analysis and quantification.<P>

4.1.4.	Additional Areas of Research<P>

	a. To investigate the fidelity required in simulations/wargames for:<P>

	- Training<P>
	<P>
	- Mission rehearsal<P>

b. To investigate the requirements and feasibility of dynamically linking existing or planned tactical decision supports and aids to the core of the HLWF.<P>
4.1	Research in the Short, Medium and Long Term 4.1	Research in the Short, Medium and Long Term 4.1	Research in the Short, Medium and Long Term 6	Research in the Short, Medium and Long Term<P>


<h4>5.1  Conclusions</H4>

5.1.1	An initial prototype of a High Level Wargaming Facility has been developed which currently consists of:<P>

- A Wargame Design and Planning Tool<P>

- A Wargame Information System<P>

5.1.2	The prototype High Level Wargaming Facility is now being used to quantify and assess the process of  high level wargaming. There are also implications from the work being undertaken  for the quantification and assessment of the wargaming process at the operational and tactical levels. <P>

5.1.3	The following areas of research are now being addressed with the HLWF:<P>

- Applicability and cost effectiveness of wargaming.<P>

- Investigating the effectiveness of the military decision making process.<P>

- Investigation of synthetic environments, networked simulations/facilities and protocols to achieve a cost effective high level wargaming process..<P>
NATO UNCLASSIFIED	<P>


