<td width=440>

<h2><center>The Information Warfare Challenges of a National Information Infrastructure</H2>

by Ronald Knecht  and  Ronald A. Gove, Ph.D.<BR
Science Applications International Corporation<BR></Center>

<BR>
The phenomenal growth of the Internet is redefining our very notion of privacy and property. The Internet has created a demand for instantaneous information exchange in the military, government, and private sectors that is without precedent. Information networks and computers that are connected to the Internet are routinely processing private, proprietary, sensitive, classified,and critical military and business information. Our economic base and our military effectiveness are more dependent on automated information systems than any country in the world.  However, the very technology that created this dependence is its greatest weakness: the infrastructure is fundamentally insecure to attacks from individuals, groups or nation-states which can easily deny service or compromise the integrity of information.<P>

In this paper we discuss the elements of a coherent strategy that will support the goal of creating a robust,  interoperable, and cost effective information infrastructure.  Given that it is not possible to control the state of the globally interconnected information infrastructure, we must determine how to design information services that can operate safely in this inherently unsafe environment. This infrastructure must include built-in resiliency for information and resource protection. The problem is incredibly complex and will require fundamental changes in the approach to designing and operating an infrastructure.  Each subsystem, component, protocol, and software application must be designed knowing that they will be operated in a malicious environment. Network managers must be equipped  to know the status of the infrastructure on a global basis and be able to detect attacks or system failures.  They must be prepared to react effectively and efficiently when a problem does occur to diagnose,  control, and recover capability.<P>

In the following paragraphs we address a number of challenge areas that are known to be fundamental to improved NII/DII security  and will  suggest strategies, legislation, or other mechanisms for balancing the three legs of the NII/DII INFOSEC equation: protect, detect, react. <P>

The critical issue areas are:<P>

<UL>
<LI>- Fragmentation of Responsibility<BR>
<LI>- Technology<BR>
<LI>- Architectural Framework<BR>
<LI>- People<BR>
<LI>- Facilities<BR>
<LI>- Data Bases<BR>
<LI>- Network Control<BR>
<LI>- Threat and Risk<BR>
<LI>- Security in a Global Infrastructure<BR>
</UL>
<BR>
Our discussions are not intended to provide final answers, but rather to get the community thinking about these issues.<P>

Fragmentation of Responsibility It is critical that the U.S. develop an integrated, assured, end-to-end information transfer capability that can be managed through centralized technical control processes and mechanisms.<P>

"During World War II everyone knew that it was the Navy's job to protect oil tankers from marauding U-boats," stated Bob Ayers, chief of the Information Warfare division at the Defense Information Systems Agency (DISA).  A similar clear assignment of responsibility for protecting the transport of information across a global telecommunications networks does not exist.<P>

The American military is the most information dependent in the world. Computers support everything from the design of weapons to pay and health care.  We would have much less of a challenge if this computer processing and telecommunications were conducted over private military networks.  But that just isn't reality; about 95% of the military's communications are carried over the public switched networks (PSN).  These same networks are shared by individual users, universities, various governmental entities, and private corporations, world-wide.  The networks are spread across many states, countries, principalities and are subject to a multitude of laws and regulations under a variety of jurisdictional authorities.  <P>

The already complex mix of stakeholders interested in the rapid access to information and near instantaneous communication is now undergoing explosive growth fueled by the world wide web or WWW.  Most major corporations are establishing WWW "home pages" for informational and advertising purposes.  Some are beginning to consider using the Internet as a medium for electronic commerce.  Microsoft and Visa have announced a joint effort to develop standards for Secure Transaction Technology to enable electronic commerce in a user friendly way while maintaining the privacy and protection of account numbers that consumers have come to expect in conventional credit transactions.  A major disruption in the PSN would also have a crippling effect on the nation's business and financial industries.  Who, then, is responsible for protecting the information in these computers and networks?<P>

Responsibility for security today tends to be assigned as a function of the classification of the information rather than the utility value of the information.  An example is the provision of P.L. 100-235 that requires security plans for Federal systems containing sensitive information, yet exempts those systems containing classified information.  Domains of authority must be clearly delineated so that when an attack occurs the appropriate agents may react.<P>

A "Big Brother" approach that places all of a nation's telecommunications under a single government jurisdiction -- even in the event of war-is probably impossible.  Most networks were built to service commercial users and private industry will object to intrusions by the government.  Consider the controversy raise by the introduction of the Clipper Chip and key escrow. Civil libertarians and conspiracy theorists would make common cause in resisting dominant government control of the telecommunications infrastructure.  The recent mood in the Congress to reduce government regulation will further inhibit the government's ability to provide centralized network control.  Regardless,  it is critical to the future security of the U.S. that we find a way manage this problem.  It must be possible to determine if an "event" involving the nation's networks is the result of an accident, is a criminal attack, is an isolated terrorist incident, or is an act of war.  The damage from an event may be the same but if the intent behind the event is malicious then the responsibility for response to the event falls under a different jurisdiction that is a function of the intent-crime, terrorist or war. If we are unable to react promptly until the jurisdiction is established, it may be too late to react appropriately.<P>

Technology:  In spite of years of discussion about the need for security in computer systems and networks, most systems continue to be designed without needed security features.  The military continues to defer the security requirements in favor of other operational needs when budgets and schedules are tight.  Even where security is being included, the current process of development and security evaluation causes systems to be obsolete by the time they are fielded. This must change.  We must change the very premise on which systems and infrastructure are designed and acquired. The time between generations of computing technology has dropped from five years to eighteen months and is now approaching one year.  Clearly, to acquire military systems over a 5 to 10 year acquisition cycle is inconsistent with today's needs. Also, the DoD has imposed an ill-defined certification process for security products that lags far behind the technology life cycle resulting in the fielding of obsolete security technology that is incompatible with rapid technology refreshment.<P>

In addition to separating the acquisition of data, applications and the underlying computing and communications technology so that each is acquired on an appropriate cycle-as contrasted to the failed grand design systems acquisition approach-a design approach is needed that is appropriate to the continued injection of security technology into existing and developmental information environments. This design approach should explicitly address the security design practices for the protection on information environments, the detection of malicious action, and the capability to react to such actions.<P>

This must be contrasted to past practices focused on the protection of confidentiality where, in spite of over ten years of publicity regarding the need for secure computer systems, we have failed to train designers to consider security as a fundamental feature of an operating system or computer application, nor have we trained acquisition managers to insist upon secure computers and application software; when cost and schedule become an issue, security is the first thing dropped. <P>

Architectural Framework:  The Information Infrastructure Task Force (IITF) Technology Policy Working Group, supported by the National Institute of Standards and Technology is examining an  Architectural Framework for National Information Infrastructure Services and Standards that will lead to an open systems environment.  However, the focus on security in this initiative is primarily driven by privacy concerns.  The implications of malicious or hostile action taken against the elements the NII is not given suitable attention.  <P>

Likewise, the Office of Management and Budget has published five draft Security Tenets [Federal Register/ Vol 60. No. 28/ Friday February 10, 1995] that the NII should provide the people who use it:<P>

(1)  The ability to control who see (or cannot see) their information and under what  terms;<BR>
(2)  The ability to know who they are communicating with and that information received comes from who it says it is from;<BR>
(3)  The ability to know that information stored or transmitted is unaltered;<BR>
(4)  The ability to know when information and communication services will (or
will not be) available; and<BR>
(5)  The ability to block unwanted information or intrusion<BR>
<BR>
These are very worthwhile tenets and address the issues of integrity, confidentiality and availability but still do not get at the issues of malicious attack on the NII.<P>

Further, if you examine OMB's report  "NII Security: The Federal Role", of June 5, 1995, prepared by the National Information Infrastructure Security Issues Forum, you will find that it does not address the need for a national information strategy on how to assure national security and network protection. The section of the report titled "Privacy and Security" is concerned almost exclusively with privacy. There is no discussion of the potential threats to national security from disruption, corruption or compromise of the NII by actual or potential enemies of the United States.<P>

People:  Ultimately, many problems are the result of authorized individuals roaming and browsing in computers and computer files outside of their specific responsibilities.  In the business world, the majority of crimes are committed by authorized users acting outside of their authorized duties.  We know that we are not going to change human nature. There will always be persons acting in ways that are contrary to societal norms.  It is possible, however to be aware of such behavior and to design systems and procedures that mandate accountability.<P>

The techniques for protecting systems against insider threats are well-known and do not need repeating.  Training and awareness, strong identification and authentication, meaningful audit collection and reduction.  Clearly we must focus resources on the passive and continuous identification and authentication of the users of information systems, auditing of users activities at both the technical telecomputing and application (work flow) levels (including audit reduction), and the design of personnel security programs for information workers.<P>

Facilities:  We must not neglect the physical plant that houses our information systems.  Computers will not run without electricity and water for large air conditioning systems.  Critical data must be backed up regularly, stored in locations that will not share common disasters.  In addition, means for distributed computing that is inherently protected from local perturbations should be developed.  <P>

Data Bases:  Data base research and design requirements should be explored including such topics as how the integrity state of stored data can be known even if not being used to support active transactions and design features for the rapid replication of data bases while under attack as a strategy to preclude single point failures.<P>

Network Control:  In an integrated information infrastructure, a coordinated network control capacity is required to integrate the communications control function and the data control function. This coordinated control requires the visibility of infrastructure operations from keyboard to keyboard.  The issues are still: protect, detect, react. We must be able to detect the signs of an attack early and to be able to distinguish attacks from other forms of failure or perturbation.  We must be able to determine the nature and extent of that attack (isolated incident or global attack). The overall Defense Information Infrastructure needs to be monitored by an external security control center.  This center will have primary responsibility of defensive information warfare and will have a robust computing and communications capability. It must be able to diagnose problems, conduct triage actions to limit proliferating attacks or cascading failure modes,  and manage the restoration of operations without being dependent on the damaged network for this activity. Recall the Morris worm incident, where systems were taken off the Internet, thus shutting off the primary means of communication between system operators, who were so dependent on the Internet as a communications medium that they often were unaware of each other's telephone numbers.  <P>

Threat and Risk:  We must rethink our approach to relating threat and risk. Our past approaches have been confused and of limited effectiveness.  In themilitary and government environment it has been the case that "threat" was paramount.  One always needed to have a well defined threat in order to provide a justification for protective measures.  It was considered prudent to purchase countermeasures in proportion to the clearly defined threat in order to avoid spending more than the risk would warrant.   The commercial world tended to be checklist oriented.  Various standard practices and procedures had evolved over time and businesses were expected to follows these practices. These common business practices have not kept up with the growth and dynamics of computer technology.<P>

The technical capacity and cost to attack an information system is now so insignificant in proportion to the value of the information that we must assume the threat is real.  Under the right motive or circumstance every network can be attacked.  In order to conserve our critical resources, we must balance protection with the value of the information.  We need to develop design metrics that relate a specified degree of protection to cost.  A normalized means of addressing the incremental cost of various information security  technologies and design features in relation to the anticipated risk is needed for informed design decisions.<P>

Security in a Global Infrastructure:  The DII is not simply part of a defense infrastructure.  It is rather part of a global information network whose interconnections are beyond visualization and understanding.  We must develop capabilities that will enable the protection of information enclaves within this global environment. The tension between protection and openness and balance between economy and effectiveness must be carefully addressed.  <P>

Economic pressures will force private industry to develop strategies for dealing with security and privacy in electronic commerce.  Visa and Microsoft have recently announced that they have established a joint venture to establish standards for electronic commerce in their Secure Transaction Technology.  Microsoft and other software developers are including C2 (Trusted Computer System Evaluation Criteria rating) features in their standard product line (e.g. Windows NT and Novell). However, even commercial giants like Microsoft are not likely to develop the global protective and reactionary mechanisms needed to protect the networks from concentrated attack.  This will have to come from government efforts.<P>

What should we do?<P>

Private industry will need to work cooperatively with the Federal government to provide the required levels of protection.  We likely will need to evolve toward enclaves or domains of systems whose levels of protection will vary according to the utility of the information in commerce or warfare.  Related to this will be the need to develop processes and metrics so that developers of the DII/NII can demonstrate the cost basis for the resulting trade-offs.  <P>

The key to protecting the nation's information infrastructure is to provide the ability to:<P>
<UL>
<LI>- Protect the system from attack<BR>
<LI>- Detect an event when it is occurring and be able to decide if it is an
attack, a failure mode, or an isolated hacker<BR>
<LI>- React to the event in a way that minimizes the impact and restores and maintains capability.<BR>
</UL>

<U>Protect! Detect! React!</U>  To achieve this we begin with a systematic examination of information security research and design criteria at the architectural level.  We must find <P>

1. A means to know the current state of an information system environment at the technical computing level, the telecommunications level, and the application level.<P>
2. A criteria to recognize when the current state of the environment is perturbed in order to provide for automated diagnostics and warning.<P>
3. Features at the technical and application levels that will enable the ready restoration of a perturbed environment to a known desired state.<P>
4. Basic protection features that will limit well-known and low cost attacks in an information environment<P>
5. Network features that will automatically limit proliferating attacks or cascading failure modes.<P>

Most importantly, we who have the good fortune of having a technical background that enables us to have some informed insights into this very complex challenge have a  responsibility to educate the general public on the importance of this issue.   We must foster a climate of reason so that we can reach agreement on acceptable means to conduct status monitoring of the NII in such a way that it will allow industry and government to detect and to react to attacks on the United States through cyberspace without creating an electronic police state that inappropriately monitors the information transactions of individuals and businesses. <P>

Conclusions.  In this paper we have considered some of the problems facing the future of information infrastructure.  The threat is very real.  The ability to cause a catastrophic breakdown of our information and telecommunications infrastructure exists and is not technically challenging.  A computer and a modem is all that is needed.  In the past, it required the resources of a nation to wage war.  Today anyone with a thousand dollars worth of equipment and a modicum of technical understanding can bring down the house.<P>

<h4>About The Authors:</h4>

<I>Ronald J. Knecht, Vice President.<P>
Ron Knecht currently supports ongoing Joint Staff and DISA  information warfare (IW) initiatives and has worked in IW-related  activities for over three decades. While serving as the Special  Assistant to the Assistant Secretary of Defense for Command, Control, Communications, and Intelligence; Office of the Secretary of Defense; Pentagon, Washington, DC he played a central role in the establishment of the DoD IW program, including developing and obtaining approval in December 1992 of DoD Directive TS3600.1, Information Warfare (U) and program oversight.  Prior to joining OSD Mr. Knecht served over 29 years in the United States Air Force.  His IW-related assignments included program manager for the acquisition of the strategic command and control system used to provide planning and decision support involving<P>
compartmented capabilities for the Secretary of Defense, CJCS and CINCs; a six year assignment as the senior Joint Staff representative to the JCS Joint Special Studies Group at Ft. Meade, MD where many IW-related concepts were developed; and the development and fielding of related compartmented capabilities while assigned to Headquarters Air Force<P>

Ronald A. Gove, Ph.D., Vice President<P>

Dr. Gove joined SAIC in 1994 to assist in the development and management of an information systems security organization. He currently is the operations manager for the INFOSEC Operation.  Dr. Gove has a more than 25 years experience in systems security.  From 1984 to 1994 he led an information systems security business at a major international  consulting firm.  He was responsible for providing technical guidance and oversight in all areas of information systems security including system accreditation and certification, risk assessment, security test and evaluation, and security training and awareness. Dr. Gove has developed formal mathematical security policy models and developed and presented a one day seminar on this subject.<P></I>

Ronald A. Gove, Vice President<BR>
SAIC MS E-12-4<BR>
8301 Greensboro Drive, McLean,Virginia 22102<BR>
703 734 5915<BR>



