<td width=440>


<H2><Center>
Export Control As a Proactive Defensive 
Information Warfare Mechanism</H2>
by 
Winn Schwaratau</Center><BR>



<P>Information Warfare in both a commercial or military model is generally categorized as either offensive or defensive, but one can argue for the inclusion of a third category, Proactive Defensive Information Warfare (PDIW),  which contains characteristics of the former two. </P>

<P>Offensive Information Warfare would consist of specifically offensive actions to deactivate opposition infrastructure, ability to communicate, ability to collect, transmit  or use information.  It well might involve the use of passive data collection (insidiousness) through any available means, or the use of mis/dis-information, or any of a number of other approaches which are outline in "Information Warfare: Chaos on the Electronic Superhighway."</P>

<P>Defensive information warfare would include countermeasures to defeat any offensive actions on the part of either a known or unknown adversary.  Hardening of missile silos against the secondary EMP effects of a nuclear attack certainly fits into this category: the defensive goal being to maintain availability of information system to permit an appropriate response.  On a smaller, less cataclysmic scale, the use of Tempest shielding to prevent remote eavesdropping of spurious information from information systems is certainly defensive in nature.  And so is the use of sophisticated encryption and key management techniques to keep data transmissions and storage media free from breaches of confidentiality and integrity threats. </P>

<P>Proactive Defensive Information Warfare techniques, though, do not cleanly fall into either mode, although a case could be made along either or both lines.   Such appears to bt the case when export control mechanisms such as ITAR and COCOM, are employed.  A compelling case can be made for this third category to be actively used to protect US military and commercial interests.  As we shall see, IW and PDIW are symmetrical, and similar techniques can be used against our own infrastructure by foreign information warriors.</P>

<P>ITAR and COCOM export restrictions are, at a high level, intended to keep so-called 'sensitive technology' out of the hands of certain, policy chosen, third parties.  (It is the not the intent of this paper to identify those individuals, groups or nation-states; these will change from time to time as geopolitical and econo-technical conditions evolve.  We will only refer to them for discussion's sake as Potential Adversaries.)  Nonetheless, the commercial sector has made consistent arguments over the last decade, and most notably since the end of the Cold War, that export restrictions have inherent points of failure, and thus our export policies should be altered to reflect new realities in a global market.</P>
<UL>
<LI>	Much of the US restricted technology is available anyway from foreign companies who may not adhere to US export controls and laws.  Therefore, why bother with export controls over such items.

<LI>	 History has shown that many restricted export technology regulations have been easily bypassed by less than scrupulous manufacturers and through multi-pathed distribution channels.

<LI> US Customs (and Customs of other countries) does not have the ability to perform 100% inspections, and often the technology is beyond their scope of expertise to make a determination upon.

<LI>	Some restricted export technology is only restricted in its final assembled form, thereby permitting legal export of subsystems and components, wherein the final 'export-restricted' product is assembled by the Potential Adversary.

<LI>	 US companies have argued that based upon the 'holes' in the export policy and enforcement, many export regulations are simply rendered ineffective.

<LI>	 Some US companies further argue that the loss to the US economy is import revenues and domestic employment is a greater threat than the export of the technology itself.</P></UL>

<P>This debate has gone on in various arenas for years, but as global availability of advanced fundamental technology proliferates, the efficacy of export restrictions has been further weakened.  </P>

<P>The most visible debate which has reached the front pages of the conventional media has been over the export control of encryption.  For example, Bruce Scheier's book, "Applied Cryptography" is fully able to be exported without restriction, even though it contains detailed source code listings of popular, unclassified encryption algorithms.  However, the exact same material, when copied onto electronic media such s floppy disk, has been denied an export license under current ITAR interpretation. </P>

<P>Detractors of the current export policy maintain that the policy does not inhibit the export of the 'restricted technology,' and indeed may call more attention to its particular value.  A similar failure can be observed with the export control of DES (Data Encryption Standard) under ITAR, even though DES has been a US public domain standard since 1976.  Today, despite attempts at export control, approximately 50% of the world's DES products are not made in the United States.  What further exacerbates US manufacturers, is not only the loss of international market share, but when a US company uses a non-US DES engine, he is free to import the raw components from countries such as Germany, Taiwan and Japan, but he is restricted from re-exporting them.  In some cases, this has caused manufacturing and re-assembly of these devices to be moved to non-US soil where export restrictions are more relaxed.</P>

<P>The emergence of the Internet further adds fuel to the argument that export controls are not effective. Phil Zimmermann wrote a software based encryption program called PGP (Pretty Good Privacy) which employs a public-key technology.  PGP was placed on a computer node connected to the Internet (by persons unknown) and thus is now a virtual standard for private electronic communications on the Internet.  As a result Zimmerman is facing possible prosecution by the Department of Justice for alleged export control violations.</P>

<P>The ostensible aim of cryptographic export control is to make the US intelligence community's job easier.  Given that the NSA is the electronic listening post as the interests of the US dictate, they understandably want to make their job as easy as possible.  Intercepting signals transmissions is only one part of their task.  The other is to make sense of them from a contents standpoint.  Thus, the more cryptographically encoded transmissions they encounter, the more time, money - resources- they must expend to fulfill their task.  It is completely within reason, from their perspective then, that they actively promote and lobby for adherence to ITAR in the area of cryptography.</P>

<P>This is clearly once area in which we have already seen the NSA proactive in what we might now call Proactive Defensive Information Warfare.  NSA wants to make their job easier not harder, so they expend efforts to encourage cryptographic export, but only under certain conditions.  </P>

<P>When a cryptographic engine is under export control review for either specific foreign customers or a general license, NSA acts a reviewing counsel to the Department of State and Commerce.  In some cases, the export is completely denied or permitted.  Intuitively, such decisions would likely be decided upon by the relative difficulty of decoding such encrypted messages, but the details of export permission/denial are not publicly available. In other cases, though, the NSA will confer with the manufacturer/designer who is attempting export, and ask that certain changes to the encryption engine be made.  </P>

<P>Some manufacturers allege that the changes instituted by the NSA are designed with two goals in mind, both of which neatly fit into the PDIW concept.</P>

<OL>
<LI>	NSA suggests changes to the algorithm and encryption engine to make their decryption of intercepted messages using that engine simpler.</P>

<LI>	 NSA suggests changes which 'label' the encrypted message with a 'flag' so that upon interception, they know which process to employ for rapid decryption.  </P>
</OL>
<P>This second approach is subtle, but reminiscent of other signals interception techniques.  No manufacturer has suggested that upon examination of the source code that the NSA triggered alterations actually place a header or tail on the transmission which say, "I am encryption technique XV367, use decryption process F618."  That is too obvious a trap which would not meet the subtler needs of the capable Information Warrior or serious adversary.</P>

<P>Rather, private crypto code analysts maintain, the NSA changes create a cryptographic 'signature' which becomes part of the message.  Marshall McCluen's "The medium is the message" prediction comes patently to life with such a tactic.  Once a signal is intercepted, and upon the discovery that the signal is somehow encoded. through the use of sophisticated real-time analysis tools, the code breakers determine which encryption algorithm was used in the encoding.  Then, if they so choose, they employ the inverse as a crypto-analytic attack upon the message. This can also be viewed as a sublte form of Steganography, the inclusion of a private communication within an open one, such that the casual observer cannot determine the meaning of the hidden information, or even that such information exists.</P>

<P>This approach makes total sense since NSA had spent extensive resources on electromagnetic eavesdropping techniques from keyboards, monitor screens and printers.  They prepared what is called Digram tables for a myriad of printers - each of which exhibits specific electromagnetic patterns upon analysis.  Thus, when US intelligence places a covert eavesdropping device into an opposition's IT equipment, based upon the device's known catelogued patterns, analysis of the actual signal contents becomes an exercise in computing horsepower. </P>

<P>This is an ideal example of PDIW.  Permit the export of 'restricted technology' but insure that within that exported commodity, a so-called 'back door' is in place which largely nullify much of its original purpose.  </P>

<P>But these 'secret' techniques are fairly 'open' and the NSA's real or perceived policies, are (rightly or wrongly) deemed for what their detractors claim them to be: thinly disguised attempts at restricting export of technology through fear and loathing and disinformation.  Therefore, the quality and inttegrity of exported US crypto products is increasingly viewed with suspicion by the majority of industrialized nations.  A secondary goal is thus achieved: imbue distrust into the approved export products which will diminish their use. I would suggest that a backlash effect can occur, where independant cryptographic efforts from other countries develop even hard to crack codes. Only the NSA knows for sure.</P>

<P>As a vehicle of PDIW, NSA control over cryptographic export restriction is like having Ronald McDonald pick the world's best hamburger.  However, from a strategic policy standpoint, it makes a lot of sense.  And so do other similar instances,</P>

<P>In the late 1960's. Poland wanted to purchase a new telephone system.  Obviously, AT&T with its latest generation of telephone switching equipment, as did others,  wanted to be the recipient of such a mega-dollar contract. However, the export of such technology was restricted to a Soviet bloc country.  A deal was reached, a critical part of which the Poles were ignorant.  The AT&T switch would receive export permission if certain alterations to the switching system were made.  Poland would never know the difference, since all apparent systemic functionality would be unimpaired.  </P>

<P>What was added to the Poland bound telephone switch was the equivalent of a remote controlled 'self destruct' switch.  The goal was simple, obvious and effective.   According to knowledgable sources within the NSA, AT&T made certain modifications to the system that would permit we, the good guys, to, at will, remotely access and subsequently shut down the telecommunications infrastructure that was controlled by this equipment.  The thinking was, "only hypothetically, mind you; you can't use my name" (said the NSA gal/guy) "that in case of a Soviet incursion into Western Europe - through Poland - we (the US/NATO) could shut down land based telecomm in a microsecond."</P>

<P>More recently, the US military used the media as an unwitting participant in an active mis/disinformation campaign  example.  Government representatives claimed that during the opening minutes of the Gulf War, we injected a hardware based computer virus into a printer destined for Iraq.   Because the virus was so smart, we (the Allies) were then able shut down Iraq's Windows 3.0 based air defense systems,  (US News and Report unknowingly bought into this story despite massive substantiation that the entire tale was in reality a replay of an April Fool's hoax originally printed in the computer industry magazine, InfoWorld.) </P>

<P>What really happened, though, is that the NSA built a special integrated circuit in their own silicon foundry at Fort Meade. Designed to duplicate the functions of a chip within a printer, it of course performed as expected, but it also contained special circuitry to broadcast a unique low-level electromagnetic signature which was detectable by intelligence satellites.  The purpose was to track the routing and identify the final destination of the printer.  This intelligence gave the Allies additional bombing target options of information processing centers.  </P>

<P>A similar approach has been taken with North Korea.  Although under severe ITAR and COCOM restriction, North Korea has been able to build a formidable military machine.  One of their main military processing centers is run by an old IBM series 370 mainframe with an old, presumably altered version of the company's operating system.  It is claimed that we have the means to deactivate that center through at least two back door channels in the event of heightened readiness or imminent  conflict.  </P>

<P>The IBM AS-400 series computers are also export restricted to North Korea, but the country has apparently been able to acquire up to a few hundred of them, allegedly from a distribution point in India.  These machines are directly tied to the offensive capabilities of that country, and thus of strategic value.  Specifically, a denial of service assault upon them would be a prime means to deactivate much of North Korea's military power.  </P>

<P>Certainly a very clean, non-lethal (and politically acceptable) method of launching a successfully denial of service attack against these machines is preferable to physical assaults.  Again, with the unwitting cooperation of the Indian government, ITAR export permits allowed the export of this advanced technology to India, from where (the planning assumed), the machines would soon find a anew home: North Korea.  </P>

<P>But these machines are different.  They have been 'chipped' with special NSA manufactured silicon devices, designed to fail upon command.  Either single or multiple silicon critical component which are presumably difficult to acquire and replace are carefully chosen as the chipping targets.  The exact details are likely classified, but the general technique uses a remote high frequency 'trigger' signal that the modified chip 'hears.'  Conceptually no more complex than a child's remote control device, the target chip fails, and thus causes a systemic denial of service event.  In the event of conflict, the US military obviously gains a significant advantage.</P>

<P>Let's then briefly consider how such similar PDIW mechanisms can present the US with both opportunity and risk.</P>

<P>From a military and national intelligence standpoint, these techniques meet a number of key criteria.</P>
<OL>
<LI>	 Conceptually simple.
<LI>	 Highly efficient.
<LI>	 Reasonably 'safe' (non-lethally speaking).
<LI>	 Insidious and extremely difficult to detect.
<LI>	 Highly targetable.
</OL>
<P>Such techniques will continue to be used more extensively in PDIW for the above reasons, but we now can ask ourselves, just how far beyond tthe domain of the military and conventional national security should we take this tact?  Third world countries do not have the resources to develop their own technology and must source it from first world technology nations, most of whom subscribe to ITAR or COCOM -like policies. </P>

<P>If listening devices, tracking devices, trap-door software, or self-destruct mechanisms are built into both critical and non-critical US manufactured export systems, (with or without the assistance of the original manufacturer for security reasons) at what point does the target Potential Adversary suspect that all US sourced equipment is so configured?  Will this approach cause a shift to purchase of non-US equipment because either the equipment is modified for PDIW, or merely because it is suspected that the equipment might be so altered?  And if so, what effect does this have on export revenues, domestic employment and strategic advantage?  </P>

<P>Alternatively, similar tactics can be used on greater quantities of US exports, to include non-critical export items so that even off-shore assembly of systems would be infected with any of a number of embedded weaknesses?  For example, if high speed line printers were outfitted with an electromagnetic detector to read the solenoid signatures as printing occurred, a similarly planted transmitter could send the printer output to a convenient listening post.  The Russians allegedly used this approach, (however with a more crude implementation) by so 'bugging' Moscow based US State Department teletype machines in the early 1980's.  Upon receipt of the signals, a digram analysis is performed for a real-time reading of the machine's output.</P>

<P>When one considers that the French put listening devices in first class seats of Air France airplanes as a part of their national economic intelligence program, we should consider what technologies are available to the US for similar intelligence gathering or denial of service capability.</P>

<P>On the risk side, the US private sector and government are potentially vulnerable to similar strategies.  Much of the technology used in both commercial and classified systems are sourced from the Far East, even though integration and deployment are domestic.  Low level, silicon implementations of common functionality are bought on price: they are commodity items. But what happens when an insidiously designed piece of hardware or software, destined for a critical system (private or government) is remotely triggered to fail? Or if the MTBF is built right in as a form or Denial of Service through pre-planned pbsolescence? Woth a second or two of condsideration.</P>

<P>The symmetrical nature of export controlled PDIW becomes apparent, when we become the potential victim. Commercially available keyboards have been found with pre-programmed silicon chips that insert nasty messages into word processors. Funny? Maybe not so funny in many applications.</P>

<P>The risks are becoming more defined as our reliance upon technology increases daily. The risks to 'our side' also increase if our trading partners fear that we may use such techniques as a form of PDIW. There is no clean, simple solution that fits within 10 pages.</P>

<P>Thus, part and parcel of quality systems design and security considerations, should be an analysis of the defensive postures needed to thwart exported information technology products based PDIW assaults against the US.  The solutions to this conundrum are not simple, implying a greater expenditure of resources to develop identification methods, and then expending the time to perform thorough inspections.</P>

<P>Since such export controlled PDIW techniques give us potential advantage as well as point our potential weaknesses, policy must be developed for export controls as they apply to PDIW, and policies must be developed which would provide additional protection to our domestic private and government infrastructures.</P>



<BR>

</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
