<tr>
<td width=440>


<H2><Center>Ethical Conundra of Information Warfare</H2>
by Winn Schwartau</Center>
<BR>

<p>At first blush it sounds so clean. </p>

<p>So non violent. So intangible. Then you get to thinking about it.</p>

<p>Information Warfare. </p>

<p>In the late 1980's, the military began to think about a new kind of warfare; on in which the American populace could be more supportive in whatever overt or covert actions were required. A new and better kind of warfare; more palatable for the dinner eating, news watching family of four. Vietnam era pictures on the six o'clock news graphically showed dead soldiers and children burning from napalm strikes which did not fit neatly with the desired American image of White Hat, Mom and Apple Pie. As a country, we are not comfortable with viewing ourselves as baby killers or unleashing mass destruction just for the hell of it.</p>
<p>The media has had a tremendous effect on how we view war, and with the advent of "anywhere, anytime" instant remote communications, our soldiers are no longer thousands of miles away, fighting for American national interests. Today, they fight in real time, in our living rooms, where not only we, but the entire world watches and judges our actions.</p>
<p>Consider the involvement of US troops in Somalia. Media broadcasts of horrendous conditions, fiefdom-like chaos and civilian tragedies created a swell of urging for America to do something to assist a helpless population. And so we landed on East African shores for a peace keeping mission. But oddly enough, the media beat us to the punch. Entrenched on the hot beachheads with their cameras and boom microphones, live broadcasts of arriving Marines filled the airwaves. And then we went to work, attempting to bring some sort of order to a country in dire straits.</p>
<p>But our exit from Somalia was as cathartic as our entry. Full color videos of Somalian rebels dragging a dead US soldier through the streets in effigy was too much for most Americans too stomach. Nearly instantly, support for US intervention waned and we pulled out.</p>
<p>Based upon conversations with, and getting to know hundreds of military folks over the last five years, I believe that a new breed of soldier, a post-World War II soldier is coming to the fore. We are being guided by military leaders who are charged with defending our country, but who are also keenly aware that we do indeed live in a new world. They thoroughly understand that the typical war fighting projection of power must be handled in ways that not only make military sense, but do not violate the political, social and ethical consciences of those who must support them. </p>
<p>Now this might sound like a George Bushism, but I believe that the US military genuinely wants to be a kinder and gentler fighting force. Inherently, we have attained what might be referred to as an enhanced consciousness. We have a fundamental desire to whip the bad guy's butt, but we want to do it honestly, quickly, efficiently and with a minimum of bloodshed. From what I have seen and learned as a civilian, every effort is being made to develop ways for America to fight a clean war.</p>
<p>The military has been developing an array of technologies which fit into the non-lethal category. Sticky-foam which when shot out of a hand held 'cannon,' binds the enemy in a spider web of inescapable gluey substances. Sonic cannons which incapacitate adversarial forces. Nerve shattering electromagnetic emanations which effectively paralyze the enemy's ability to function. </p>
<p>But none of the non-lethal methods have attracted as much attention as Information Warfare.</p>

<h4>                                          Info-War</h4>

<p>The definition I first proposed for Information Warfare back in 1993 was a conflict in which "information and information systems act as both the weapons and the targets." At that time the working military definitions of InfoWar were classified, but some versions were close to the one I offered. Today, the Pentagon's working definition of InfoWar has been expanded to include the concepts "deny, destroy or intercept adversary computer, network or communications, while protecting ones own."</p>
<p>The other criteria I have used when describing Information Warfare is the total absence of bombs, bullets or other conventional tools of physical destruction. Thinking in this focused manner, concentrating exclusively within the virtual domain, or fourth dimension of warfare, hones the process of problem solving and generates new paradigms of thought.</p>
<p>Within this model of (Pure) Information Warfare, many options become apparent that are no so readily available for conventional conflict. </p>
<p>Simply put, if we (or anyone else for that matter) flies a plane into the airspace of a sovereign state and drops a load of bombs, there is a reasonable chance that such an act would be considered an act of war. However, we must note that the US has not "officially" been at war with anyone since the end of World War II, which further complicates the process. (I say this with full recognition and respect for the soldiers and families who suffered during the last half century of conflict in undeclared 'wars.')</p>
<p>Consider that in the last decade or so, several international allegedly unprovoked "shoot-downs" did not trigger war: the Soviet downing of KAL 007; the American missiles that shot a civilian Iranian jet-liner; the recent Cuban fatal interception of Cesnas in the Caribbean. Then consider that in 1986, American warplanes ravaged through downtown Tripoli and we did not see a military response.</p>
<p>The bottom line we have come to accept, perhaps in too cavalier a fashion, is that we are King of the Hill militarily: we are the big kids on the block, and don't screw with us if you know what's good for you. Thus, one could argue, we have seen an increase in terrorist type state-side events from non-US interests. They can't beat us in a "fair" fight, so they resort to terrorism.</p>
<p>Now with the advent of Information Warfare as an increasingly viable option to conventional armed conflict, we should inwardly examine those issues which we must openly face, come to terms with, and if I had my say-so, clearly announce our policy and attentions about to the world.</p>
<p>Pure Information Warfare takes many forms, and I will concern myself with only Class II and Class III InfoWar as detailed in "Information Warfare: Chaos on the Electronic Superhighway." </p>
<p>             Offensive Capabilities</p>
<p>Forgetting about the defensive aspects for a moment, what do we have in our arsenal that would permit the US to wage InfoWar against an adversary, whether by the military or by other officially government sanctioned organizations? Briefly, they include:</p>
<UL>
<LI>Offensive software: viruses, Trojan horses, embedded exported systems or other malicious software.<BR>
<LI>Sniffing the communications of foreign (domestic) civilian and military networks and communications.<BR>
<LI>Tempest style eavesdropping upon electronic devices with characteristic emissions.<BR>
<LI>Chipping: hardware based embedded malicious software in <BR>
<LI>Directed energy weapons which disable or destroy electronic systems.<BR>
<LI>A full range of PsyOps capabilities.<BR>

</UL>

<p>Used in various combinations, deployed by a politically willing and ably armed force, these 'weapons' have the capability to potentially replace much of our military's conventional means of conflict? </p>
<p>But, should we use them, other than in times of 'war,' (ie, Gulf Conflict) or as an adjunct to conventional conflict? Can the weapons of Information Warfare stand alone as means of projection of force?</p>
<p>This is the ethical conundrum that we face today.</p>
<p>* * * * </p>
<p>Is it ethically correct for the US to defend its economic national security interests by resorting to those same tactics that are used against us? </p>
<p>It goes without saying that the United States is a highly visible and rich target for the theft of intellectual property from the private sector, and to a lesser degree from the military sector. We have the most sophisticated spying apparatus in the world. to the tune of nearly $30 billions per year, but to date the immense sscapabilities have been relegated to Cold War tactics and military protectionism.</p>
<p>Should we, restructure our 'eyes' and 'ears' to the industrial and economic treasures of our friends and adversaries alike, not with the prime intentions of military advantage, but global economic supremacy instead? We know full well that in less than two decades, unless radical steps are taken, the United States will become second or third in national global economic might. Should we not utilize the same tactics and techniques as our competition? </p>
<p>Or, do we find it ethically displeasing to "read other men's mail?" On the other hand, what choice do we have?</p>
<p>Is there a middle ground, perhaps? That while we may choose to listen to our competitors, we will do nothing overt to actively disrupt their operations? Or do we find ourselves in the position that must use clandestine and covert methods. Perhaps we should employ technical mercenaries, in no way officially affiliated with the US government, who will remotely, invisibly and deniably effect our will. </p>
<p>The capability is distinctly there. Some corporations are allegedly already engaged in such missions for their own behest; but, if caught, will the US prosecute those persons who are operating in the best interests of our country?</p>
<p>Ethical considerations, whose decisions, will set the American tone for generations to come. </p>
<p>Another option we face, which also creates and ethical dilemma, is whether we should use Export Control as Means of Proactive Defensive Information Warfare. </p>
<p>The US has the capability to export technology, ostensibly for the good of the buyer and the seller. However, using advanced software and hardware techniques, we can also export goods that can effectively be used as 'weapons' if indeed the need so arises. In the early 1970's, according to intelligence sources, when AT&amp;T sold a national telephone switch to Poland (then a Warsaw Pact country), they were asked to include 'bits and pieces' that would allow the United States to remotely shut down the country's communications infrastructure. The idea was that in the event of a Soviet land based incursion, we would slow down and perhaps thwart hostile activities. Similarly, it has been claimed by other sources, that we have developed similar capabilities against North Korean military computers.</p>
<p>The question becomes though, should we as a country exploit this capability by using 'infected' or malicious software, or by installing modified silicon chips whose payload can be activated by the US when deemed appropriate? In a world of global competition, and as military, national economic and civilian interests converge, how do we draw a line between those actions that should be taken, and those from which we should refrain?</p>

<h4>Collateral Damage</h4>

<p>I pose this situation for your consideration.</p>
<p>The United States is involved in an armed conflict with a recognized adversary, and we have the support of our significant allies and the majority of our population. CNN and the world's major news services have access similar to that in the Gulf War; ergo, we assume that cameras are on the shoulders of our military.</p>
<p>In order to achieve some very specific tactical goals, the field commanders are faced with a choice.</p>
<p>	1. They can pick a sophisticated smart bomb, which will almost assuredly strike the exact designated target, and will definitely kill 7 - 15 innocent civilians. </p>
<p>	2. They can choose to use a non-lethal weapon (of whatever sort - that's immaterial here) which will have the same tactical effect as #1 above. However, there will be no civilian deaths to record on video tape immediately. Instead, the planners project 100-200 collateral civilian deaths within two weeks, as a result of the non-lethal attack.</p>
<p>What do we do?</p>
<p>This is the crux of the ethical conundrum that we face, for the use of non-lethal weapons in no way means that deaths will not occur, either in the short term or the long term. Non-lethal refers to the immediate casualty count of the weapon's use, not it's downstream collateral effects.</p>
<p>Further complicating the issue is the fact that Information Warfare offers additional opportunities other than in strict conflict, war or not. The techniques and offensive capabilities of InfoWar weapons can be considered part of our arsenal for:</p>
<UL>
<LI>Operations Other Than War<BR>
<LI>Prelude to Conflict<BR>
<LI>Alternative to Conflict<BR>
<LI>Sanctions<BR>
<LI>Middle ground between diplomacy and war (conflict).<BR>

</UL>
<p>A couple of examples should suffice.</p>
<p>Country 'A' is misbehaving, and the international community agrees that steps must be taken to bring them into line. One of the options available is to deny them access to international communications and or financial commerce. Through the use of jamming, denial of service attacks or assorted other methods, Country 'A' is electronically isolated from the world. As a result, the internal economy suffers, and a range of social effects are seen and felt, perhaps including starvation, an inability to care for sick people, etc. </p>
<p>If the only other alternative is conventional conflict, is this an acceptable route for we and our allies to take? We have to then consider if the 'attacks' against Country 'A' are all done outside of their physical sovereignty, or are some waged from within their physical boundaries. Does this make a difference to our chosen policy? </p>
<p>Denial of Service attacks offer a great deal of power to the Information Warfare enabled nation-state. The targets for such attacks in today's integrated information society (given an appropriately vulnerable society) blur the lines between the military and civilian as the increased convergence occurs.</p>
<p>Therefore, is an InfoWar attack against a power plant which services a military target acceptable, if we know that the same power source is the life line to a civilian population as well? Or, is it politically and socially acceptable to avoid the headline grabbing visual carnage that a military strike might cause, preferring instead to permit invisible collateral damage (although perhaps deeper in long term fatality).</p>
<p>Military and political planners will have to come to terms with these fundamental issues as we move into the fourth dimension of war - Cyber or Pure Information Warfare - but we must also remain acutely aware of the ramifications of such actions.</p>
<p>Let us say that the US does initiate some sanctions based offensive denial of service assault against a target nation-state. Or, fraught with even more complexity, we launch and InfoWar offensive against a non-nation-state entity, whose physical location happens to lie within the physical boundaries of a nation-state.</p>
<p>Even though the United States is still unclear policy-wise what constitutes and Act of War against us, we must consider how the target will view such actions on our part. Perception is the name of the game; especially with a world-wide audience watching. Will the target react as though the US had in fact declared war? No military action notwithstanding? Will the target in turn react offensively against US interests using either conventional, unconventional or InfoWar weapons? And then what is our response.</p>
<p>This issue begs the question: Is Information Warfare a potential step which can lead to an escalation to military conflict which was meant to be avoided in the first place? Or does Information Warfare present merely ethical questions, since no country in their right mind would militarily assault us?</p>
<p>The definition of War in this new age of Global Networks, trans-national commerce, and increasing fuzziness of borders is arguable at best - and create an essential debate for the future of peace. At the core of any nation-state's view of war should be a National Information Policy which clearly delineates value, national security and the thresholds over which another nation-state must not cross. But in addition, such a Policy view must include options for dealing with renegades, terrorists, corporations or individuals who provoke the international community.</p>
<p>Many people maintain that an Act of War implicitly involved fatalities.</p>
<p>I no longer believe that to be the case, and thus the ethical conundrum of exactly what is an Act of War comes to the fore. What is a measured response? If the US is hit with a non-lethal or InfoWar weapon, how should we respond? Our options are wide open today, but will increase as our arsenals grow in sophistication and complexity.  Further, as third world nations get 'wired' to the Global Information Infrastructure, they too, will find a demonstrable vulnerability that they currently do not enjoy.</p>
<p>There are no immediate answers that are right or wrong, but the questions and conundra beget more questions and dilemmas as we look into the future of warfare. It is my sincere hope, that this type of thinking and pondering will allow us all, as a nation and as a planet, to evolve our thinking past bombs and bullets, past military superiority, and find a common strength and unity amongst ourselves.</p>
<p>The alternative is not pleasant.</p>
<p>For we find, each of us as we leap forward into the future, that our greatest assets are indeed, also our greatest vulnerability. The ethical balance that we choose to follow in the coming decades will define us a species.</p>
<p>Let's make the right choices.</p>


<BR>

</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
