<td width=440>



<H2><Center>
INFORMATION WAR - CYBERWAR - NETWAR</H2>George J. Stein<BR></Center>

<H4>INTRODUCTION</h4>
<P>In Arthur Waley's Three Ways of Thought in Ancient China, Chuang Tzu tells the story of a simple gardener who was shown a new tool which promised to change gardening.  He laughed scornfully and replied, "I used to be told by my teacher that where there are cunning contrivances there will be cunning performances, and where there are cunning performances there will be cunning hearts.  He in whose breast a cunning heart lies has blurred the pristine purity of his nature; he who has blurred the pristine purity of his nature has troubled the quiet of his soul, and with one who has troubled the quiet of his soul Tao will not dwell.  It is not that I do not know about this invention; but that I should be ashamed to use it."1 </P>

<P>Strategy, according to the Department of Defense, is the "art and science of developing and using political, economic, psychological, and military forces as necessary during peace and war, to afford the maximum support to policies, in order to increase the probabilities and favorable consequences of victory and to lessen the chances of defeat."2   For most of us it is obvious that the political and economic aspects of the national security policies of the United States are developed by the national political authorities, the President and the Congress, and, in dealing with foreign states or groups, executed by the Departments of State, Commerce, Agriculture, or whatever.  Policies for the development and use of military forces are, likewise, formulated by the national political authorities and conveyed to the armed forces through the Secretary of Defense.  Few people, however, have paid much attention to just how and by whom psychological forces are to be developed to support national policies and, more importantly, what are psychological forces, by whom will these forces be used, with what authority, and to what ends.  The development of new tools and technologies for communication, especially those based on computers and other aspects of information technology,  has created the potential for a new form of  psychological warfare to a degree only imagined in science-fiction: that is, "Information Warfare."  It may be that when we come to know the Tao of such an invention as Information Warfare, we should be ashamed to use it.   </P>

<P>The futurists Alvin and Heidi Toffler have argued in their recent book War and Anti-War that the United States armed forces need to develop a "systematic, capstone concept of military knowledge strategy" which would include clear doctrine and policy for how the armed forces will acquire, process, distribute, and project knowledge and information to serve national strategy.3  Quoting from the "Memorandum of Policy No.30" (6 May 1993) of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff, the Tofflers argue that the U.S. military is expanding the concept of Information War to include psychological operations aimed at influencing the "emotions, motives, objective reasoning, and ultimately the behavior" of others.  Such an expansion would mirror the evolution of traditional warfare in the direction of Information War as now foreseen by the armed forces.  It also mirrors the historical transformation of the means of generating wealth from land through natural resources and industrial infrastructure to knowledge and the manipulation of data and information as the new creators of wealth.  As "first wave" wars were fought over land and "second wave" wars were fought over physical resources and productive capacity, the emerging "third wave" wars will be for the access to and control of knowledge.   And, in the Tofflers construct, as the "combat form" in any society follows the "wealth-creation form" of that society, the wars of the future will be increasingly "Information Wars."</P>

<P>Currently, although Information Warfare is the hot topic in the strategy community, there is nothing remotely resembling formal military doctrine or official definitions of Information Warfare.  Common terms include information war, information-based warfare, command and control warfare, information operations, electronic warfare and, in Russian usage, sixth-generation warfare.  But, despite the tortured terminology and computer-nerd jargon involved, the idea of Information Warfare has not only captured the attention of military analysts, it also poses important policy questions.  Given the lack of authoritative definitions, Netwar and Cyberwar are emerging as key concepts in discussing Information War.  Originally these ideas seem to have come from the science fiction community as, for example, in the very thought-provoking future war suggested in Bruce Sterling's Islands in the Net.4  More recently, the concepts of Netwar and Cyberwar have been developed by John Arquilla and David Ronfeldt in their important essay "Cyberwar is Coming!"5  Their suggestions provide a thoughtful starting point for exploring the military and civil/military issues of Information War.</P>

<P>Netwar, according to Arquilla and Ronfeldt, is a "societal-level ideational conflict waged in part through internetted modes of communication."  Netwar is about ideas and epistemology, what is known and how it is known, and would be waged largely, but not entirely, through a society's communication systems.  Netwar, then, is most likely to be a nation-against-nation strategic level conflict and is the new form of psychological warfare.  The target of netwar is the human mind and, as such, represents an exponential increase in the opportunities for strategic psychological warfare.  One could argue that certain aspects of the Cold War had the characteristics of a dress-rehearsal for future netwar: Radio Free Europe, the Cominform, Agence France Presse, or the U.S. Information Agency.  But clearly, netwar may describe more than traditional state-to-state conflict: the mushrooming of non-state political actors such as Greenpeace and Amnesty International, through ideologically inspired movements such as survivalist militias or Islamic revivalists, all with easy access to world-wide computer networks for the exchange of information or the coordination of political pressure on a national or global basis, suggests that the "government" of a "nation-state" may not be the only parties among whom "war" is waged.</P>

<P>Cyberwar, on the other hand, is the application of the same electronic tools and techniques to military operations in the traditional sense.  Called command and control warfare or C2W by the armed forces, cyberwar uses the new opportunities for internetted communication to amplify the battlefield application of the more traditional war-fighting techniques of operations security, electronic warfare, psychological operations, deception, and physical destruction of enemy communications to achieve information dominance in the battle.  Cyberwar or C2W is not the key issue: netwar is.</P>

<P>At first glance, netwar may appear to be a computer-nerd word for good, old-fashioned propaganda.  It would be comforting to believe that the technology to manipulate propaganda has just improved a bit and the same "tried and true" methods (and limitations) still worked.  As the Tofflers suggest however, the recent Gulf War showed both Saddam Hussein and the Alliance were still mostly in the old school.  The war contained many elements of classic propaganda: atrocity accusations of bombed baby-milk factories and stolen baby incubators from Kuwaiti hospitals, inflated rhetoric and inflated stakes of the conflict with the future of the new world order and the mother of battles for the future of Islam in the balance; the classic "us or them" polarization in which "neutrality" or unenthusiastic support was decried. Only one element of traditional propaganda was absent: while Saddam Hussein became the new Hitler and President Bush was the "Great Satan," the Gulf War is unusual in that there was far less demonization or dehumanization of the opponent.  Perhaps the multicultural nature of the American-led alliance precluded turning the Iraqi army into something subhuman.  Indeed, there may have been a spark of netwar genius in treating the Islamic Iraqi soldiers as "brave men put into an impossible situation by a stupid leader."  No dishonor in surrendering then.  And, there may have been a glimpse of the netwar future when, thanks to the technologies available for cyberwar, it is rumored that Baghdad Radio signed on one morning with "The Star-Spangled Banner."</P>

<P>Traditional propaganda, however, was usually targeted via mass media to influence a mass audience.  One consequence of contemporary technologies is the potential for customized propaganda, or in the Toffler's lexicon "de-massified" propaganda.  Anyone who has received individually targeted advertising from a company specializing in "niche" marketing has had a momentary shudder upon realizing there are private companies who seem to know everything about our buying habits and tastes.  Contemporary data bases and the constantly expanding multiplicity of sources, media, and channels for the transmission of information have created the opportunity and target sets for custom-tailored or precision netwar attacks.  Computer bulletin boards, cellular telephones, video-cameras, fax machines -- all provide an entry point and dissemination network for customized assault by governmental, commercial, and private interests.  </P>

<P>A major new factor in Information War results directly from the world-wide infosphere of television and broadcast news.  Many people have begun to realize that governmental decisions are becoming increasingly reactive to a "fictive" universe created, among others, by CNN and its various international competitors.  This media-created universe is dubbed "fictive" rather than "fictional" because while what is shown may be "true," it is just not the whole, relevant, or contextual truth.  And, of course, the close etymological relationship between fictive and fictional suggests how easy it is to manipulate the message.  Nevertheless, this fictive universe becomes the politically relevant universe in societies in which the government or its military is supposed to "do something."  Somalia gets in the news and the United States gets into Somalia despite the reality of equally disastrous starvation, disorder, and rapine right next door in Sudan.  There were no reporters with "skylink" in Sudan as the government of Sudan issued no visas to CNNs reporters.  The potential for governments, parties in a civil war such as Bosnia, rebels in Chiapis, or even non-state interests like Greenpeace, to manipulate the multi-media, multi-source fictive universe to "wage societal-level ideational conflicts" via the Internet and the World Wide Web should be obvious.6 </P>

<P>Fictive or fictional operational environments, then, whether mass-targeted or niche-targeted, can be generated, transmitted, distributed, or broadcast by governments or all sorts of players through increasingly diversified networks.  The niche-manipulation potential available to states or private interests with access to the universe of internetted communications such as the networks over which business, commercial, or banking information are transmitted to suggest that Mexico is about to devalue the peso could easily provoke financial chaos.  The target state would not know what had happened until too late.7  Direct satellite broadcast to selected cable systems, analogous to central control of pay-per-view programs, again offers the potential for people in one province or region of a targeted state to discover that the maximum leader has decided to purge their clansmen from the army.  To put it in the jargon of the info-warriors, info-niche-attack in an increasingly multi-source fictive universe offers unlimited potential for stealthy and precision strike societal-level netwar .</P>

<h4>PICTURES WORTH A THOUSAND TANKS</h4>

<P>When the new, but already well understood, simulation technologies of the Tekwar and MTV  generation are added to the arsenal of netwar, a genuinely revolutionary transformation of propaganda and warfare becomes possible.  Traditional propaganda, as in World War Two, might have attempted to discredit an adversary's news media by showing, for example, that as the official German losses in the Battle of Britain were demonstrably false, all "news" from the German government was equally false.  The credibility of the opponent was the target and the strategic intention was to separate the government from the people.  </P>

<P>Today, the mastery of the techniques of combining live actors with computer-generated video graphics can easily create a "virtual" news conference, summit meeting, or perhaps even a battle which exists in "effects" though not in fact.  Stored video images in governmental and commercial data bases can be recombined endlessly to produce any effect chosen.  Now, perhaps, "pictures" will be worth a thousand tanks.  Of course, "truth will out" eventually, but by the time the people of the targeted nation discover that the nationwide broadcast of the conversation between the maximum leader and Jimmy Carter in which all loyal citizens were told to cease fighting and return to their homes was created in Hollywood or Langley, the war may be over.  Netwar is beginning to enter the zone of illusion.</P>

<P>This is not science fiction; these are, as anyone who has seen Forest Gump knows, the capabilities of existing or rapidly emerging technologies.  Heres how it might work: through hitching a ride on an unsuspecting commercial satellite, a "fictive simulation" is broadcast.  Simultaneously, various "info-niches" in the target state are accessed by our net-warriors via the World Wide Web and the Internet.  These info-niche-targets, and the information they receive, are precision tailored to the strategic needs of the moment: some receive reinforcement for the fictive simulation; others receive the "real" truth; others receive merely slight variations.  What is happening here?  </P>

<P>This kind of eletronic information manipulation elevates the strategic potential of propaganda to new heights.  This is not traditional propaganda in which the target is discredited as a source of reliable information.  Rather, the very possibility of  "truth" is being replaced with "virtual reality" that is, information which produces effects independent of its physical reality.  What is being attacked in a strategic level netwar are not only the emotions, or motives, or beliefs of the target population, but the very power of objective reasoning: this threatens the very possibility of rational state control.</P>

<P>Let us return to the previous scenario to play out its effects.  The fictive simulation of the maximum leader's call to stop fighting would, of course, be followed immediately by a "real" broadcast in which te Voice and Vision exposes the netwar attack as propaganda invented by culture destroyers in Hollywood.  Jimmy Carter is denounced as a hoax.  But the damage has already been done: it is all but impossible for the television viewers of the targeted state, including military commanders, to tell which broadcast is true and which fiction, at least in a timely manner.  In a society under assault across its entire infosphere, it will become increasingly difficult for members of that society, but essential for the military, to verify internally the truth or accuracy of anything.  Objective reasoning is threatened.  </P>

<P>At the strategic level, the ability to "observe" is flooded by contradictory information and data; more importantly, the ability to "orient" is weakened by the assault on the very possibility of objective reasoning as the known is replaced by the fictive; "decisions" respond increasingly to this fictive or virtual universe and; of course, governmental and military "actions" become increasingly chaotic as there is no "rational" relationship of means to ends.  It would seem, then, that strategic level netwar or Information War brings us within sight of Sun Tzus elusive "acme of skill" wherein the enemy is subdued without killing by attacking his ability to form or execute a coherent strategy.8   Reality, especially battlefield reality, may be far more complex than the Info-warriors yet imagine, and victory not so neat.  The idea of "societal-level ideational conflict" must be considered with all the care given to the conduct of nuclear war as the "end state" of netwar may not be bloodless surrender, but total disruption of the targeted society.  Victory may be too costly as the cost may be truth and social order.</P>

<h4WHAT IS TRUTH</h4>

<P>Any discussion of Information Warfare, netwar, cyberwar, or even perception manipulation as a component of command and control warfare by the armed forces of the United States at the strategic level must occur in the context of the moral nature of communication in a pluralistic, secular, democratic society.  That is, the question must be raised whether using the techniques of information warfare at the strategic level is compatible with American law, purposes and principles.  Likewise, the question must be raised whether the armed forces of the United States have the constitutional, moral or legal authority and, more importantly, the practical ability to develop and deploy the techniques of Information Warfare at the strategic level in a prudent and practical manner.  There are good reasons to be skeptical. </P>

<P>According to the philosopher Eric Voegelin, the moral basis of communication in any society can be discussed in terms of its substantive, pragmatic, and intoxicant functions.9  The substantive purpose of communication is the building or developing of the individual human personality.  It is the process by which a substantive, real-world community of "like-minded" persons is created, developed and sustained.  Simply, it is the glue which binds a society together and orients the societys members to decide and act in the world.</P>

<P>At the most trivial level, the moral purpose of substantive communication can be seen in contemporary American efforts to remove sexist or racist language from accepted use.  At a more serious level, the debates in American society about family values and prayer in the public schools illustrate a recognition of the substantive and formative nature of communication in society, as "private religious views," in the view of many, must not corrupt the public school formation of character for life in pluralistic, modern America.  Finally, any real world society rests on the substantive communication and understanding among its members.  Again, in Voegelins terms, society is no mere external structure of relationships; it is a "cosmion," a universe of meaning illuminated with meaning from within by the human beings who continuously create and bear it as the mode and condition of their self-realization. 10 Substantive communication makes a society and the personalities of the individuals in it.</P>

<P>The efforts of several nations such as China, Iran, or Saudi Arabia to insulate their societies from the effects of the global communications network illustrate their awareness that their cultures and societies depend on a shared, substantive universe of discourse distinctive to their societies.  Even within the West, the French are fully aware that the continued existence of France as a distinctive society organized for action in history may require state intervention in the substantive content of communication within society.11  That France seeks to limits the percentage of foreign broadcast material and American films in Europe illustrates the seriousness with which they consider the substantive nature of communication.  </P>

<P>The acknowledgment of a substantive function of communication is, however, problematic in American society as the ethos of much of the dominant political class has reduced "morality" or character formation to a question of private prejudice.12 Religious arguments that abortion is wrong as it violates "natural law" are marginalized politically as "private opinion."  How long the armed forces will continue to be permitted to discipline an officer on the basis of such a quaint concept as adultery remains to be seen.     </P>

<P>Voegelins second construct, identifying the pragmatic function of communication in society, is reasonably straightforward.  Pragmatic communication is defined by its goal and consists of the whole range of techniques designed to influence other persons to behave in ways the communicator wishes.  Only behavior matters.  Most political and commercial communication is merely pragmatic.  It is usually indifferent to the substantive moral content of the message and intends to mold perception, and consequently behavior, to the purposes of the communicator.  The target of pragmatic communication, real human beings, is reduced to an object for manipulation.  The morally dubious quality of an advertising industry devoted to the development of the personalities of Americans as consumers of superfluous material goods needs little comment.  The morally destructive quality of political advertising which reduces civic discourse to conditioned response to sound-bytes and slogans has been seen, correctly, as a threat to democracy.  This pragmatic use of communication as an attempt at perception manipulation is, of course, the central essence of Information War: its use by the government and the armed forces is, consequently, the real issue.</P>

<P>Finally, the intoxicant function of communication in American society is equally straightforward.  The addiction of a considerable part of the citizenry to talk shows, soap operas, romance novels, professional sports broadcasts, high-profile legal trials and other well-known forms of distraction and diversion is well catered to by the "entertainment" industry.  Whatever the morality of the entertainment pushers denounced by Senator Dole, the intoxicant quality of much contemporary communication may be more a commentary on the bored, empty and confused personalities of the addicts.  The cultural impact of the U.S. entertainment industry on other nations is, again, widely recognized and is seen, correctly, as a form of cultural imperialism.</P>

<P>For Voegelin then, civil communication or public discourse in contemporary American society is dominated almost entirely by the intoxicant and pragmatic modes.  More importantly, the serious lack of substantive communication in American public life is defended by much of the secular and liberal political class in the name of freedom, pluralism and multiculturalism.  Pluralistic America is supposed to be a society in which the formation of character or opinion is left, through the use of various means of communication, to private initiative.  Government attempts at "communication" in an Information War, especially if prosecuted by the armed forces, would raise serious legal and moral questions in a pluralistic, multicultural society. </P>

<P>The official military view of strategy, recall, is the "art and science of developing and using political, economic, psychological, and military forces as necessary during peace and war, to afford the maximum support to policies, in order to increase the probabilities and favorable consequences of victory and to lessen the chances of defeat."   Strategy is the means to achieve an end, with military strategy, as Clausewitz observed, serving political or policy purposes.  A slightly different view of strategy, as developed by Admiral J.C. Wylie, exposes the key problem with Information War.  If strategy is a plan of action designed to achieve some end; a purpose together with a system of measures for its accomplishment, the limitations of Infowar thinking are obvious.13  </P>

<P>Sound military strategy as a general theory of power control requires influencing the adversary decision-maker in some way that is not only advantageous, but reasonably predictable.  The goal is control, not chaos.  A national security strategy of Information War or netwar at the strategic level, that is, "societal-level ideational conflict waged in part through internetted modes of communication," and an operational-level cyberwar or C2W campaign to decapitate the enemy's command structure from its body of troops, may or may not be "advantageous" but, more importantly, are unlikely to produce effects that are reasonably predictable.  Conflict or war is about a determinate some thing, not an indeterminate any thing.  If the goal of influencing the adversary's ability to "observe" by flooding him with corrupted or contradictory information and data; disrupting his ability to "orient" by the elimination of thepossibility of objective reasoning; and forcing his "decisions" to respond to a fictive or virtual universe, actions will, of course, be produced. They may, however, be actions which are chaotic, random, non-linear and inherently unpredictable by our side for the simple reason that there will be no "rational" relationship of means to ends.</P>

<P>In the context of military operational-level cyberwar or C2W, this appears to the Info-warrior as an attractive military strategy.  The inherently unpredictable nature of combat, Clausewitzs notorious "fog and friction" of real battle, will be amplified a hundredfold for the enemy in a successful cyberwar.  A successful cyber-strategy depends on the ability of the local military commander to deploy his power assets, especially his combat forces, not merely to dominate the enemy decision-cycle {which, after all, has just been rendered chaotic}, but to exploit battlefield opportunities as they evolve unpredictably from the disoriented, decapitated or irrational enemy actions.  Whether, then, C2W can shape the battlefield or will merely generate chaos remains to be seen.  </P>

<P>Cyber-strategy is the control of the evolution of the battlefield or theater power distribution to impose the allied commander's "order" on the enemy's "chaos."  As Sun-Tzu observed, "those who are able to adapt to changes in the enemy and achieve victory are considered supreme."14  The threat exists, however, that the destruction of the enemys command and control systems, and consequently, his rationality, may collapse "battle" into mere "fighting" with no outcome but surrender or death.  Merely defeating hostile fielded military forces may be insufficient for strategic victory.  Sun-Tzu also observed that "when battles gain victories and attacks achieve occupations, yet these successes are not followed up, it is disastrous.  This is known as 'persisting turmoil'."15  Whether the recent Gulf  War was a strategic victory or only one "battle" between Iraq and the U.S. remains for historians to judge.  Operational-level cyberwar may, then, be that very "acme of skill" which reduces the enemy will without killing.  On the other hand, cyberwar may also be the abolition of strategy as it attacks the very rationality the enemy requires to decide for war termination.</P>

<h4>STRATEGIC IMPLICATIONS</h4>

<P>The tools, techniques and strategy for cyberwar or C2W are being developed and, during wartime, should be employed.  In many ways, given the harsh requirements of war fighting, cyberwar is more demanding than netwar. Information-based cyberwar, as it will be increasingly the combat form of the future, should be supported politically.  The resources, organization and training needed for cyberwar will be provided once its war winning, and casualty reducing, potential is grasped by the national command authorities and the political leadership in Congress.  This development is certainly prudent as information dominance is essential for stealth, precision strike, and dominating maneuvre.  On the other hand, many of these very same tools and techniques of battlefield cyberwar can be applied to netwar or strategic-level Information War.  This, however, may not be prudent, as there are serious reasons to doubt the ability of the United States to prosecute Information War successfully.</P>

<P>First, at the level of pragmatic communication, the United States is an open society and may be too vulnerable to engage in netwar with an adversary prepared to "fight back."16  The communications infrastructure, the information highway is "wide open" in our society.  Both Vice Adm. John M.McConnell, Director of the National Secuity Agency and Adm. William Studeman, former Deputy Director of the C.I.A., have argued that the United States is more vulnerable that any other nation to this kind of warfare.  American society is vulnerable to a strategic netwar attack as physical control and security may be impossible for the domestic computer, communication, and information networks essential for the daily functioning of American society.  These systems, especially the militarys systems, are under constant attack and are vulnerable to penetration, manipulation, or even destruction by determined hackers.17  In the future, these may not be unstructured anarchic amateurs but well-paid network-ninjas inserting the latest French, Iranian, or Chinese virus into Compuserve or the Internet.18  A strategic Information Warfare attack on America's communication systems, including our military communication systems, air traffic control system, financial net, fuel pipeline pumping software, or computer-based clock/timing systems could have the strategic effect of infrastructure or societal paralysis.  </P>

<P>If the goal of pragmatic communication is merely behavior modification and if our open society pretends to resist all attempts at manipulation, the opportunity for "benign" attempts to shape perceptions and public opinion by little-regulated foreign interests, whether governmental, business, or "private," is, again, an important vulnerability.  Currently, for example, there are over 14,000 data-bases on Internet accessible and used by over 30 million people in over 90 nations world-wide.  There are over 1,600 known software pirates prowling the Internet, some no doubt, in the employ of hostile commercial or intelligence services.  The recent spy flap between France and the United States over alleged U.S. attempts to gather data on French Telecom may be indicative of the future.19   The Pentagons own netwar security technicians succedded in penetrating over 85% of the Department of Defense systems they hacked and, more importantly, were undetected in over 95% of their attacks.20  Infosphere dominance -- controlling the world of information exchange -- may be as complex and elusive as "escalation dominance" appeared to be in nuclear strategy.21  It will certainly be expensive: Assistant Secretary of Defense for Communications, Emmett Paige Jr., estimates the cost of defensive network security for the Pentagon at over $15 billion.  The U.S. business community, Federal, State and local governments, and the U.S. armed forces, are required to devote ever more resources and attention to computer, communications and data-base security.  The resources and skills required for battlefield cyberwar, whether defensive or offensive, are not insignificant; the resources and skills required to wage Information War, offensively or defensively, at the national strategic level would be massive.</P>

<P>Second, the political and legal issues surrounding Infowar are murky.  What of congressional oversight -- would one declare information war in response, say, to an Iranian-originated computer virus assault on the FBIs central terrorist data-base?  And what about preparing for it -- developing and implementing a national capability for defensive or offensive netwar?  The National Security Agency can assist the Pentagon with defensive information security but has no legal authority in the private, civil or commercial information universe.  The National Bureau of Standards, oddly enough, has some authority and is quite jealous of its prerogatives.  While theoretically a requirement to develop or implement a national Information War strategy, analogous to the nuclear-era Single Integrated Operations Plan, could be communicated from the President to the executive branch agencies, it is unclear whether there is adequate Congressional oversight.  Which committees of the House or Senate would have control and oversight of policies attendant to Information War or, for example, inquire into the judgment of a local ambassador or military commander who wished to use the tools of cyberwar for a benign netwar attempt at perception manipulation in peacetime to shape the potential wartime environment?22  The U.S. armed forces execute the national military strategy, they do not control it.  The armed forces are developing, quite appropriately, the tools, techniques and strategy for operational-level cyberwar or C2W to execute the national military strategy and, consequently, albeit unintentionally, are simultaneously developing the tools and capabilities to execute a national, strategic Information War strategy.  The former is their job under the Constitution; the latter may not be.  Congressional oversight of the development of a national strategic-level Information War capability is even more essential than oversight of the intelligence community.</P>

<P>Third, Information War seen as "societal-level ideational conflict waged in part through internetted modes of communication" may simply be beyond the competence of the executive agencies who would have to determine the substantive content to be communicated.  Pluralism is a great strength of American society, but perhaps a drawback in waging Infowar.  While diversity may make the formation and execution of domestic and even foreign policy more complex, it can be argued that the lack of a moral center or public philosophy in American society would render the political leadership nearly incapable of building a consensus on any substantive content for strategic level Information War policies.  Official American public substantive communication concerns essentially private or personal contending secular visions of America.  For some, enlightened self-interest is the substance of the good society.  For others, liberal individualism, technological progress, ethno-nationalistic racialism, New Age self-actualization, or Montana survivalism are the public project.  And, as "Moral Reason," in the classical or religious sense of the distinctively human mode of moral discourse, has been replaced by contending private moralities, even a national security strategy of Information War could be developed by the national security elite which related resources and effort to purposes or ends without substantive political, public, or moral debate.</P>

<P>Finally, however, a concrete real-world human society targeted for Information War aimed at influencing the "emotions, motives, objective reasoning, and ultimately the behavior" of either leaders, citizens, or subjects is still, as Eric Voegelin observed, a universe of substantive conversation "illuminated with meaning from within by the human beings who continuously create and bear it as the mode and condition of their self-realization."  The technological wizardry does not change the humanity of the target.  Unless the goal of Information War is merely to use the techniques of pragmatic communication to unhinge people from their ability to reason objectively, and, consequently, create an interesting problem for post-conflict reconstruction, any strategic-level netwar or Information War would seem to require the ability to communicate a substantive replacement for the discredited substantive content of the target society.  </P>

<P>If, say, an Information War were to be mounted against China to disrupt its drive for regional hegemony, the goal would be to "withdraw the Mandate of Heaven" from the rulers and "influence" the Chinese leaders and people to adopt the policies or behavior we find appropriate.  Put in terms of such a concrete policy goal, the philosophically problematic nature of Information War becomes outrageously obvious.  Does anyone really believe that the U.S. national executive agencies, including the armed forces or the Central Intelligence Agency, knows the substantive discourse of China sufficiently well to withdraw the Mandate of Heaven?  Worse: does anyone really believe that any set of officials in the U.S. government or military has the philosophical sophistication to project an alternative substantive discourse to replace, convincingly, the emotions, motives, reasoning, and behavior grounded in the Chinese reality we propose to "influence?"  Would our fictive creation really have virtual effects.  Would our fictive creation really have predictable effects.  We might be able to use the armed forces or CIA to destroy their objective reasoning through a "successful" Information War.  We might indeed be able to loose mere anarchy in a society, but that is not usually the political goal of war-fighting.</P>

<h4>SECOND THOUGHTS</h4>

<P>The techniques being developed by the armed forces for a more narrowly constrained operational-level cyberwar or C2W military campaign whose goal is to exploit disoriented enemy actions by superior ability to deploy allied military assets is appropriate and even essential in war.  This was demonstrated in the Gulf War. Translated to the strategic level, however, netwar or Information War is not a prudent national security or military strategy for the simple reason that neither the armed forces nor any other instruments of national power have the ability to exploit an adversary's society in a way that promises either advantageous or predictable results.  "Societal-level ideational conflict" must be considered with all the care given to the conduct of nuclear war as the "end state" of a netwar may not be bloodless surrender, but total disruption of the targeted society.  Conflict resolution, including ending wars this side of blasting people into unconditional surrender, assumes and requires some rationality -- even if it is the mere coordination of ends with means.  Moral reasoning and substantive communication may not be required; minimal reasoning and pragmatic communication are required.  A successful all-out strategic-level Information War may, however, have destroyed the enemys ability to know anything with certainty and corrupted his ability to communicate as a society to such a degree that his capacity for minimal reasoning or pragmatic communication is destroyed.</P>

<P> On the assumption that it was never the goal of U.S. national security policy to totally destroy the Soviet Union,  the "decapitation" of the Soviet military leadership in a hypothetical nuclear exchange was intended to defend the United States by preventing an escalatory or exploitative strike, nuclear or otherwise.  Precisely how war-termination would have been accomplished without an effective Soviet leadership will remain, hopefully, one of the great mysteries.  The "decapitation" of the leadership is, however, often proposed as a key goal of an Information War.  That is, the credibility, legitimacy, or even physical ability to communicate of the leadership/decision-makers will be compromised or destroyed relative to their own population and in terms of their own orienting world-view.  And, even if we merely electronically seize his communication system to substitute our reality into his society, with whom, then, do we negotiate the end of the conflict?  What confidence do we have that a call to surrender, even if communicated to the people by either the enemy leadership or our net-warriors, would be accepted as "real" and not another "virtual" event?  And, depending on the content, intensity and "totality" of a strategic Information War, the political equivalent of psychological inflation is a genuine possibility.  Personalities could be flooded with irrational or unconsciousness factors -- the clinical consequence of which is generally acute psychosis.  Many members of the Japanese military in 1945, including the war minister, were prepared for Japan to commit national suicide like a beautiful flower.   How do we do conflict resolution, war-termination or post-conflict reconstruction with a population or leadership whose "objective reasoning" has been compromised, at best?  </P>

<P>As the mutually destructive effects of nuclear war were recognized by rational American and Soviet decision-makers as disproportionate with the goals of almost any imaginable conflict, likewise, the mutually destructive effects of a "total" Information War exchange on the humanity and the rational foundation of communication in either society may be equally disproportionate with the any rational political goals of the conflict.  And, as the techniques of cyberstrike proliferate throughout the international system, the ability of even small powers, non-state actors, or even hacker-terrorists to gain the capabilities to do massive damage to the United States, mutually-assured-cyber-destruction may result in a kind of Infowar deterrence.  The Pentagons own Defense Science Board has admitted that Information Warfare technologies and capabilities are being developed in the open-market, beyond government control and that a Third World  nation could procure a formidable, modern IW capability virtually off-the-shelf. 23  Infowar deterrence or Infowar arms-race?  As Sun-Tzu observed, then, "without advantage, do not act; without gain, do not utilize; without crises, do not battle."24  </P>

<P>Information Warfare is the central national security issue of the 21st century and the United States must develop a coherent national-level policy on the military and strategic use of these new technologies and capabilities in peace and war.  The U.S. armed forces are developing, under the rubric of Command & Control Warfare, the technologies and systems needed to provide the needed capability for cyberwar.  The control and exploitation of information and information technologies to impose or adapt the local military commander's battlefield order to purposely generated stochastic chaos may be possible, then, in operational cyberwar.  Even here, there are some doubts.25  Most of these same electronic technologies and systems, however, can be used to develop a national-level strategic capability for netwar.  Here, there are genuine doubts.  The control and exploitation of information and information-based technologies to impose a form on the remnants of societies no longer capable of self-organization because their substantive universe of meaning has been destroyed or corrupted may, as Voegelin feared, not be possible.26  Few Info-warriors would claim the ability to re-orient the former Soviet Union into a liberal, Western society or influence the far more ancient barbarism in that Heart of Darkness - Rwanda.  Perhaps strategic-level Information War, netwar, is, indeed, like nuclear war: the capability must be developed if there is to be deterrence; its employment, however, would be the folly of mutually assured destruction.</P>

<P>If the United States is to build the capacity for Information War, in the sure and certain knowledge that the required technologies have already proliferated to both state and non-state potential rivals, a realistic national dialog must occur and a realistic, substantive consensus must be built.  It is useless and dangerous to pretend that the proliferation of these information warfare technologies will not provide capabilities to peer, niche, or even rogue competitors to do serious harm to American society.  It is useless and dangerous to pretend that military-based cyberwar or C2W capabilities will not be developed by potential enemies as there is almost universal recognition, even in the so-called Third World, that these capabilities are essential on the contemporary battlefield.27 It is useless and naive to pretend that cyberwar technologies could not be turned to netwar applications.  It is essential, then, that the armed forces, the foreign and domestic intelligence and law-enforcement communities, the Presidents National Security Council, the Congress, and, most importantly, the American public give serious and sustained attention to cyberwar, netwar and Information War.  Perhaps like Chuang Tzus gardener, we will say it is not that I do not know about this invention; but that I should be ashamed to use it. </P>

<h4>ENDNOTES</h4>
