<HEAD><TITLE>

On Information Warfare: Deichman

</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffFF">


<!-- Header/Nav-Bar Table -------------------------------------------->

<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td valign=top width=48>
<a href="mil_c4i.html-ssi"><img width=48 height=68 border=0 src="../../images/back.gif" alt="Back"></a>
</td>
<td valign=top width=48>
<a href="http://www.infowar.com/index.html-ssi"><img width=48 height=68 border=0 src="../../images/home.gif" alt="Home"></a>
</td>
<td valign=top width=48>
<a href="http://www.infowar.com/search_reg.html-ssi"><img width=48 height=68 border=0 src="../../images/srch.gif" alt="Search"></a>
</td>
<td valign=top align=right width=236>
<img border=0 width=236 height=68 src="../../images/line.gif">
</td>

<td width=200>
<img vspace=3 border=0 src="../../images/dot_spac.gif"><br>
<A HREF="http://www.ncsa.com
"><img width=200 height=68 border=0 src="http://www.infowar.com/sponsors/ad2.gif"></A>
</td>
</tr>
</tr>
</table>
<br>
<IMG ALT="[Bomb2]" SRC="../../images/bomb2_li.gif" width=580><p>


<!-- Article Body Table ---------------------------------------------->

<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<img border=0 width=43 height=43 src="../../images/pent.gif">
</td>
<td valign=middle width=440>
<center><h2>
ON INFORMATION WAR

</h2>


</Center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>

<Center>

Shane D. Deichman<BR>
NCCOSC RDT&amp;E Division<BR>
Code 4122<BR>
49180 Transmitter Road<BR>
San Diego, California 92152-7341<BR>
+1-619-553-2767 [fax: -6288]<BR>
deichman@nosc.mil<BR>
</Center>

<p>We are at the dawn of a new age, one that will have a profound impact on the way we live, work and fight.  No longer is military effectiveness simply a function of delivering ordnance to target.  The evolving art of "information warfare" offers the promise of an entirely different means of ensuring national security and the defense of national interests.</p>

<h4>Introduction</h4>

<p>Information plays a crucial role in the conduct of warfare. In fact, the evolution of warfighting can be traced more readily through advances in information systems than through advances in weaponry.</p>
<p>The agrarian revolution of mankind's early history was based on ploughs and the animals that pulled them.  Metal-working ability was a prerequisite, which in turn led to the development of armor, swords, etc.  Wars were fought primarily by non-professional militia forces, and standing armies were practically nonexistent (a notable exception is the Spartan land  armies of the fifth century B.C.).[1] </p>
<p>Warfare during this epoch was conducted on a comparatively  small scale.  For instance, the entire Athenian army at the start  of the Peloponnesian War in 431 B.C. was roughly as large as a contemporary infantry division.  Information was derived empirically,  and transmitted either by hand or by some limited form of long distance communication (e.g., smoke signals). The industrial revolution, based on engines and the fuels that fed them, vastly increased a society's production capability as well as its capital.  This creation of a large, powerful middle class led to the establishment of massive professional armies that numbered (in some cases) in the millions.  The concept of _levee en masse_, promulgated during the French Revolution, made "total war" a reality.  The conduct of warfare was ferocious, as evidenced in the battles of Gettysburg, Verdun  ("_On ne passe pas!_"), and Stalingrad. Today, the information revolution -- rooted in computers and the networks that connect them -- is undoing the ills of the industrial revolution.  The ability to instantaneously transmit information to anywhere on the globe has made Napoleon's strategy of applying massive force at decisive points obsolete and morally unpalatable.</p>
<p>The Clausewitzian trinity of the political leadership, military and populace has shifted dramatically to the people. No longer will populations stand for the wholesale slaughter and destruction of strategic bombing campaigns, such as those conducted in Japan during World War II (which left over eight million homeless and killed hundreds of thousands).[2]  In Operation DESERT STORM, the world was offered a glimpse of the future's potential: precision-guided munitions minimizing collateral damage; intelligence networks providing realtime information relay (cf. CNN); and crippling blows dealt to key decisionmaking nodes in order to minimize retaliation.  The prospectus for the 21st century is that he who wins the  information war will be the victor.</p>
<p>Information warfare offers many prospects for non-hard kill engagements that prevent a shooter from ever getting int  a position to fire.  However, though the United States has a doctrine for all elements of hard kill warfare, "[w]hat is missing ... is doctrine for information."[3]</p>

<h4>Global Outlook</h4>

<p>Several factors will have a significant impact on warfighting in the 21st century.  Among them are the demonopolization of information, the proliferation of technology and manufacturing expertise, and the likelihood of combating adversaries equipped with assets of blue manufacture.  In addition, the political stresses associated with renascent nationalism will have a debilitating impact on global stability and the traditional means of coalition warfare. The end of the Cold War has witnessed the decreasing prevalence of nation-states with absolute geographical boundaries as mechanisms of political power.  Nation-states gained predominance as a political entity following the Peace of Westphalia in 1648 and the model regime of Louis XIV, who established a centralized bureaucracy with administrative control over a geographical concentration of people bound by a common culture.  </p>
<p>Due to the limited methods of communication and information dissemination -- usually text printed on a Gutenberg-style press -- collocation was vital. Telecommunications technology is eliminating the boundaries of knowledge and thought.  "Nations" (i.e.,collections of people with common political interests, such as the Palestine Liberation Organization) no longer presuppose geographical collocation.  The ability to instantaneously transmit information from one location to any other on the globe, coupled with the renascent nationalistic fervors (in locales as diverse as Abkhazia, Ossetia, Nagorno-Karabakh, Timor, Ghana and Bosnia-Hercegovina), will have a profound impact on the very nature of the threat to America's national interests.</p>
<p>The greatest threat to national security in the 21st century will come not from an industrial power mobilizing massive conventional forces (and providing extensive strategic warning), but from geographically-dispersed "cyberwarriors" operating on the world's information superhighways seeking to upset fragile communications links. The cyberspace of information warfare promises to become the principal "battlefield" of the 21st century.</p>

<h4>Prospectus</h4>

<p>The center of gravity of modern militaries is shifting from large force concentrations to the fragile command and control networks that relay vital information to deployed units --be they small infantry units, fighter squadrons performing defensive counter-air missions, or destroyers creating an ASW picket.  Every element of warfighting is increasingly dependent on information obtained from both organic and nonorganic sensors.</p>
<p>Information warfare constitutes an entirely different method of warfighting.  While the revolution of air power earlier this century gave operational commanders new ways to perform the traditional task of delivering ordnance to target, the developments of the information revolution will give the "C4I warrior" the ability to prevent a shooter from ever coming close to delivering weapons.</p>
<p>Beyond simply spoofing "bogeys" with false track information so their precision-guided munitions go astray, lines of supply and logistics networks can be upset long before an engagement seems imminent.  Imagine the havoc that would ensue  if an electronic requisition for spare parts of a critical system component (e.g., o-rings) was clandestinely decreased by several orders of magnitude -- or if a request for a particularly expensive component were similarly increased. The purveyors of information warfare must be highly specialized, joint operators.  Information warfare _demands_ jointness.  Interoperability and portability among Navy battlegroups, Army and Marine divisions, Air Force wings and even Coast Guard assets is essential if the U.S. is going to be an effective combatant in the battlefields of the 21st century. Failure to do so will result in too many varying protocols to be effective, and a lack of synergy in an extranational engagement.</p>

<h4>The C4I Warrior</h4>

<p>In their landmark document entitled "C4I for the Warrior,"  the Joint Staff (J-6) established a precedent for integrating  modern information technologies into the warfare environment.  Acknowledging that teamwork is the key to achieving the vision of a joint, interoperable architecture, Admiral Richard C. Macke, USN (then Director, J-6; currently U.S. CINCPAC) identified the warrior's needs as "a fused, realtime, true representation of the Warrior's battlespace -- an ability to order, respond and coordinate horizontally and vertically to the degree necessary to prosecute his mission in that battlespace."[4]</p>
<p>The proliferation of information processing technologies -- already a _fait accompli_ -- is fulfilling the vision of J-6, creating an entity that can be described as the "C4I Warrior."  While information processing and dissemination was once the sole purview of operations specialists and other technically-oriented billets, the warfare environment of the 21st century will require that everyone be competent in the art of information war.The C4I Warrior is representative of any warfighting element that uses, creates or manipulates information in order to gain an operational or a tactical advantage.  The spectrum encompasses elements as granular as a ten-man infantry squad outfitted with position locating and reporting transceivers (PLRS) to those as grandiose as an amphibious ready group with a Marine expeditionary unit and integrated tactical flag command center (TFCC).</p>
<p>Some Principles of Information Warfare</p>
<p>The technological developments of the transistor age have undermined the traditional focus of warfare on elements of space (_vice_ time).  Clausewitz's distillation of Napoleon into theory, and Mahan's extension of Clausewitzian concepts to naval warfare, both focused on the spatial elements of warfare --the massive accumulation of force at decisive points, the military control of spatial dimensions, and the demands of logistics manifested in "culminating points."</p>

<p>However, more appropriate to the modern age of warfare is a balanced, "spacetime" approach akin to Sir Julian Corbett's principles of maritime strategy.  While Mahan wrote of sea control in a context that was pervasive in its spatiality (asserting continuous control of the seas, forcing an enemy back into his ports where his ships could be dealt with at the leisure of his opponent), Corbett introduced temporal considerations -- i.e., "sea denial" -- to maritime strategy.  Rather than expending resources to constantly secure vital sea lines of communication (SLOCs) by way of "positive sea control," Corbett admonished naval  strategists to instead work toward denying an adversary critical  access to his own SLOCs.  An enemy who lacks control of his own sea lanes lacks the means by which to threaten others. To paraphrase Corbett, "The object of information warfare must always be directly or indirectly either to secure the command of information or to prevent the enemy from securing it."[5]</p>

<h4>Strategies of the Offensive</h4>

<p>A key element of the information warfare environment is the participants need not possess superpower status.  Any power (even those not considered nation-states) with a modicum of technology can disrupt fragile C2 networks and deny critical information services.  Rather than a Mahanian "information control" strategy that attempts to dominate all segments of the information spectrum, though, a more realistic strategy for U.S. forces is one of "information denial" (i.e., the denial of access to truthful information).</p>
<p>As technology has grown, so too have the dimensions of the engagement envelope.  Over-the-horizon weapons, "fired and forgotten," are commonplace on the modern battlefield -- as is the operators' reliance on the veracity of their sensor displays. The inability to empirically confirm or deny the presence of a threat has created a new sense of "truth" -- that which corresponds to the perception of sensor data. Manipulation of an adversary's data in order to provoke (or deny) a reaction is not a new idea.  However, rather than flooding the electromagnetic spectrum with broadband energy -- as dictated by current electronic warfare doctrine -- more elegant methods of information warfare subtly manipulate the signals an enemy's sensors provide to his decisionmaking </p>
<p>Such forms of "very soft kill" can be accomplished remotely through any networks to which an adversary may be connected, or locally by embedding malicious signals into a carrier wave to be detected by enemy sensors. Other means of "very soft kill" of information systems include overload (e.g., filling a message buffer with superfluous electronic mail messages so as to diminish its efficiency) and denying services by electronically "cracking" a system and altering file structures.</p>
<p>The offensive opportunities of the information revolution will allow global disruption of critical C2 networks, effectively "cutting an enemy's head off and leaving his body to die."  Soft and very soft kill techniques are also a veritable means of hard kill avoidance, thereby minimizing collateral damage. As Corbett prescribed methods of "sea denial" in pursuit of maritime supremacy, U.S. forces should focus on "information  denial" as a means of both protecting their own information  networks and preventing an adversary from being able to deliver ordnance to target.</p>
<p>While simply disrupting information flow (via jamming or other soft kill means) alerts an adversary to the presence of a threat, the surreptitious alteration of the very information he perceives can cause him to make incorrect decisions.  Such an accomplishment -- achieving victory without bloodshed -- is what the ancient Chinese warrior-philosopher Sun Tzu called "the acme of skill."[6]</p>

<h4>Quo Vadis?</h4>

<p>The stunning technological breakthroughs of the information age are revolutionizing the means and methods of warfighting.  Gone are the days of massive armies engaged in a perpetual "tug-of-war" across trench lines.  Warfighting in the 21st century will be won not by he who can deliver the highest tonnage of ordnance, but by he who wins the information war. To be prepared for this new dimension of warfare, the U.S. needs to reexamine its force structure at all levels to ensure that every sailor, soldier, airman and Marine is proficient with information technologies.  At the policymaking level, a doctrine for information warfare must be developed jointly by all services. </p>
<p>Given the recent reorganization of Department of Defense information agencies under the single umbrella of the Defense Information Systems Agency (DISA), logic dictates that any DoD information warfare doctrine originate from there. By elevating the position of Director, DISA to a four-star billet with a seat on the Joint Chiefs of Staff, in addition to establishing a civilian counterpart to interface with the service Secretaries, the U.S. will take a proactive approach towards influencing the principle means of warfighting in the 21st century.</p>
<p>The United States has the most capable, best trained fighting force in history.  For that legacy to continue, the U.S. must awaken from the dogmatic slumbers of hard kill overdependence and embrace a new era of warfighting.</p>
<p>(Reprinted with permission of author. A condensed version of this article appeared in the Nov. 95 issue of  SIGNAL Magazine.</p>

<h4>Endnotes</h4>

<I>
<p>1       Thucydides, History of the Peloponnesian War, trans. by Rex Warner, Penguin Classics (1954); Appendix 2, p. 613.</p>
<p>2       Greenfield, Kent R., American Strategy in World War II -- A Reconsideration, Robert E. Krieger Publishing Co. (1982); p. 119.</p>
<p>3       Strassmann, Paul (former Director of Defense Information); quoted in Toffler, Alvin and Heidi, War and Anti-War: Survival at the Dawn of the 21st Century, Little, Brown and Co. (1993); p. 140.</p>
<p>4       "C4I for the Warrior," published by the C4 Architecture and Integration Division (J6I), The Joint Staff, The Pentagon (1992).</p>
<p>5       Adapted from Corbett, Sir Julian S., Some Principles of Maritime Strategy, Longmans, Green and Co. (1911); p. 87.</p>
<p>6       Sun Tzu, The Art of War, trans. by Samual Griffith, Oxford Univ. Press (1963); p. 77.
</I>


