<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<img border=0 width=43 height=43 src="../../images/pent.gif">
</td>
<td valign=middle width=440>
<center><h2>
Comments from Moscow about their attitudes to Information Warfare.</B>
<P>

</h2>


</Center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>

<Center>

Taken from OTC News Alert<BR>

</Center>



<P>
 <P>MOSCOW, July 25 (Itar-Tass) -- The Federation Council upper house of 
parliament today held hearings about new threats to Russia's security in
the time of instability and uncertainty at home and the transition to a 
multi-polar world in the international arena. </P>
  <P> As concerns external threats, first deputy general-director of the
Federal Government Communications and Information Agency (FAPSI) Vladimir
Markonenko pointed out that the U.S. intelligence services are working on
methods of penetrating the computer networks of potential enemies and
implanting viruses and "logical bombs" for future activation in the event
of a crisis. </P>
  <P> Such time bombs can disorganise defences and the state government
system,  as well as transport and energy infrastructure, Markonenko said. </P>
   <P>He noted that "the danger of an information war breaking out is coming
to the fore, and information warfare will soon rank second only to
thermo-nuclear war by its consequences." </P>
  <P> Markonenko said, "the danger of unsanctioned intervention in the
operations of information systems has increased abruptly." </P>
<P>   An analysis of the state of information security in Russia has revealed
that "the threats to the country's closed telecommunications systems are
real and it is necessary to take adequate measures without delay." </P>
  <P> According to Markonenko, "the foreign special services focus first of
all on ways of gathering information about the activity of the supreme
bodies of state authority of Russia, as well as on ways of influencing the
country's financial, economic, and banking systems." </P>
  <P> Markonenko noted that the protection of confidential national
information has become one of priorities in the state policy of many
developed countries. He recalled that six federal laws on combatting crime
in this sphere were already effective in the United States and four - in
Germany. </P>
   vfp/ <BR>
    Copyright 1996<BR>
<BR>

</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
