<td width=440>


<H3><Center>
SPA vs. Site with Hack links? Private Big Brother?
</H3>
</Center>
<BR>
<P>A really close friend of mine was INVESTIGATED not for hosting a site but
for providing DNS for a web site that was on hacking. Not Software piracy
but hacking. Information on how to hack things like telephones etc. Pure
information. No software, no files and full disclaimers.

<P>He gets a call and a letter from the SPA who tells him that he is going 
to be investigated unless he cuts the link. He cuts the link and they 
send him a document to sign that releases him of his responsiblity 
regarding the situation. These people were literally ready to 
storm-trooper into his home, search his premises, search his place of 
employment and most likely get him fired.

<P>It totally blew me away that the SPA has this power to chill free speech
and expression on the net. Hot damn, they are international as well.

<P>If anyone starts an anti-SPA group, I'll join. :)</P>

John<BR>

