<tr>
<td width=440>


<H2><Center>
Hackers crack CIA home page code.
</H2>
</Center>
<BR>
<P>This morning, hackers did a number on the CIA home page, altering it, adding
some obsecentities and changed the title to "Central Stupidity Agency."   It
was stated that a tipster call CNN Interactive in Atlanta  and said that the
break-in was done by Swedish hackers.   The phone call was received about
5:45 a.m. EDT. When asked what the hackers had done to the page, the man
said, "I think you  should just take a look at it."   Withour further
comment, he hung up.</P>
<BR>
>The hackers appeared to have obliterated the CIA's entire <BR>
>site, replacing it with their own design. The site greeted <BR>
>Internet surfers with: "Welcome to the Central Stupidity <BR>
>Agency," followed by the intriguing statement, "STOP LYING BO <BR>
>SKARINDER!!!"<BR>

<P>The hackers were kind and provided several links underneath the greeting
including  Playboy, Hackerz.org, Flashback Magazine and protocols from The
Swedish Hackers Association.

<P>The group who did this dastardly deed called themselves."Power Through
Resistance," left an obscenity-laced message at the bottom of the page.

<P>CIA officials were not immediately available for comment.

<P>Internet break-ins have become an increasing concern for U.S. defense and
intelligence agencies. Last month, hackers broke into the Justice
Department's Web site, adding swastikas, obscenities and a picture of Adolf
Hitler to the page. 

<P>Justice officials were quick to state that the hackers did not gain access
to criminal files and pulled the plug on the site.   


<BR>

</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
