<HEAD><TITLE>
CONCEPT OF HACKING

</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffFF">


<!-- Header/Nav-Bar Table -------------------------------------------->

<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td valign=top width=48>
<a href="hacker.html-ssi"><img width=48 height=68 border=0 src="../../images/back.gif" alt="Back"></a>
</td>
<td valign=top width=48>
<a href="http://www.infowar.com/index.html-ssi"><img width=48 height=68 border=0 src="../../images/home.gif" alt="Home"></a>
</td>
<td valign=top width=48>
<a href="http://www.infowar.com/search_reg.html-ssi"><img width=48 height=68 border=0 src="../../images/srch.gif" alt="Search"></a>
</td>
<td valign=top align=right width=236>
<img border=0 width=236 height=68 src="../../images/line.gif">
</td>

<td width=200>
<img vspace=3 border=0 src="../../images/dot_spac.gif"><br>
<A HREF="http://www.infowar.com/sponsors/ad1/oss96.html-ssi
"><img width=200 height=68 border=0 src="http://www.infowar.com/sponsors/ad1.gif"></A>
</td>
</tr>
</tr>
</table>
<br>
<IMG ALT="[Bomb2]" SRC="../../images/bomb2_li.gif" width=580><p>


<!-- Article Body Table ---------------------------------------------->

<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<img border=0 width=43 height=43 src="../../images/hack.gif">
</td>
<td valign=middle width=440>
<center><h2>

</h2>


</Center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>


<H2><Center>CHAPTER ONE - AN INTRODUCTION TO THE STUDY THE CONCEPT OF HACKING - A THREAT</CENTER></H2>
<P>

Download the complete text of this<a href="hackrisk.zip"> Thesis by Alan Nicholas Chantler </a> in Word DOC format: 426K Zipped. 
<BR>
<BR>
<I>In this chapter, the focus of this ethnographic study is broadly
described, the purposes and significance of the study delineated,
and the structure of the report overviewed.</I>
<P>
<I>The chapter also conceptualises and defines hacking. This is
done by considering the historical development and conceptualisation
of hacking in symbiosis with the development of computer technology.
The current literature's descriptions of hacking, the players
who are involved in hacking (such as hackers and security people),
and the groups into which hackers have been divided are then described.
This follows with a list of perceived threats and examples of
the dangers which hackers pose to the technological world.</I>
<P>
<I>(It could be argued that this chapter should be part of Chapter
2 - The Literature Review. However, because of the conceptualisations
which are developed here, it was felt more appropriate to keep
it as a separate chapter.)</I>
<P>
<B>1.1 BACKGROUND</B> 
<P>
The concept of the historical development of hacking, in symbiosis
with the development of computer technology, is presented in this
section.
<P>
The computer can be considered as a calculating machine, its history
stretching back thousands of years to the abacus; 'a calculating
frame with balls sliding on wires' (Garmonsway 1965, p1). Calculating
machines, e.g., Babbage's Difference Engine of 1822 and the slide-rule,
may also be described as computers. More recently the computer
was defined as 'an electronic calculator' (Wright 1951, p31);
'a machine which &quot;memorises&quot;, sifts, analyses and correlates
data, and produces selective data as required.' (Garmonsway 1965,
p148); however, today the term is usually limited to those electronic
devices that are 'given a program to follow, data to store or
calculate with, and means with which to present results or (other)
stored information' (Yule 1979, p136).
<P>
Computer technology continues to evolve at an accelerating rate
and with it society has developed new roles and professions to
address the emerging specialisations within the computing field
(Chantler 1992a). The advent of the small business computer, followed
by the proliferation phenomena of technology in the 'home' or
'personal computers' (PCs), leading to the 'portable' then 'laptop'
and currently the 'notebook' PCs, has seen the emergence of a
corresponding social phenomena, that of the 'computer hacker'.
<P>
Levy (1984) in <I>Hackers, Heroes of the Computer Revolution</I>presents
hackers as the original gurus of computing. At their 'birth' in
the late 1950s, they were portrayed as the people who actively
sought new ways to improve the hardware and the software, often
to make it perform in ways that were far beyond what they were
originally designed to do. They were the enthusiasts who were
totally absorbed by the fascination of their work. 'Hackers' today,
in the broadest sense of the word, are considered as computer
enthusiasts who, using their home PC and a telephone modem, illegally
'break-into' computer systems that belong to the large multi-national
corporations and government agencies (Jones 1993).
<P>
The researcher (the term 'researcher' hereinafter is used to refer
to the writer of this thesis) suggests that as information-technology
continues to invade our private lives, the scope for hacker-crimes
also increases: the temptation is there to penetrate fax machines,
electronic funds transfer (EFT) systems, electronic mail systems,
PABXs (telephone exchanges: Private Automatic Branch eXchange),
VMBs (voice mail boxes) and remote controlled security systems.
To do so is illegal and these illegal activities have branded
hackers as criminals. Hackers actively create an increasing number
of problems in our computer-dependent society.
<P>
An early article (Electronics Australia 1975, p28), titled 'How
Safe are Computers from Sabotage?', details the threats to information
systems. These range over a broad spectrum including natural catastrophe;
sabotage; theft of data, theft of application software and theft
of hardware; bugging; accidental disclosure and physical assault.
Two examples of computer crimes are also presented to illustrate
the need for more stringent security precautions: the first one
is described as 'a now classic and very imaginative example of
computer crime' which was carried out by a young electrical engineer
on the West Coast of the USA. Posing as a customer, he discovered
a way to log-on to the computerised central supply division at
the Pacific Telephone and Telegraph Company. Before someone betrayed
him, he had illegally ordered over $1 million worth of equipment
without paying for it. The second example details 'a weak spot'
in a banking computer system which was found by a clerk in a Washington
DC bank. Noting that the bank's computer only checked the magnetically-coded
deposit numbers on the bottom of the incoming deposit slips, he
replaced the usual supply of deposit slips on the customers' desks
with his own account number. Depositors, using forms from the
lobby desks, unknowingly added money to his account. A few days
later he withdrew the money and disappeared.
<P>
It is interesting to note that in both of these examples, the
word 'hacker' does not appear. However, these specific cases have
since been referred to in more recent times (Yovel, Oren and Klein
1989) as the activities of 'computer hackers'. Now, over twenty
years later, the word 'hacker' is seen to be synonymous with such
activities.
<P>
The extent of the phenomena of 'hacking' has been further dramatised
by the media, the security and intelligence agencies, the police,
and telephone companies. Legislation has evolved and specialised
computer security services have been built to address the problems
caused by hackers (Parker 1993, p1). Because of this exposure,
much of the current knowledge about hackers has come from 'the
popular press'; police and security agencies, computer security
specialists, and also from those hackers who have been caught.
However, because of the clandestine nature of much of their activity,
the world of the computer hackers and their activities are mainly
unknown.
<P>
<B>1.2 RESEARCH GOALS</B>
<P>
This ethnographic study is about computer hackers and the threats
and risks which they are purported to pose.
<P>
Because of the links that tie hackers to the media, the researcher
will utilise some 'press' material. Normally this would not be
viewed as 'academic' enough to use as references. However, with
the lack of other more 'formal' information and because the researcher
is restricted in the use of classified information from defence
services and intelligence agencies, these are valid reasons for
its utilisation.
<P>
The media continually present us with reports on the exploits
of computer hackers. The majority of these reports appear to capitalise
on sensationalism. Hackers are described as 'whiz-kids, code-junkies,
cyberspace-jockeys, crackers, feral technocrats, fone-phreaks
or cyberpunks'. They are presented to us in a 'picture' which
indicates that they can penetrate all types of electronic information
systems and cause millions of dollars worth of damage; access
sensitive classified data; manipulate and steal money through
EFT (electronic funds transfer); compromise the nation's military
secrets; conduct fraud on a large scale; and, halt corporate businesses.
<P>
The research goals for this project are as follows:
<P>
1. To complete an ethnographic study devised to explore popular
perceptions of hackers and what they do. ('Living with the hackers'
to explore their 'world', forms a major part of this program.)
<P>
2. To determine the veracity of the perspective of the press by
examining the role of the media in the development of the perceptions
of hackers.
<P>
3. To determine the extent to which the hacker society poses as
a threat/risk environment and to examine their impact to electronic*
systems.
<P>
* The word 'electronic' is used as a blanket statement to cover
all the systems which are of interest to hackers. The author's
studies indicate that hackers are interested in a range of technical
targets; at one end of the scale, business information systems
(by far the highest percentage of interest) and at the other end
of the scale (for example), magnetic-stripe fare-tickets, typically
used for passenger rides on the underground rail links and the
Sydney Harbour ferries.
<P>
<B>1.3 OBJECTIVES</B>
<P>
The objectives of this research are:
<P>
to review the literature in the area of 'computer hacking';
<P>
to describe the 'hacker' environment;
<P>
to identify the characteristics of 'hackers', particularly with
respect to motivation;
<P>
to develop a model of hacker information processing;
<P>
to generate hypotheses with regard to the genesis, functions and
limits of hackers with particular respect to the threats/risks
which they pose;
<P>
to define the difference between a risk and a threat in this context;
<P>
to propose the components which constitute a threat;
<P>
to quantify the qualitative data collected about hackers into
risk/threat levels; and,
<P>
to propose methods to control the threats.
<P>
These objectives are addressed by observing hacker activity (through
computer communication), interviewing hackers and examining their
artifacts (the programs, notes, games, utilities etc., that they
develop). In particular, the artifacts are analysed to provide
a reflection of the hacker society and its complexity. These artifacts
also reflect the development of hackers, their intellectual ability,
knowledge base, level of sophistication and affective drives.
<P>
<B>1.4 SIGNIFICANCE OF THE STUDY</B>
<P>
An extensive research of existing literature on this subject,
indicates that, contrary to popular opinion, there has been little
formal or systematic research with respect to hackers. There are
many snippets of information which appear in the press which may
give the opinion that 'everyone knows about hackers': illegal
access to computer systems; theft of computer-time and information;
copyright infringements; sale of user access codes and passwords;
modification of operating systems; damage of data; the writing
of 'rogue code' (computer viruses, worms etc.); credit card fraud;
'fone phreaking'; trading in subversive, terrorist information
and pornography. (James and Chantler 1994) However, these are
the 'end products' and their appearance in the majority of articles
that label perpetrators of an alleged computer crime, do not give
any insight or understanding into the 'world' or culture of hackers.
<P>
The study reported in this thesis addresses the gap in the research
by providing a thorough and systematic study of hackers. It describes
the 'world' of the hackers, their culture, characteristics, thinking
in terms of information processing, and their motivation. No previous
study has been traced to date that has interviewed hackers or
utilised observations and examined their artifacts in relation
to the points above. Hence the study is significant because of
its innovation.
<P>
By the nature of their activities, some hackers can represent
a threat to those aspects of government and the corporate sector
that deal with the protection of computer systems and the security
of information. There are many technological solutions to combat
these threats, to protect individuals and organisations. These
solutions are available from security specialists, consultants
and the suppliers of the information-technology hardware. Most
are costly, time-consuming and can become an irritation in the
day-to-day management of such systems (James and Chantler 1993).
The continued 'explosion' in numbers of PCs throughout society,
suggests that there is a growth in computer literacy, and with
it an increasing number of hackers within society. Rather than
following a 'treat the symptom' approach to security breaches
by spontaneously 'grabbing' at solutions from security specialists
(as mentioned above), it is more efficient to 'treat the cause'.
Hemmel (1994) stated in his opening address of a recent Security
Research Symposium, that 'Security begins with society; society
can be reached through education'. It would appear that another
way to control the threat from hackers is to effect the growth
of hacker groups and their aspirations through education. For
instance, approaches such as introducing 'ethics' into computer
classes, or ensuring that educators and educational practices
are ethically based, could create a greater responsibility amongst
students of information-technology. Therefore, this study is significant
because its results may assist in addressing the current problems
that exist for national and corporate security, the theft and
damage of information and aspects relating to the Privacy/Freedom
of Information Acts, which Chantler has previously mentioned in
reports to the government (Chantler 1988a, 1989, 1990a, 1991a,
1992b).
<P>
The author of this thesis is in a unique situation to be able
to research hackers. He was formerly the head of computer security
for the Australian Army. (The relevance of mentioning this precise
position is that computer hackers show an attraction for military
sites. Accordingly the author is well-placed to be within an environment
that is 'rich' for hacker connections.) He is now in the Army
Reserve and still directly involved with computer security. In
these positions, he has been able to have access to computer-to-computer
communications between hackers. He has formed relationships with
twenty-three confirmed hackers (Chantler 1992c). He has also gained
insight into understanding the hacker from earlier research involved
with his Army Intelligence positions, which has been presented
in various ABC radio and television interviews (Chantler 1990b,
1991b, 1992d, 1993a,b,c, 1994a,b,c,d). Hence, the credentials
of the author and researcher also add significance to this study.
<P>
In summary, this study is important through its contribution to
information systems security and business security management,
together with contributions in varying degrees, to a wider range
of fields (education, criminology, psychology, sociology and information
technology). Specifically,
<P>
it provides the first comprehensive description of hackers and
their environment based on formal research;
<P>
it provides a model of the genesis of hackers (i.e., what internal
and external aspects of an individual's life impact on their development
as a hacker);
<P>
it identifies the characteristics of 'hackers', particularly with
respect to motivation;
<P>
it proposes a model of hacker information processing;
<P>
it identifies their functions and their limits with respect to
the threats/risks which they pose;
<P>
it identifies a list of hacker 'targets' - assets vulnerable to
hacker attack;
<P>
it defines the difference between a risk and a threat (in this
context), and also proposes the components which constitute a
threat;
<P>
it identifies a categorisation of the types of hackers based on
their functions and limits;
<P>
it proposes a method of quantifying qualitative data about hackers
into risk/threat levels for use in security assessments of information
technology environments, with proposals on providing a better
control over the threats;
<P>
it describes the hacker 'nether world', often referred to as Cyberspace;
<P>
it proposes a 'model of motivation' for educators to enable positive
components of hacker motivation to be transferred into other subject
areas (the author's previous research found hackers to be highly
motivated, to the extent of bordering on becoming obsessed with
their 'hack' task); and,
<P>
it provides information technology educators with a greater awareness
of the need for a focus on teaching the ethical use of computers,
personal standards and responsible role models.
<P>
<B>1.5 OUTLINE OF THE CHAPTERS</B>
<P>
<B>1.5.1 Chapter 1 - An Introduction to The Study - The Concept
of Hacking</B>
<P>
The focus of the study is broadly described, the purposes and
significance of the study delineated, and the structure of the
report overviewed. This chapter, also conceptualises and defines
hacking. This is done by considering the historical development
and conceptualisation of hacking in symbiosis with the development
of computer technology. The current literature's descriptions
of hacking, the players who are involved in hacking (hackers,
security people, etc.), and the groups into which hackers have
been divided are then described. This follows with a list of perceived
threats and examples of the dangers which hackers pose to the
technological world In other words, the world of hacking is conceptualised
in this chapter.
<P>
<B>1.5.2 Chapter 2 - Literature Review</B>
<P>
The literature about hackers is reviewed to determine specific
areas for consideration in this research (e.g. scope of knowledge,
motivation, information processing, education, modus operandi,
etc.). Hacker types are identified along with various traits and
conceptions. Initial categories and models are developed. Hacking
as a compulsion is noted to other addictive behaviours, e.g.,
alcoholism and drugs. Finally, implications for the study are
drawn from the literature.
<P>
<B>1.5.3 Chapter 3 - Research Design</B>
<P>
The research methodology is described in detail and the reasons
for selecting a qualitative study and an ethnographic approach
are presented. Factors detailing how the hacker 'tribe', as an
ethnographic case study, is different from traditional form, e.g.,
studies of social constructs such as schools or street gangs,
are also addressed. The hackers and the other stakeholders are
the subjects of this research. Observations, surveys, interviews
and artifact analysis form the instruments; whilst the procedures
and analysis of data may be described as conventional in keeping
with qualitative research design. There is also an element of
quantitative research used in this program. This relates to using
conventional statistical analysis in the quantification of qualitative
data with respect to the level of threats posed by hackers.
<P>
<B>1.5.4 Chapter 4 - Observations</B>
<P>
The behaviours observed are described. These include computer
to computer 'live' communications and BBS (bulletin-board systems)
messages and communications. Inferences are drawn from these observations
in terms of knowledge, information processing, motivation and
threats .
<P>
<B>1.5.5 Chapter 5 - Surveys and Interviews</B>
<P>
Results of the surveys and the interviews conducted with hackers
and stakeholders are described. The development of the surveys
and interviews scripts are described and the form, structure and
content of each survey and interview are defended. The results
are discussed, with reference being made to specific survey responses
and interviews, and then the hacker survey and interview responses
are compared and contrasted with the non-hacker stakeholder interview
responses. The results are collated and displayed in tables. Commonalities
are identified to assist with analysis of certain categorisations
(e.g. knowledge and motivation).
<P>
<B>1.5.6 Chapter 6 - Artifacts</B>
<P>
The range of hacker artifacts is described and analysed for the
knowledge, the information processing and the motivation that
lies behind them.
<P>
The artifacts include:
<P>
computer programs, challenges and tests;
<P>
electronic (underground) magazines;
<P>
conventional (printed) hacker magazines (e.g. '2600', 'TAP');
<P>
notes, communications and messages;
<P>
rogue codes;
<P>
pornography;
<P>
virtual reality;
<P>
technical information on: explosives, anarchy, fone phreaking,
and 'sensitive information';
<P>
new languages, slang, and hieroglyphics.
<P>
The outcomes will provide evidence to further support, or dispel
the facts which emerge from the observations and surveys for comparison
with the findings in the literature review. Details of aspects
that address the notion of 'cyberspace' will also be collected
to define and clarify the term 'cyberspace' from the hacker viewpoint.
<P>
<B>1.5.7 Chapter 7 - Cyberspace, The Computer Underworld</B>
<P>
The notion of 'cyberspace' is investigated and the particular
'cyberspace' inhabited by the hackers of this study is described.
(This term 'cyberspace' often appears to become confused when
presented in the press. This is because of the inaccurate definitions
and the close associations which the term has with 'the information
superhighway', 'internet', 'cybernetics' and 'virtual reality'.)
The reason for including this chapter in the thesis is based on
the perceived connection between hackers and 'cyberspace' which
seems to be repeatedly presented in the popular press.
<P>
<B>1.5.8 Chapter 8 - Risks &amp; Threats: Application of Hacker
Attributes into Risk</B>
<P>
<B>Assessment Security Surveys</B> 
<P>
This chapter discusses risks and threats, and how they differ.
The components of a threat, along with a methodology to transform
the qualitative hacker data into a quantitative form, are presented
for inclusion into existing security survey methodologies. Suggestions
are also made to address the various threats which hackers pose.
<P>
<B>1.5.9 Chapter 9 - Conclusions, Limitations and Implications
</B>
<P>
Conclusions are described and the limitations of the study and
its implications for further research are delineated. Implications
are also proposed for handling hackers in terms of security. This
chapter summarises what research was conducted, what was found,
what the implications are, and future directions.
<P>
The results from each of the chapters: 5, 6, 7, 8 and 9 are further
analysed, discussed and compared with each other, along with data
from the literature.
<P>
<B>1.6 THE HACKING CONCEPT AND THREAT</B>
<P>
<B>1.6.1 The Origin of Hacking</B>
<P>
The term 'computer hacking' originates in 1958. The first description,
that shows a link between technology and hacking, is found in
Stephen Levy's book <I>Computer Hackers: Heroes of the Computer
Revolution</I> (Levy 1984). Levy describes a student called Peter
Samson who is in his freshman year at the Massachusetts Institute
of Technology (MIT) in 1958-59. The student is depicted wandering
along the labyrinth of laboratories and storerooms in building
26 when he discovers the EAM room (Electronic Accounting Machinery),
'a room that housed machines which ran like computers'.
<P>
Peter Samson is also a member of the Technical Model Railroad
Club (TMRC). He, and others, have a thirst for knowledge to know
how electro-mechanical machines work. They are much more interested
in what goes on under the model train set, than what is above
it. There are plenty of other people in the TMRC who are much
more interested in what is above, on the tables; the exactness
of the scenery, the perfection in art and historical replicas.
Underneath, there are the neat regimental lines of switches, regular
rows of relays and long rambling tangles of wire. Here is a classic
example, perhaps for the first time, where we see people from
the Arts and the Sciences being drawn together by a common technological
interest.
<P>
Levy (1984) continues to describe how Samson and his friends are
intrigued by a keypunch machine in the EAM room. The keypunch
machine punches holes into cards for the 'hulking giant' on the
first floor, an IBM 704 computer. It can also read and sort cards
and print a listing. The control of this machine can be changed
by wiring up a plugboard, a small plastic square with a mass of
holes in it. By putting hundreds of wires into it, in a certain
order, it is possible to change the machine's characteristics.
It could be made to do whatever you want it to do.
<P>
The same thing is true of the TMRC. The Signals and Power sub-committee,
of which Samson is a member, are continually improving, revamping,
perfecting and sometimes 'gronking' (in club jargon, screwing-up)
the workings under the display. When a piece of equipment isn't
working, it is 'losing'; when a piece of equipment is ruined it
is 'munged'; and a project undertaken or a product built not solely
to fulfil some productive goal, but with some wild pleasure taken
in mere fulfilment is called a 'hack'
<P>
While someone might call a clever connection between relays a
'mere hack', it would be understood that to qualify as a hack,
the feat must be imbued with innovation, style, and technical
virtuosity. Even though one might say he is 'hacking away at the
system' (much as an axe-wielder hacks at logs), the artistry with
which one hacked was recognised to be considerable. The most productive
people working on the Signals and Power called themselves 'hackers'
with pride. This often took long hours of dedication, almost to
the extent of being seen as an addiction. It is interesting to
note the term hacker is derived from the word 'hackney', which
means drudgery, 'hackneyed' means 'worn out from overuse'. An
old worn out horse is defined as a 'hack' (Schwartau 1994).
<P>
Thus the adoption of the word 'hack', over thirty years ago, has
now evolved to 'hackers' and 'hacking'.
<P>
<B>1.6.2 Hacking as a Developing Culture</B>
<P>
It has been suggested by Bowcott and Hamilton (1990) that Charles
Babbage, the nineteenth-century English mathematician, was arguably
the first hacker, using the term in its computer sense. He devised
principles and constructed working models which were accepted
as the forerunners of the modern computing machines. Babbage set
out a series of definitions of a machine which would take the
drudgery out of mathematical calculation and eventually, he hoped,
improve on human accuracy. His work was encouraged and supported
by Lady Ada Lovelace, the poet Byron's daughter and a contemporary
mathematician often described as the world's first programmer.
(As a tribute to her, the name Ada was later used for a defence
computer programming language developed in the 1960s.)
<P>
The <B>first generation</B> of computers in the 1940s, that we
have come to accept as the forerunners of the computers of today,
operated on thermionic valves or vacuum-tubes. The <B>second generation
</B> used transistor based technology. The <B>third generation
</B> relied on ICs (integrated circuits), also called silicon
'chips'. The <B>fourth generation</B> computers of today, are
using new technologies where more and more circuitry is being
squeezed onto the 'chip', VLSI, (very large scale integration).
<P>
Just as computer technology has developed, to become more and
more sophisticated, so too have hackers. The first hackers appeared
with the second generation computers. They were intimately connected
with the development of computers, either by research or directly
to a firm, for they were the privileged few who studied and worked
within this new world of high technology (Levy 1984, p7). Today,
few hackers have any commercial connection to a computer industry
(Simmonds 1993, p16).
<P>
The first hackers were 'die-hards' and were committed to advancing
technology. They are still with us today and are considered as
the 'High Priests' of hackers. Similarly, there were two other
'classes' or types of hackers that match the third and fourth
'generations' of computers. Consequently, hacker culture has developed
from those early days of 'isolated gurus' into a sophisticated
network that reflects its own culture within society.
<P>
Clough and Mungo (1992) describe the hacker culture in terms of
the development of different generations. The first generation
hackers were based on the East Coast of America, developing software;
the second-generation, 1970s hackers were on the West Coast, developing
hardware. The next generation, the third, was based both in North
America and Europe. These were young adolescents, mostly males,
who had inherited technology's 'gift' of the personal computer
and were copying and selling the first computer games. Their motivations
were described as being 'often a fast buck, and their instincts
entirely commercial'. The fourth generation, had inherited a world
in which technology was rapidly converging around the new standard-bearer,
the IBM PC. This new generation shared the same 'obsessions' as
their predecessors, but now they took 'hacking', previously an
'honourable trade', and made it into a form of breaking and entering.
The higher principles of hackers were summed up in a draft declaration
prepared at a national hacker meeting (the 'Galactic Hacker Party')
and circulated among delegates for their signatures; it stated
that the free and unfettered flow of information is an essential
part of fundamental liberties, and shall be upheld in all circumstances,
computer technology shall not be used by government and corporate
bodies to control and oppress the people.
<P>
Stang and Moon (1993, p196) propose that the hacker culture is
not just a single group united in motive and mission;, for they
consist of the following subgroups:
<UL>
<LI>Hackers; devoted to breaking into and exploring mainframes.
<LI>Phreaks; specialising in mastering the telephone system.
<LI>Codes kids; who run code snatching programs, looking for calling
card and PBX numbers.
<LI>Cybercrooks; criminals who have learned computing to steal
cash any way they can.
<LI>Wares dudes; specialising in collecting and trading in pirated
software.
</UL>

<P>
The future should bring about even more complex changes within
hacker culture. The expansion of the mind through the use of computers
is becoming more apparent than ever before. People now see computers
as an opportunity to link their ideas and interests to their imagination,
particularly with VR (virtual reality). This 'science fiction'
perspective sees the application of new technology as creating
new realms. (This aspect will be addressed later in greater detail;
see Chapter 7 on Cyberspace.)
<P>
In the 1990s, PCs are more commonplace and hackers are becoming
younger. As Bowcott and Hamilton (1990, p43) have stated, young
hackers are 'Kids with PCs no longer but hackers worth their salt
with intelligence data and a copy of the <I>Unix System V</I>book
beside them ... The development of technology has fed imaginative
minds ...'.
<P>
<B>Figure 1.1</B> indicates <I>The Development of Hacker Culture
</I>, and provides a graphical representation on the development
of the hacker culture. It presents a conceptual model of the phenomena
of the hacker culture based on the expansion of the 'areas of
interest to hackers'. This is shown in relation to a time-line
with the development of computer technology, showing the different
generations of computers, as previously mentioned. As technology
has developed, it has given birth to the phenomena of hackers.
As it continues to expand, so does the opportunity to increase
the scope of topics that are of interest to hackers. (The 'areas
of interest' to hackers are the result of previous work completed
by the author. This work consisted of a study where all the areas
of study were considered for each of the time-slots 1958, 1973,
1978 and 1994.)
<P>
The first computer crime is presented on the time-scale at 1973.
This was a fraud case in America where a computer was used illegally
to generate a large number of bogus accounts. It was considered
that the crime could not have been committed without the use of
a computer and therefore it became known as the first 'computer-crime'.
<P>
It is open to conjecture as to whether this was really 'the first
computer-crime' particularly if we consider some of the elements
that we now believe constitute a computer-crime; <I>viz</I> eavesdropping,
intrusion into computer information systems, theft of data, espionage,
sabotage, decoding of encrypted data, etc. In this light, it could
be argued that an 'acceptable' form of 'computer crime' has been
with us long before 1973.
<P>
From the 1940s to the present day, governments have used computers
for eavesdropping and code-breaking. Recently (Rhodes 1995) there
is the sanctioned use of internet by the American CIA and DIA
(Defense Intelligence Agency). So why is gaining unauthorised
entry by intelligence agencies not a crime? 1955 1960 1970 1980
1990 2000
<P>
