&#169; N. Chantler 1995
<P>
<U><B>Figure 1.1 The Development of Hacker Culture</B></U>
<P>
Perhaps this is because it is not an individual <I>per se</I>,
but rather a department or organisation which has the appropriate
sanctions. This aspect will not be considered further, on the
basis that it is a nation's right to decide what is ethical and
what constitutes a crime. Therefore, given that hacking is not
necessarily 'criminal' but merely innovative, crime in this context
reflects the 'laws in force' in the countries where hackers exist.
<P>
<B>1.6.3 Hacking Defined</B>
<P>
Early descriptions of hacking are considered to be the results
of innovative enthusiastic people who explore technology. In the
1960s and 1970s they were not always linked to computers. 'Hacking
also meant anything either particularly clever or particularly
wacky, with or without a computer, as long as the manipulation
of a complex system was involved' (Hafner &amp; Markoff 1991,
p11).
<P>
In 1958 (Levy 1984) hacking was considered to be innovative and
a positive force in computing; hackers were 'heroes'. This view
has remained to some extent, as can be seen in the status given
hackers in contemporary films such as <I>War-Games</I> (1983),
<I>Prime Risk</I> (1984), <I>Sneakers</I> (1992) and more recently
<I>The Net</I> (1995). However, in the 1980s, hacking became linked
to crime (even though the first recorded incident of computer
fraud occurred in 1973, it was not linked to hacking). The press
used it to define 'password pirates and electronic burglars'.
As a result, the public's perception of hackers were no longer
seen as benign explorers, but 'malicious intruders' (Hafner &amp;
Markoff 1991, p12).
<P>
Recent statements from around the world have defined hacking as:
<P>
'to scan files containing confidential information and ex-directory
telephone numbers ... to hack into military systems, credit companies'
records and university files' (Press Association 1994, p3);
<P>
'causing losses of billions of dollars from telephone toll fraud
and theft of telephone services through company PABXs, and causing
expensive litigation in disputes between telephone companies and
their customer over who is to pay for the stolen services ...
engaging in piracy of commercial software products and computer
games causing losses on a similar scale. Credit card numbers are
stolen, traded, and used for fraudulent telemarketing purchases.'
(Parker 1993, p1);
<P>
'branching out into producing and distributing contraband literature'
(Simmonds 1993, p16);
<P>
'running-up bills worth thousands of dollars...known as phreaking
... sending codes to telephone exchanges which are recognised
as legitimate.' (Giles and Clayton 1993, p31); and
<P>
'to gain unauthorised entry ... infiltrated secret American FBI
and NASA computer data.' (Dibben 1993, p15).
<P>
All of the activities, within these recent statements, are defined
as illegal or criminal acts. Throughout the progression and development
of the hacker culture, there appears to be an underlying and increasing
fascination with 'forbidden areas' that link into the 'dark' side
of our society.
<P>
<B>1.6.4 Threat Metamorphosis and Future Threats</B>
<P>
Initially, it seems that hackers were secretly admired for their
exploits, particularly where some ingenuity was displayed at overcoming
the defences of the multi-national or government organisations.
It now seems that hackers have progressed from a 'fun' stage through
a 'nuisance' phase, a vandalism phase, and are now perhaps moving
towards the more sinister role of corporate crime and information
warfare.
<P>
A recent typical indicator of this point was the front page headlines
of the British newspaper <I>The Independent</I> on 24th November
1994 (Kelsey 1994), which read 'Revealed: how hacker penetrated
the heart of British Intelligence'. The article, which continued
on pages 2 and 3, describes how a hacker broke into British Telecom's
(BTs) main database and copied telephone numbers and addresses
of 'MI6, MI5, many secret Ministry of Defence installations and
other very sensitive information.' (telephone numbers of the royal
family, politicians, secret US installations in the UK). 'one
of the most serious breaches of national security in recent years'
The thousands of pages which were copied were then sent out on
Internet, a global network of computers, to which any one of 35
million users would 'potentially have access'. The article then
describes how it was able to verify that the information was bona
fide, and quotes one of Britain's leading computer security experts
as saying that 'it is the most serious breach of computer security
I have ever heard of.'
<P>
In this instance it is interesting to note that the article also
says 'the information was copied by the hacker without any special
technical expertise'; and from the information collected that:
<P>
'MI5 phone bills are being paid by the Home Office not the Ministry
of Defence';
<P>
One MI5 location is described as 'shoe shops' and another as 'textile
warehouse';
<P>
'The MI6 training establishment, 'school for spies' , sits next
to a pub in a nondescript building on a busy street in South London.'
<P>
One gets the feeling that again the journalist reporting this
incident is capitalising on a good story; it therefore follows
with the question, 'then just how reliable is it?'. The background
and grass-roots of this story are that a computer enthusiast (Steve
Fleming), who uses Internet, posted an electronic message (e-mail)
to other enthusiasts to confirm or deny the activities of hackers.
A hacker found lax security on British Telecom's computer system
and copied some information, sent it to Steve Fleming and another
sensational hacker story was born.
<P>
Some critical points emerge from this example:
<P>
it appears that hackers may be induced into sensationalism by
the press;
<P>
it was an easy penetration of a government computer system by
the hacker;
<P>
the hacker capitalised on lax security procedures;
<P>
the hacker does not appear to have had a more sinister motive;
<P>
the hacker is a thrill-seeker looking for a challenge, a way to
prove themselves, but never-the-less is basically 'honest';
<P>
the hacker did not 'rush in' or make an opportunist snatch at
data; this was a planned attack; and,
<P>
it seems that it was the computer enthusiast, with a link to journalism,
who conducted a crude analysis of the information received.
<P>
Further aspects dealing with these points will be covered later
in this research.
<P>
<B>1.6.5 The Players and the Hacker Domain</B>
<P>
With the increasing numbers of people who use computers, it seems
that there are a greater number that are being 'drawn' into hacking.
For this description of the flow and migration of people into
'Hackerdom' (the hacker domain), it is possible to categorise
hackers into two groups: the '<I>Malhacks'</I>, representing 'the
hackers of today' - the 'bad hackers'. These can be seen to be
distinct from the purist hackers typified by those of the 1960s
and 1970s, called the '<I>Bonhacks</I>', representing the 'good
hackers'. This conception of growth in the hacking community is
presented in the following <B>Figure 1.2</B> <I>The Growth of
Hackerdom,</I> which shows a proposal for the evolutionary lines
and migration of PC users into 'Hackerdom'.
<P>
The different thickness in arrows represents the numbers of people
involved. A thick arrow indicates <I>many</I>, a thin one <I>few
</I>. It can be seen, that since the mid 1970s, there has been
an increase in the number of PC Users, some of whom have entered
Hackerdom, with the majority of them joining the <I>Malhacks</I>and
a few becoming <I>Bonhacks</I>. This does not imply that these
groups are 'static', for it seems that there is a continual entry
and exit migration which occurs, albeit small.
<P>
<U><B>The Evolutionary Lines and Migration into Hackerdom</B>
</U>
<P>
 2000
<P>
1990
<P>
1980
<P>
T
<P>
I
<P>
M <B>Bonhacks Malhacks</B>
<P>
E <B>PC Users</B>
<P>
 1970
<P>
<I><B>Note:</B> the difference in thickness of</I>
<P>
 1960 <I>arrows signifies differences of numbers</I>
<P>
<I>of people involved; i.e. a thick arrow is</I>
<P>
<B>Original Hackers </B><I>many people, a thin arrow is a few.
</I>
<P>
 1950
<P>
<I><B>HACKERDOM</B></I>
<P>
&#169; N. Chantler 1995
<P>
<U><B>Figure 1.2 The Growth of Hackerdom</B></U>
<P>
Within the realm of hackers, a survey based on 284 reports of
hacking, Chantler (1993d), showed that there are three main groups
of people (<B>Figure 1.3</B>.) involved within the hacker's domain
<I>Students:; Criminals</I>; and <I>Others</I>. The <I>Students
</I>included people from primary, secondary, tertiary and other
educational environments. In the context of the survey, a <I>Criminal
</I>was identified as person who had been found guilty of 'the
crime' and who was clearly only interested in pecuniary gain.
<I>Others</I> covered a wide range of other people who were all
involved with these incidents, but were of a much smaller percentage
to be considered on their own, e.g. computer-security specialists,
information system administrators, law-enforcement personnel,
journalists and authors).
<P>
It could be argued that journalists and authors should be distinctly
identified here, for they often seem to have a high impact in
the involvement with hackers. However, because of their small
numbers they have been grouped with <I>others</I>.
<P>
<B>STUDENTS CRIMINALS</B>
<P>
<B>OTHERS</B>
<P>
<U><B>Figure 1.3. The Main Groups of People within the Hacker
Domain</B></U>
<P>
It is interesting to note that this grouping is not static. For
example, Chantler (1993d) found that students may move from within
the student 'circle' into the criminal 'circle', while others
may have a 'foot in each camp', etc.. <HR>

<P>
<U><B>Figure 1.4. Player Percentages</B></U>
<P>
The 'Player' percentages (<B>Figure 1.4</B>.) are taken from the
same source (Chantler 1993d). The survey was based on the reports
of hacking incidents and who was involved. This covered the period
from March 1991 to March 1993. It is important to appreciate that
these percentages are based only on the reported events. It must
therefore be considered that this may prevent a distorted view,
based on the idea that more is known about 'student' hacking than
is known about 'criminal' hacking.
<P>
<B>1.6.6 Implications</B>
<P>
The contemporary world is increasingly reliant computers and information
systems. It is logical to accept that with more computers, there
will be a corresponding growth in computer literacy, a continual
growth in hacker numbers and therefore a continued growth in the
threats to these systems. It would appear, based on the majority
of press reports, that students become major players in the hacker
domain; this is of concern. This is particularly so, when considering
that the majority of hackers seem to commit illegal or criminal
acts. Is this a reflection of the education that we give them?
Why do they find 'forbidden areas' of knowledge so interesting?
Do we address ethics within information-technology education?
These points, and others, are addressed within the bounds of this
research. 
<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
