<!-- Article Body Table ---------------------------------------------->

<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<img border=0 width=43 height=43 src="../../images/prod.gif">
</td>
<td valign=middle width=440>
<center><h3>
Infowarrior Road Kit</h3>
 <h4>by Stephen Cobb
</h4>
</center>
 
<BR>

<BR>

October 31, 1996

<P>You've got your passport. You've got your airline tickets. You've got your
notebook. You're a high-tech road warrior, ready to take off and take on the
world. But do you have the Executive Notebook Computer Travel Kit? Without it,
or a similar collection of the bits and pieces contained therein, you
might not be able to power up, or jack in, when you arrive at destinations that don't
celebrate Independence Day on the 4th of July. 

<P>A surprising number of business people are still surprised to find that many
countries in the world don't use RJ-11 sockets to plug in phones and modems. 
And even though a lot of today's notebook computers automatically adjust to a wide
range of voltages, many countries don't dish up the juice in familiar U.S.
sockets. For business travelers whose laptop batteries need charging at least
daily, and for those who can't work without frequent email pickup and
delivery, the worldwide array of socket and plug combinations is a serious impediment. 

<P>Some have already adopted a piecemeal approach to the problem, buying country
specific adapters as needed. But this can be expensive if you have to
travel to more than a couple of countries. For example, at Fry's Electronics in Silicon
Valley you can buy adapters at $10-$15 per country, economical if you are only
going to one country, but costly if you are on a 7 country swing through the 
EC, where "community standards" is an oxymoron, at least when it comes to
electricity and telephones.

<P>Fortunately, there is a pretty comprehensive solution right around the
corner at the Computer City chain of stores (see <a href="www.computercity.com">www.computercity.com</a> for the store
nearest you or call 817 390 2700).

<P>They now sell something called the Executive Notebook Computer Travel Kit,
a neat zippered bag of tricks, custom made in
China for this retail division of Tandy Corp. Unzip the bag and you get
several compartments where adapters are grouped by region. You will find power plug
adapters for just about anywhere in the world, with a handy chart of voltages
for those who have 110 only devices (sorry, no power conversion, that
requires a separate transformer). 

<P>The Executive Notebook Computer Travel Kit includes country specific phone
adapters for Belgium, France, Germany (which requires 2 deceptively similar
versions), Italy, and Australia. These are all made so that you can unplug the
phone, then plug in the adapter, your modem, and the phone. There is also a UK
adapter that works in New Zealand as well, plus a selection of RJ-11 adapters
(in-line, line doubling) that should handle just about anything in Asia and
South America, not to mention older hotels in North America. A couple of phone
patch cords are also included, plus a compact parallel printer cable, which
ingeniously converts to a null modem cable. 

<P>At $49.95 for all this, the Executive Notebook Computer Travel Kit strikes
this particular traveler as a bargain. Successfully collecting my email from the
other side of the world still gives me a real rush. And it sure beats 
collapsing into a hotel room at the end of a long day's travel, only to find I can't
connect my laptop to anything useful. From now on I am going to pack this
particular bag on every trip.

<P>Stephen Cobb, CISSP, was born in Britain, has lived in four countries and
travelled to fifteen. He has also visited 47 of the 50 states that constitute
the country of which he is now a citizen.

<P>Mr. Cobb can be reached at: 72662.546@CompuServe.COM

</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
