<td valign=middle width=440>
<H3>
<CENTER>Information Warfare Training</CENTER>
</h3>



</Center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>

November 28, 1996<BR>
<BR>

<P>  Syracuse Research Corporation, is pleased to announce the next offering of
our three-day seminar "Implementing Information Warfare - A Course for the
Warrior". This seminar will be offered January 27-29, 1997 in San Antonio,
TX and again in late March 1997 in Washington DC. The 3-day IW Course is
followed by a two-day "Introduction to Radar" course which is complementary
to the IW course.

<P><B>The IW Course curriculum is as follows:</B></P>

<TABLE>
     <TR>
          <TD>Day 1:</TD>
          <TD>Information Warfare: A New Realm of Conflict?</TD>
     </TR>
     <TR>
          <TD></TD>
          <TD>RadioWave Characteristics</TD>
     </TR>
     <TR>
          <TD></TD>
          <TD>RadioWave Propagation</TD>
     </TR>
     <TR>
          <TD></TD>
          <TD>The Electromagnetic Spectrum</TD>
     </TR>
     <TR>
          <TD></TD>
          <TD>Electro-Optics/Infrared Principles</TD>
     </TR>
</TABLE>
<BR>

<TABLE>
     <TR>
          <TD>Day 2:</TD>
          <TD>Off-The-Air IW Technologies</TD>
     </TR>
     <TR>
          <TD></TD>
          <TD>C4I For The Warrior</TD>
     </TR>
     <TR>
          <TD></TD>
          <TD>Future Trends in Information Technologies</TD>
     </TR>
     <TR>
          <TD></TD>
          <TD> Intelligence, Surveillance, and Reconnaissance (ISR)</TD>
     </TR>
</TABLE>
<BR>
<TABLE>
     <TR>
          <TD>Day 3:</TD>
          <TD>Electronic Warfare (EW)</TD>
     </TR>
     <TR>
          <TD></TD>
          <TD>Command and Control Warfare (C2W)</TD>
     </TR>
     <TR>
          <TD></TD>
          <TD>Information Security</TD>
     </TR>
     <TR>
          <TD></TD>
          <TD>Information Warfare - Tying It All Together</TD>
     </TR>
</TABLE>

<BR>
<P><B>Instructors for the course are:</B>

<P>Col. Douglas Hotard, (USAF-retired), former Director for IW within the
Office of the Secretary of Defense and a founding father of the Air Force
Information Warfare Program. 

<P>Capt. Richard McCluskey (USN-retired), Cryptologist and former Director of
Training for the Naval Security Group and presently an advanced technologies
consultant to the Defense Airborne Reconnaissance Program.

<P>Chief Warrant Officer John Waller (USN-retired), Director Of Security and
Engineering Training at SRC.  Cyptologic officer with the Naval Security
Group for 21 years. Mr. Waller has been working in Intelligence and EW for
over 30 years including managing many projects for the DoD while on active
duty and at Syracuse Research.

<P>Mr. Eric Wagner, an experienced EW engineer, has been heavily involved in
the development and maintenance of national technical ELINT and EWIR
databases at SRC. Mr. Wagner is a recognized computer security expert and
has been a guest speaker at numerous security seminars.

<P>Anyone interested in attending the above courses should E-mail me at
<a href="MAILTO:waller@syrres.com">waller@syrres.com</a> or call me at (315) 426-3289.

<P>You can find additional information on our Information Warfare course to
include module descriptions and listings of viewgraphs that will be used in
the course on our web page at <a href="http://www.syrres.com/courses">http://www.syrres.com/courses</a>.</P>
