<td valign=middle width=440>
<H3>
<CENTER>TERRORISM/ANTITERRORISM information available from DTIC</CENTER>
</h3>



</Center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>

November 18, 1996<BR>
<BR>

<P>  ( Pricing Schedule at: <a href="http://www.dtic.mil/dtic/prices.html">http://www.dtic.mil/dtic/prices.html</a>)

<P>   The Defense Technical Information Center gathers, catalogs and makes
available literally millions of documents (classified and unclassified)
generated as a result of research, testing, development, training and
scholarship done by or sponsored by the Department of Defense. Many of these
documents deal with subjects likely to be of interest to listmembers here.
As a teaser I have included a relatively short list of documents on the
subjects of Terrorism/ Antiterrorism from the "Hot Topics" on the DTIC home
page at <a href="http://www.dtic.mil">http://www.dtic.mil</a>.

<P>   I am often surprised at the resources various individuals (myself most
definitely included) fail to use simply because they don't know these
treasures exist. DTIC is relatively high on the list of underutilized
(though I doubt the staff there think so) resources, and it definitely
counts as a treasure. If you knew about it already, good- if not, get busy.
Registration information is appended at the bottom of the list. Someone in
your organization (library, publications, etc.) may already have a DTIC
account you can share- ask around before you begin the registration process.</P>

Fred Fuller<BR>
Marquat Memorial Library<BR>
USAJFKSWCS<BR>
Ft. Bragg, NC<BR>


                           <B><CENTER> TERRORISM/ANTITERRORISM</CENTER></B><BR>
<BR>
1  OF  12<BR>
AD NUMBER:  A303663<BR>
CORPORATE AUTHOR:  NAVAL POSTGRADUATE SCHOOL MONTEREY CA<BR>
TITLE:  MOTIVATIONS FOR NUCLEAR TERRORISM IN THE UNITED STATES.<BR>
PERSONAL AUTHORS:  DIPAOLO, PETER J.<BR>
REPORT DATE:  JUN, 1995<BR>
PAGINATION:  134P  MEDIA COST:  $11.00<BR>
<P>REPORT CLASSIFICATION:  UNCLASSIFIED
<P>DESCRIPTORS:  *NUCLEAR WEAPONS, *TERRORISM, UNITED STATES,
  POLICIES, NATIONAL SECURITY, THESES, WESTERN SECURITY(INTERNATIONAL).
<P>IDENTIFIERS:  *NUCLEAR TERRORISM.
<P>ABSTRACT:  THE DEMISE OF BIPOLARITY CREATED NEW SECURITY CONCERNS
  FOR THE UNITED STATES. TERRORISM NOW THRIVES IN THE NEW WORLD
  ENVIRONMENT. WHILE MUCH HAS BEEN WRITTEN ON TERRORISM, THE SPECTER
  OF NUCLEAR TERRORISM IN THE UNITED STATES HAS RECEIVED LITTLE
  ATTENTION. NUCLEAR TERRORISM CANNOT BE LOOKED AT THROUGH THE
  TRADITIONAL NUCLEAR WEAPONS PARADIGM NOR CAN IT BE VIEWED WITHIN
  THE CONFINES OF THE TRADITIONAL TERRORISM PARADIGM. THERE CURRENTLY
  ARE TWO PERSPECTIVES ON NUCLEAR TERRORISM: THE OPTIMISTS, WHO DO
  NOT SEE IT AS A THREAT, AND THE PESSIMISTS, WHO SEE IT AS
  INEVITABLE. EACH VIEW HAS ITS MERITS BUT NEITHER ALONE CAN EXPLAIN
  THIS SECURITY CONCERN. MERGING OF THE TWO VIEWS IS REQUIRED TO
  UNDERSTAND THE MOTIVATIONAL CONSIDERATIONS BEHIND THIS POTENTIALLY
  HORRIFIC PROBLEM. A BRIEF HISTORY OF U.S. POLICIES ON NUCLEAR
  WEAPONS AND TERRORISM IS OFFERED TO EXPLAIN WHY THERE HAS NOT BEEN
  A U.S. POLICY ON NUCLEAR TERRORISM. THE POSSIBILITY OF NUCLEAR
  TERRORISM IS REAL. A BETTER UNDERSTANDING OF THE NUCLEAR TERRORIST
  MINDSET IS REQUIRED IF EFFECTIVE POLICIES ARE TO BE DEVELOPED.</P>
******<BR>
<BR>
