<BR>
10  OF  12<BR>
AD NUMBER:  A281896<BR>
CORPORATE AUTHOR:  AIR FORCE INST OF TECH WRIGHT-PATTERSON AFB OH<BR>
TITLE:  THE POLITICS OF COUNTERTERRORISM IN WESTERN EUROPE.<BR>
PERSONAL AUTHORS: HIGGINS, TRACY<BR>
REPORT DATE:  APR, 1994<BR>
PAGINATION:  95P  MEDIA COST:  $6.00<BR>
<P>REPORT CLASSIFICATION:  UNCLASSIFIED
<P>DESCRIPTORS:  *FOREIGN POLICY, *COUNTERTERRORISM, EUROPE, STRATEGY,
  INTERNATIONAL POLITICS, POLICE, BATTLES.
<P>ABSTRACT:  EUROPEAN NATIONS, THE VICTIMS OF LEFT AND RIGHT WING,
  SEPARATIST, AND TRANSNATIONAL TERRORISM, SHARE A DESIRE TO DETER
  TERRORIST VIOLENCE WITHIN THEIR OWN BORDERS. THIS PROVIDES AN
  INCENTIVE TO DEVELOP EFFECTIVE DOMESTIC COUNTERTERRORIST POLICIES
  AS WELL AS TO COORDINATE COUNTERTERRORISM PROGRAMS AMONG EUROPEAN
  NATIONS IN ORDER TO BE MORE EFFECTIVE IN THE PREVENTION OF
  TERRORIST VIOLENCE. SOME ATTEMPTS HAVE BEEN MADE TO IMPROVE POLICE
  AND JUDICIAL COOPERATION BOTH WITHIN THE EU AND INTERNATIONALLY,
  AND THIS HAS HAD A POSITIVE EFFECT ON COUNTERTERRORISM OPERATIONS.
  HOWEVER PROGRESS IN THE AREA OF COUNTERTERRORISM STRATEGY IN EUROPE
  CONTINUES TO BE UNSATISFACTORY AS IT IS STILL THE SOURCE OF
  INTERNAL POLICY BATTLES AND MANY DIPLOMATIC DISPUTES.</P>
******<BR>
<BR>
11  OF  12<BR>
AD NUMBER:  A279584<BR>
CORPORATE AUTHOR:  NAVAL WAR COLL NEWPORT RI DEPT OF OPERATIONS<BR>
<P>TITLE:  AMERICA'S MILITARY CRISIS-RESPONSE CAPABILITY: IS
  'ANYTIME-ANYPLACE' A REALISTIC EXPECTATION?</P>
PERSONAL AUTHORS:  O'BOYLE, THOMAS R.<BR>
REPORT DATE:  FEB 08, 1994<BR>
PAGINATION:  38P  MEDIA COST:  $6.00<BR>
<P>REPORT CLASSIFICATION:  UNCLASSIFIED
<P>DESCRIPTORS:  *INTELLIGENCE, *LEADERSHIP, *LESSONS LEARNED,
  *CRISIS MANAGEMENT, *MILITARY PLANNING, *COMMAND AND CONTROL
  SYSTEMS, *TERRORISM, *COUNTERMEASURES, *RAPID DEPLOYMENT,
  INTERDICTION, PLANNING, POLICIES, REFLECTION, RESPONSE, TERRORISTS,
  TRAINING, TRANSPORTATION, USSR, WARFARE, WINDOWS, DETERRENCE, USSR,
  MILITARY HISTORY.
<P>IDENTIFIERS:  SPECIAL OPERATIONS FORCES, MILITARY RESPONSIVENESS,
  FLEXIBILITY, FRENCH AND INDIAN WAR, MAYAGUEZ CRISIS, ACHILLE LAURO
  HIJACKING.
<P>ABSTRACT:  THE DISINTEGRATION OF THE SOVIET UNION AND THE
  DISENFRANCHISEMENT OF ITS FORMER SURROGATES, MAY INCREASE THE NEED
  FOR AN EFFECTIVE MILITARY DETERRENT TO COMBAT TERRORISM. A REVIEW
  OF ROGERS RANGERS DURING THE FRENCH & INDIAN WAR (THE FIRST USE OF
  CRISIS-RESPONSE TYPE FORCES IN 'AMERICA') IS USED FOR HISTORICAL
  REFLECTION. ROGERS INTERDICTED 'TERRORISTS' WITH GREAT STRATEGIC
  SUCCESS. THE KEY TO THEIR OPERATIONAL SUCCESS WAS: THE FLEXIBILITY,
  SPECIAL TRAINING, PRECISE PLANNING AND EXCELLENT LEADERSHIP. A
  COMPARISON OF THE MAYAGUEZ INCIDENT IN 1975 AND THE ACHILLE LAURO
  HIJACKING IN 1985, IS USED TO CHART THE DIRECTION OF U.S. CRISIS
  RESPONSE AFTER DESERT ONE. THE MAYAGUEZ, REPRESENTED AN AD HOC
  APPROACH USING THEATER BASED FORCES. THE ACHILLE LAURO, REPRESENTED
  A RELATIVELY MATURE APPROACH FOLLOWING LESSONS-LEARNED FROM DESERT
  ONE. BOTH THE MAYAGUEZ AND ACHILLE LAURO INCIDENTS REQUIRED SUCH A
  RAPID RESPONSE THAT POSITIONING A MILITARY FORCE (REGARDLESS OF
  TRAINING OR LOCATION) PROVED NEARLY IMPOSSIBLE. COMPLICATIONS
  INCLUDE HOST NATIONS SENSITIVITIES, LACK OF FLEXIBLE TRANSPORTATION,
  AND THE GROWING SOPHISTICATION OF TERRORISTS. INTELLIGENCE REMAINS
  THE KEY LIMITING FACTOR. CRISIS-RESPONSE FORCES MUST CONTINUE TO
  DEVELOP FAST, FLEXIBLE TRANSPORTATION, ACCESS TO TIMELY
  INTELLIGENCE AND CONCISE DETAILED PLANNING. THE HISTORICAL WINDOW
  FOR SUCCESS IS THE 5 TO 7 DAY POINT --NOT THE 48-60 HOUR WINDOW OF
  THE MAYAGUEZ OR ACHILLE LAURO. U.S. POLICY SHOULD LOOK TOWARDS THE
  INTERDICTION OF SUCH TERRORISTS AS ROGERS RANGERS DID ON THE
  AMERICAN FRONTIER.</P>
******<BR>
<BR>
12  OF  12<BR>
AD NUMBER:  A279369<BR>
CORPORATE AUTHOR:  NAVAL WAR COLL NEWPORT RI DEPT OF OPERATIONS<BR>
TITLE:  CONFLICT WITH LIBYA: USE OF MILITARY FORCE AGAINST TERRORISM.<BR>
PERSONAL AUTHORS:  CURRY, BRUCE H.<BR>
REPORT DATE:  FEB 08, 1994<BR>
PAGINATION:  31P  MEDIA COST:  $6.00<BR>
<P>REPORT CLASSIFICATION:  UNCLASSIFIED
<P>DESCRIPTORS:  *MILITARY FORCES(UNITED STATES), *MILITARY
  OPERATIONS, *MILITARY STRATEGY, *FOREIGN POLICY, *AIR STRIKES,
  *COUNTERTERRORISM, *LESSONS LEARNED, UNITED STATES, TACTICAL
  BOMBING, LIBYA, LOW INTENSITY CONFLICT, NATIONAL SECURITY,
  TERRORISM, MILITARY HISTORY.
<P>IDENTIFIERS:  MILITARY FORCE OPTIONS, NON-MILITARY OPTIONS,
  STRATEGIC GOALS, MILITARY RETALIATION, ATTAIN DOCUMENT OPERATION,
  ELDORADO CANYON OPERATION.
<P>ABSTRACT:  THE UNITED STATES ATTACK ON LIBYA ON APRIL 15, 1986 WAS
  THE CULMINATION OF A SERIES OF DEVELOPMENTS IN U.S. FOREIGN POLICY
  AND MILITARY STRATEGY INTENDED TO COMBAT INTERNATIONAL TERRORISM.
  IT WAS THE CULMINATION OF THE U.S. ATTEMPT TO USE BOTH NON-
  MILITARY AND MILITARY METHODS TO COMBAT TERRORISM. THIS PAPER
  EXAMINES THE USE OF MILITARY FORCE AS AN APPROPRIATE MEANS TO
  COMBAT TERRORISM. IN PARTICULAR, THE 1986 CONFLICT WITH LIBYA IS
  EXAMINED CONCENTRATING ON THE FOLLOWING ASPECTS: WHETHER
  OPERATIONAL LEVEL OBJECTIVES CONTRIBUTED TO ACHIEVEMENT OF
  STRATEGIC GOALS; AND THE USE OF MILITARY FORCE AS AN EFFECTIVE
  INSTRUMENT IN THE WAR AGAINST TERRORISM. THIS PAPER CONCLUDES THAT
  THE USE OF MILITARY FORCE (ALONG WITH THE EUROPEAN NON- MILITARY
  RESPONSES) WAS AN EFFECTIVE INSTRUMENT IN THE WAR AGAINST TERRORISM
  AS MEASURED BY THE DECREASE IN LIBYAN SPONSORED ATTACKS FROM 1986
  TO 1991. HOWEVER, THE U.S. ATTACK ON LIBYA IS STILL AN ISOLATED
  EVENT AND DOES NOT PROVIDE A SUFFICIENT BASIS FOR A DOCTRINE OF
  MILITARY RETALIATION AGAINST TERRORISM.


                       <P><B><CENTER>  REGISTERING WITH DTIC</CENTER></B>


<P><B>Who Can Register for DTIC Service?</B>

<P>   DTIC serves the Federal Government research, development and
   acquisition community including contractors, grantees, and potential
   defense contractors. Because of the nature of the information that
   DTIC handles, users must qualify for service from DTIC. Among those
   eligible to receive DTIC services are:

 <P>  * Department of Defense (DoD) organizations, their contractors, and
     potential contractors.

 <P>  * U.S. Government organizations and their contractors.

<P>   * Universities involved in federally funded research throughout the U.S.

<P>   Although organizations register for service from DTIC, individuals in
   the agencies are the actual users. These include engineers,
   scientists, managers, administrators of research efforts, program
   planners, acquisition specialists and information intermediaries.


<P><B>DTIC's Registration Process</B>

<P>  To register for DTIC service, everyone must complete a DD Form
   1540--Registration for Scientific and Technical Information Services.
   Non-DoD Government agencies and their contractors should contact
   DTIC's Registration Branch for a complete registration kit. Users with
   Perform Pro/FormFlow software can download an electronic version of
   the DD Form 1540 from: http://web1.whs.osd.mil/icdhome/DDEFORMS.HTM

 <P>  If you are a contractor and want to receive export-controlled
   information, you must also complete DD Form 2345-- Militarily Critical
   Technical Data Agreement. An electronic version of this form is also
   available for download from:
   <a href="http://web1.whs.osd.mil/icdhome/DDEFORMS.HTM">http://web1.whs.osd.mil/icdhome/DDEFORMS.HTM</a>

<P>   NOTE: If you are employed by a DoD organization requiring unclassified
   information only, you do not need to complete the above forms. If you
   are employed by a Non-DoD Government organization requiring
   unclassified/unlimited information only, you do not need to complete
   the above forms. Simply contact DTIC's Registration Branch at the
   number indicated below.


<P><B>How Can I Become a Registered DTIC User?</B>

<P>   You may request a registration packet with the necessary forms and
   information about DTIC products and services through a registration
   request form or by contacting:</P>

     Defense Technical Information Center<BR>
     Registration Branch (DTIC-BCS)<BR>
     8725 John J. Kingman Road, Suite 0944<BR>
     Ft. Belvoir, VA 22060-6128<BR>
<BR>
     Telephone: Commercial (703) 767-8273 / DSN 427-8273<BR>
     Toll Free: 1-800-CAL-DTIC (225-3842), menu selection 2<BR>
     FAX: Commercial (703) 767-8274 / DSN 427-8274<BR>
     Email: <a href="MAILTO:reghelp@dtic.mil">reghelp@dtic.mil</a><BR>


<P>Fee For Service

<P>   While registering with DTIC is free, DTIC does charge for many of its
   products and services. For a complete listing of prices, see DTIC's


<P>Thanks to grp-lib1@soc.mil (Mr. Fred L. Fuller)  for submitting this.</P>


