<td valign=middle width=440>
<H3>
<CENTER> The GulfLINK Files </CENTER>
</h3>



</Center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>

November 04, 1996<BR>
<BR>

<P>We know this isn't exactly an infowar issue - or is it? Please do let us know by 
posting your responses to <a href="MAILTO:infowar@infowar.com">infowar@infowar.com</a>

<P>We were asked to help out Insignia Publishing Company who originally brought 
these now unclassified files to light. For reasons, and by persons unknown, 
Insignia Publishing was hacked on November 1, 1996 and all of the files and 
orders for the book "Gassed in the Gulf: An Insider's View of the DoD-CIA 
Cover-up of Gulf War Syndrome,"  by Patrick G. Eddington were erased. 

<P>The book is currently under CIA review. Orders are being taken in prepublication 
mode.  Call 800-606-BOOK (2665).  The  URL for Insignia is  
<a href="http://www.insigniausa.com/">http://www.insigniausa.com/</a>
The site has been restored.  </P>

<h4>Background history, GulfLINK files by Bruce W. Kletz, Insignia Publishing : </h4>

<P>On July 19, 1995 The Department of Defense posted numerous files in its GulfLINK 
Website. On November 3, 1995 Paul F. Wallner, Staff Director, Senior Level 
Oversight Panel, Persian Gulf War Veterans' Illnesses, wrote a memo ordering the 
flagging of "potential sensitive reports or documents on GulfLINK. . . .to begin 
preparation of a response on particular 'bombshell' reports." To view this memo 
click here: <a href="Wallner.html-ssi">Wallner Memorandum.</a>

<P>On February 8, 1996, DoD removed 308 files claiming that the files must undergo 
rigorous review for classified information despite their earlier electronic 
publication. Under pressure from veterans groups and the raised visibility of 
front page coverage in the New York Times, DoD returned 88 of these files to the 
website on August 30, 1996. The rest of the missing GulfLINK files remain hidden 
behind vague claims of national security.

<P> All 308 of these files are republished here. The files are presented here as 
they were on the GulfLINK website. The cryptic file names make it difficult for 
first time perusers to navigate the collection, however, <a href="gulflink.txt">partial document titles</a>
are provided to provide some relief. Those files returned to the DoD GulfLINK 
website are marked with an asterisk.

<P>Infowar.Com thanks Mr. Kletz and Insignia Publishing for their permission to 
mirror and offer these files. Their website offers the files for MAC.

<a href="gulflink.exe">Download 480K file.</a>


