<IMG ALT="[Bomb2]" SRC="../../images/bomb2_li.gif" width=580><p>


<!-- Article Body Table ---------------------------------------------->

<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<img border=0 width=43 height=43 src="../../images/question.gif">
</td>
<td valign=middle width=440>
<center><h2>
CIABASE

</h2>


</Center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>

<P>   CIABASE is a computer data base on the Central Intelligence
Agency that provides a vital, easy-to-use, historical resource for
policy makers, academicians, journalists, activists, and students.</P>

<P>   CIABASE consists of ten plus megabytes of data, divided into 100+
categories containing over 33,000 annotated and sourced entries,
for hard disk IBM compatible and MACINTOSH personal computers.</P>

 <P>  CIABASE provides data on the CIA and other individual or
organizational entities, from information gleaned from 850+
sources of various political ideologies -- congressional
reports, newspapers, and magazines, including more than 500
books.

<P>   CIABASE provides rapid access to specific data, scanning in
seconds the entire collection for word, or word-combinations, plus
date requests; e.g."Covert Action" "China" "94-95," or, "Domestic
Operations," "96." Results can be displayed, printed, or sent to
user-named files for editing or transmitting.

Users comments:

<P>   Professor of intelligence at American University, and formerly
Commandant of the the Defense Intelligence College, John Macartney,
said "CIABASE remains a one-of-a-kind, extraordinary resource for
serious scholars, journalists, and researchers, regardless of their
political leanings and research interests...there are no alternates
out there. If there were, they would undoubtedly sell for thousands
of dollars....I am in awe of the massive effort....in short I have
found CIABASE invaluable, indeed indispensable..."
Dr. John Macartney, American University.

<P>   "An outstanding job." Seymour Hersh, Pulitzer-prize-winning
journalist.

<P>   "A tremendously useful tool for any reporter or researcher."
The Nation.

<P>   "A powerful tool that includes obscure sources and a
comprehensive cross-index." The Progressive.

<P>   "An encyclopedia of CIA actions." San Francisco Chronicle.

<P>   "An amazing addition to the information world....
it is absolutely indispensable." Louis Wolf, editor
Covert Action Quarterly.

<P>   "Former CIA officer Ralph McGehee has recently updated his
excellent CIABASE system adding information from a number of new
on-line or printed publications..." "Intelligence" an on-line
magazine on worldwide developments in intelligence, 9/11/95.

<P>   The CIA called Ralph McGehee, who compiled CIABASE, an
analyst with few peers. McGehee served 25 years in the CIA,
14 years overseas as an operations officer and 11 years at its
headquarters.  Upon leaving the CIA, McGehee wrote the book
"Deadly Deceits" and began the multi-year process of compiling
CIABASE.  McGehee is a recognized authority on the CIA and has
testified many times both in Congress and in the courts and has
appeared numerous times on radio and TV.
</P>
<PRE>
            Some CIABASE subject categories are:

Academia
Agent (types, handling)
Air Op and Airline
Ambassador (relations with)
Approvals
Assassinations
Assets
Bases
Biological War
Black Market
Book and Book Review
Bribery
Budget
Chemical War
Communist Threat
Computers
Conflict, LI
Consequences
Contragate
Coordination
Corporate Interests
Counterinsurgency
Counterintel
Cover
Covert Action
Cultural
Death Squads
Deaths (of CIA personnel)
Deception
Defense Dept
Domestic Op
Drugs
Economic Intel/War
Executive Order
Election
FBI
Flap
Forgery
Foundation
Front Org
Funding
Harassment
History
Intel Community
Intel F(ailure)
Intel Op
Intel S(success)
Intel-Policy
International Orgs
Investigation of
KGB
Labor
Law
Leaks
Liaison
Maritime Op
Media
Mercenaries
Military
Mind Control
Minorities
NED (National Endowment for Democracy)
NSAG (Nat Security Agency)
NSC (Nat Security Council)
Operation (by cryptonym)
Org, Ops (Adm, Intel, etc.)
Oversight
Overthrow
Paramilitary
Personnel (policies)
Police
Procedures
Propaganda
Proprietary
Psywar
Publication
Purpose of
Quote
Reconnaissance (tech ops)
Religion
Requirements
Sex
Special Forces
Stations
Students
Tech, Audio (Photo, SW, etc.)
Terrorism
Think Tank
Torture
Training
Veterans
Watch List
Weaponry
White Paper
Youth
Z NED         Special category due to volume of entries re NED</PRE>

            ----------------------------------<BR>
            CIABASE ORDER FORM - IBM/MACINTOSH<BR>
            ----------------------------------<BR>

<P>CIABASE works with any monitor. A hard disk is essential due to
the over 10MB of information with the 48K search program software.

<P>IBM compatible: Check one [ ]  5.25-inch, AT HD disks.
[ ]  3.5-inch, 720K  disks. [ ]  3.5-inch, 1.4MB disks

<P>MACINTOSH -  check one [ ] 800K disks. [ ] 1.4MB disks

<P>Please enclose a check or money order for $199.00 (no checks
drawn on foreign banks).

<P>CIABASE provides original purchasers updates @ $99.00. CIABASE
holds most all source material and will photocopy for a fee.

CIABASE<BR>
POB 5022<BR>
Herndon, VA, 20172-1961<BR>
Phone (703) 437-8487<BR>
Fax (703) 437-8487<BR>
<a href="MAILTO:rmcgehee@igc.apc.org">rmcgehee@igc.apc.org</a><BR>

<P>For a one-level trial search of CIABASE's four-field
search structure, see the prize-winning web site at --<BR>
<a href="http://www.webcom.com/%7Epinknoiz/covert/ciabase.html">http://www.webcom.com/%7Epinknoiz/covert/ciabase.html</a>

<BR>

</td>

