<!-- Article Body Table ---------------------------------------------->

<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<img border=0 width=43 height=43 src="../../images/question.gif">
</td>
<td valign=middle width=440>
<center><h3>
 The Spring and the  CWSAPPS LIST<BR>
Announce Online User Conferences<BR>

</h3>

</Center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>

<BR>
20 November 1996
<BR>

<BR>

<P><CENTER>DISCUSSION FORUM FOR USER INPUT NOW AVAILABLE
FROM THE INTERNET'S PREMIER SOFTWARE SITE </CENTER>

<P>AUSTIN, TX (November 11, 1996) -- The world's premier web site for Internet 
applications announced today a 
new conferencing system that will allow users to share their opinions on 
applications and software 
packages freely available on the World Wide Web. The Consummate Winsock Apps 
List (The CWSApps List), in 
partnership with the Spring World Wide Web site, offers the new system as an 
extension of its already 
free Internet software services. In addition to previously offering users 
up-to-date information and 
reviews for the latest and greatest software available on the Internet, The 
CWSApps List will now be 
able to give its users a voice in the process as well. 

<P>Both novice and expert users will be able to benefit by having immediate access 
to input from one of the 
Internet's most respected software gurus as well as from the millions of users 
that frequent The CWSApps 
List. Applications reviewed and available for discussion at the sites include 
e-mail clients, WWW (World 
Wide Web) browsers, Usenet newsreaders, FTP (file transfer protocol) clients, 
HTML (Hyper Text Markup 
Language) editors, VRML (Virtual Reality Modeling Language) browsers, and more. 
In addition, the sites 
offer auxiliary Internet applications including virus scanners, image viewing 
and manipulation tools, 
compression utilities, and spelling checkers. 

<P>Integrating users into the process of reviewing, categorizing, and rating 
Internet software is expected 
to be the primary benefit of the new conferencing section. In addition, novice 
users will find extensive 
resources for getting up and running with the best software for use on the 
Internet. Experts will be 
able to discuss with their peers the best uses for existing software, including 
new features that need 
to be added and existing problems that need to be addressed. The need for new 
applications to satisfy 
unmet user needs is another anticipated benefit. 

<P>New users to the system can browse the available topics but will first need to 
register in order to 
fully utilize the conferencing and input your own comments (registration is 
free). At this point, a user 
can access more than 300 individual forums based on the software applications 
reviewed by The CWSApps 
List. Access is available to each forum through the full review section for each 
application featured on 
the list. A comprehensive listing of conference areas is also available at 
<a href="http://www.spring.com/yapp-bin/public/browse/apps/all">http://www.spring.com/yapp-bin/public/browse/apps/all</a>. 

<P>No other service on the Internet will make it easier for users to obtain the 
newest applications, 
information on these applications, and opinions from both satistifed and 
unsatisfied customers. Both The 
CWSApps List site itself and the conferencing section will be updated daily in 
order to ensure that 
users have immediate access to the newest products and the latest information on 
their favorite 
applications. Help files and informational links to aid users in troubleshooting 
apps and learning more 
about clients will be provided as well as comprehensive reviews for more than 
300 different software 
applications. These free services will continue to be available to anyone with 
Internet access and a 
World Wide Web browser. Available Web browsers include Netscape Navigator, NCSA 
Mosaic, and Internet 
Explorer. 

<P>The CWSApps List is a World Wide Web site located at <a href="www.cwsapps.com">www.cwsapps.com</a> and 
<a href="www.stroud.com">www.stroud.com</a> that offers 
users links to the most popular Internet software clients on the net. In 
addition to providing easy 
access to these programs, The CWSApps List rates and reviews each application, 
providing critical 
information on each program including the newest version available, recent 
changes, home page links, and 
much more. The CWSApps List is, quite simply, the single most important 
reference for Windows 3.x, 95, 
and NT Internet applications on the World Wide Web. The CWSApps List currently 
has mirror sites at more 
than forty locations in twenty different countries. Together these sites receive 
over two million hits a 
day. The list is maintained in its entirety by Forrest H. Stroud, 
<a href="MAILTO:neuroses@tcac.com">neuroses@tcac.com</a>. 

<P>apps conference site: <a href="http://www.spring.com">http://www.spring.com</a> or telnet spring.com
<P>conference manager: <a href="MAILTO:terry@spring.com">terry@spring.com</a> * Paul Terry Walhus * 512/303-4000

<P>The Spring is Austin, Texas version of the WELL.  The Spring supports 
conferences on many 
subjects of cultural, poltical, and educational interest.  Topics include tv, 
movies, books,
music, politics, cultures, spirit, the net, unix, vitual communities, sports, 
performing 
arts, the austin scene, and more.  </P>

</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
