<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<img border=0 width=43 height=43 src="../../images/chez.gif">
</td>
<td valign=middle width=440>
<center><h3>
Winn Schwartau <BR>
Interview for a Dutch publication by Walter Belgers
</h3>


</Center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>


<BR>
Interview:<BR>

<P>En hier is dan het eerste echte Giga-Interview. Niet zoals aangekondigd
met Dan Farmer, maar wel met Winn Schwartau, die zich bezighoudt met
Information Warfare.

<P>Als je daar meer over wilt weten kun je:
<UL>
- op Winn's site kijken, http://www.infowar.com/ ;<BR>
- zijn boek "Information Warfare, Chaos on the Electronic Superhighway"
  lezen (Thunder's Mouth Press, 1994). Dit boek is een droog verhaal
  over wat Information Warfare is en wat je ertegen kunt doen. Niet echt
  een aanrader;<BR>
- zijn boek "Terminal Compromise" (Inter.Pact Press, 1993) lezen. Dit is
  een echter techno-roman, onderhoudend en spannend. Wel een aanrader,
  temeer omdat dit boek ook het eerste shareware boek is, je kunt het
  gratis van Internet downloaden (bijvoorbeeld van ftp.eu.net als
   /documents/published/books/terminal-compromise/termcomp.zip).<BR>
</UL>
<P>Het interview is voornamelijk geschreven n.a.v. het boek "Information
Warfare".</P>

Walter=Walter Belgers<BR>
Winn=Winn Schartau<BR>

<P>Walter: The book "Information Warfare" is clearly written from the
US perspective. It repeatedly states the US are the victims of
information crimes. Don't you think every country in the world uses
information warfare in one way or another? Contrary to your beliefs
("Shouldn't we try to [..] do a little industrial and economic spying
of our own?") I think (know) that the US is involved in information
warfare and industrial spying at this very moment.

<P>Winn: The US perspective - yup; you're right. Any society or country
that depends upon its infrastructure for survival is just as
vulnerable as the US. And every day that is becoming truer and
truer. Infowar is only now coming out of the closet. Don't forget
that when I wrote it, Infowar was still classified by the US
military.  The book broke thru the veils of secrecy. Yes, we do
some spying, but not as an open collaboration between the government
and the private sector.  Spies may be willing to die for their
country, but not for IBM or Exxon. Our primary infowar capabilities
are for the military at this point. I am working with several
countries in this area to develop a greater convergence between
the government and private sector. Common electronic civil defense
is the answer.

<P>Walter: You say that people suffer from "Binary Schizophrenia",
they are afraid of the amount of control computers have, and that
they want to have control themselves. I see just the opposite,
people want to run Windows 95 on Plug & Play computers, and credit
cards and other things that make life easy (sic). What makes you
say they want control?

<P>Winn: Plug and Play is the problem, exactly. People do not really
know what is going on underneath the cover and behind the PLAY
button. They want the convenience without knowing the insides. And
when something goes wrong, they rightfully so, blame the computers.
The schizophrenia is "I need and want computers, but I hate them
at the same time." Only a very small percentage of the population
really knows the technology.

<P>Walter: What is your definition of a hacker? In "Information
Warfare", you say hackers cracked into hundreds of computer sites
in February 1994 and stole hundreds of thousands of passwords using
sophisticated software.  To me, those are not hackers but vandals.
I also think the software is not sophisticated. If somebody invents
a nail, and I put it on the road to cause flat tires, I'm just a
vandal that doesn't do anything sophisticated.

<P>Winn: Simplicity is the best way to commit a crime. The difference
between hackers and criminals is indeed gray. I prefer to think of
it as an issue of capabilities rather than intentions. And yes,
the lines are emerging: hacker, cracker, criminal, terrorist. In
Apollo 13, the NASA engineers hacked with the tools they had
available to them to save the astronauts lives. Hacking is the use
and stretching of technology to its limits.

<P>Walter: Some new threats you see in the information society are
HERF guns and van Eck eavesdropping. I first saw a demonstration of
van Eck on Dutch television in the early 80s, but recently I've
heard from several people who investigated van Eck that its practical
use is almost zero because of interference with other systems (it's
rare to have just one monitor in a room). Where did you get your
results?

<P>Winn: That statement is inaccurate. I have built my own Van Eck
devices and it is indeed easy to distinguish between monitors
because of differences in relative horizontal scan frequencies. At
trade shows we could pick and choose our targets from hundreds on
the floor, lock into the hotel systems or surveillance cameras.
Whoever hasn't played with these systems just doesn't understand
how they work.

<P>Walter: Who are the bad guys anyway? I don't think many Information
Warriors will cause great havoc if they're working alone. I'm afraid
of Information Warriors that get orders from big institutions/countries.
You even say the White House ordered the IRS to investigate tax
records.  One of the creapiest things I've ever seen was a movie
about the US having a military base in England where most satellite
traffic was intercepted and scanned for information. Should we be
afraid of people operating on the edge of the law when we're being
attacked by multinationals?

<P>Winn: The whole point is capabilities. Whether it's over exuberant
law enforcement, or big companies gone mad; or the White House
going over the edge, it's the same thing. This is about motivation
and intention - and that almost doesn't matter.  The bad guys are
anyone with the technology, the know-how and an attitude.

<P>Walter: Is there a way to protect yourself against an attack? You
say "most companies don't plan for one, much less two, disasters
at a time" but "We can defeat the Information Warrior". How can we
if we get, say, 10 disasters at a time? How can we protect against
EMPT/Y bombs?

<P>Winn: The first defense is a board or executive level policy which
says, "we recognize the value of our information and info-systems
and want to protect ourselves against our potential adversaries."
This must be a corporate mandate.

<P>Two, institute proper perimeter control mechanisms, firewalls,
replace passwords with decent idenfitication mechanisms, get rid
of floppy drives, train security guards properly, institute waste
management procedures.

<P>Three. Train, retrain and retrain again. Staff, management, lawyers,
accoutnants, human resources etc.

<P>Four. Develop contingency plans for the Acts of Man as well as the
Acts of God. Learn how to think like the Bad Guys.

<P>Against EMP and HERF? Today, it's too hard and expensive to defend
that at the front lines. If someone uses that, today, you have to
retreat, regroup and get a response mechanism in place. The technology
to defend is unwieldly, and is not perfect. But, we are working on
it.

<P>Walter: Can you still enjoy computers and computer networks?

<P>Winn: Yes, but only with adult supervision. :-)

<P>Walter: When you discuss a National Information Policy, you say
that encryption is something that should be regulated. Don't you
think encryption techniques are a great opportunity instead of a
threat? First of all there's an economic interest. The US have made
it impossible to develop encryption techniques as they cannot be
exported. Non-US encryption techniques however can be used all over
the world which gives non-US countries an advantage. Furthermore,
encryption provides a perfect way to ensure privacy in an age where
we trust almost everything to computers. If we use DigiCash instead
of real cash, our transactions are becoming even more private than
they are now! With encryption, I can authenticate myself, which I
can't when talking to a stranger on the phone, so that's a big
improvement.

<P>Winn: Crypto is a national issue for the politicians, civil
liberatarians and anyone else who cares. But to understand it, you
have to be able to switch hats.</P>
<UL>	1. Why would law enforcement want to permit the export or
	   unrestricted use of crypto which will only make their
	   job harder? That makes no sense.<BR>
	2. Why would a foreign country want the US holding the keys
           on a crypto system within their borders? They wouldn't.<BR>
	3. Why would any criminal worth his salt not super-encrypt
           any messages that use government approved crypto?
</UL>
<P>So, we switch hats and get different views.

<P>Then, anonymous transactions are a legitimate worry for nations;
drugs and illegal laundering of money. Of course they don't want
that to happen.

<P>I am not convinced that there is a sensible answer that will work
for us all. There needs to be compromise, but it is ultimately an
issue of power.

<P>So, the US cannot regulate foreign crypto. The US is not the smartest
in crypto. There are no borders. The proposed policies are generally
ineffective.

<P>Walter: I hear you have recently been a victim of information
warriors that have tampered with your phone. Why do you think they
picked you?

<P>Winn: I still have no real reason except that I am a high profile
target. Vengeance maybe? Jealousy? Maybe. Maybe they just need to
get a life. I recently received a WAV file with a fake interview
they constructed from TV bits I did and edited it so I said I
wanted to take down the telephone companies. Waste of their time.

<P>Walter: A few weeks ago, I read that cops in the US are testing a
HERF gun to stop cars that are being chased. What do you think of
this development?

<P>Winn: A potential for good, a potential for evil. So far this is
urban lore talking, and yes it works in labs, but we have political
questions that must be addressed before these systems can be
deployed. What happens if:</P>

        - the car goes of control?<BR>
        - You shoot the wrong car?<BR>
        - You fry the driver's liver with microwaves?<BR>

<P>A ways to go before the police deploy them.

<P>(c)1996 Walter Belgers <walter@giga.nl>. Dit interview mag alleen als
onderdeel van TOM18 of na uitdrukkelijke toestemming van de auteur
verspreid worden.

<BR>

</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<br>
