<td valign=middle width=440>
<center><h2>

From Sources e-Journal
</h2>

<a href="http://www.dso.com/sources">Sources E-Journal </A>
</Center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>


<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>W</FONT>inn Schwartau is considered by some to be one of the country's leading experts on information security and electronic privacy. He is often referred to as "<I>the civilian architect of information warfare</I>" by those who study United States national security in cyberspace. His writings and research have served to bring a previously classified subject into the "<I>commercial</I>," open source arena. 
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>A</FONT>s the President of Interpact, Inc., Mr. Schwartau provides valuable services to both private and public industry, as well as governments on Information Warfare, how it is waged and how to best defend against information attack. Mr. Schwartau has been working to establish US and International policies and standards with regards to electronic privacy and related issues. His work and clients have grown globally, and now span three continents. 
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>H</FONT>is non-fiction book, "<B>Information Warfare: Chaos on the Electronic Superhighway</B>" is considered required reading on the subject. It is a compelling, analysis of personal privacy, economic and industrial espionage, national security and defense. Schwartau calls for the creation of a <B>National Information Policy, a Constitution in Cyberspace</B> and an <B>Electronic Bill of Rights</B>
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>M</FONT>r. Schwartau also authored the novel "<B>Terminal Compromise</B>" which details a fictionalized account of an information war waged on the United States. This prophetic book predicted a number of cyber-events, including the Clipper Chip, illegal chipping, magnetic weapons assaults and data and hardware viruses to name a few. He has written articles for <I>Information Week, Network World, ComputerWorld, Network Security, Internet World, Infoworld, and PC Week</I>, and had a script called "<B>The Hackers</B>," produced on TV's <I>Law and Order</I>.
</BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="Start Interview"></A>
<align="right"><B>SOURCES:</B><BR> <FONT SIZE=+2>I</FONT> have to pose this to you this up front, given that <I>Wired</I> hasn't gotten around to reviewing, or, apparently, reading your book -- <I>Wired</I> recently opined that infowar is nothing more than a hyped meme that won't last another year; that it means nothing; that there is no such thing as information warfare; that it's not going to happen? What do you say to that notion given its being touted in such a popular journal of cyber culture?
<BR>
<BR>
<B>SCHWARTAU:</B><BR> <FONT SIZE=+2>I</FONT> can't believe they're that blind. I don't know why, other than looking at some of the influences of the people that have been involved in <I>Wired</I>. For example, I gave one of the first speeches ever given in the U.S. on infowarfare, back in 1992, when the subject was still classified by the government. So, if it's a flash in the pan, it's been a flash in the pan now for four years, not eleven months. 
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>J</FONT>ohn Perry Barlow was in the audience, he was a speaker at the same conference, and I was sitting there describing my views on what's going to be happening, and he's shaking his head and holding his head in his hands, going "<I>no, no, no.</I>" The rest of the audience was understanding exactly what I was talking about, it was a heavily military and heavily intelligence-oriented group. I talked to John afterwards, and he didn't say so in exactly these words, but my impression was, was that he views this whole cyberspace thing, whatever you want to call it, as a panacea, as a great social wonderment, as the benevolent future, and he doesn't want to see any negative aspects of it. 
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>he same thing occurred with Al Gore back in 1990 when he introduced the national information superhighway. I met with him, and I said "<I>what about the problems with it</I>," and he and those around him did not want to talk about the problems. My view was that, in Gore's case it was politically derailing for his initiative, with the Barlow's and the other people of the world who pooh-pooh my kind of work; they basically only want to look at the good side things and don't want to look at the downside risks.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>SOURCES:</B><BR> <FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>hat's kind of the way Bob Steele sees this whole issue. What he told me recently is that he sees "<I>a complete lack of vision in the senior leadership positions and a strong reluctance to tell the President that we cannot defend our home electronics.</I>"
<BR>
<BR>
<B>SCHWARTAU:</B><BR> <FONT SIZE=+2>S</FONT>teele and I agree on that 100% 
<BR>
<BR>
<B>SOURCES:</B><BR> <FONT SIZE=+2>I</FONT>f the intel community and the defense community understand the problems and the security and other issues, then why is there such a slowness in addressing this problem, addressing it adequately. You know, they've got some good people who understand the problem, like <B>Emmett Paige</B>, but as far as getting the momentum going it doesn't seem like it's happening.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>SCHWARTAU:</B><BR> <FONT SIZE=+2>G</FONT><B>eneral Edmonds</B> from <B>DISA</B> has some very good insights, and so, too, does Paige, they understand the problems very well, and there are a number of others. I think there are two fundamental problems: 
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>O</FONT>ne is that the senior leadership within the intel and military computer community tend to be a little bit older, and, that's not meant to be a criticism, but it's an observation that they have not grown up with this technology; they have not grown up in the environment. They don't live in cyberspace, and an awful lot of them still very much have a Cold War mindset. They're entrenched in the bomb and bullet scenarios, living in a bipolar, militaristic world, whereas <B>we are now moving into a world of distributed capabilities</B>. 
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>he second issue is that the White House doesn't have a vision for this future. They're talking about creating jobs, and about reducing poverty, and, yes, these are all terrifically important things, I'm not going to downplay them at all, but I have not heard out of the <B>White House</B> or out of <B>Congress</B> any vision about where this country needs to go or how it's going to get there. They're not recognizing the very fundamental changes that are occurring. <B>This country's wealth is now based on its econo-technical infrastructure</B>. The econo-technical infrastructure is the fundamental '<I>framework</I>,' if you will, of our value-added wealth. And until they thoroughly understand that and until it has become part of their thinking and planning system, I believe it's going to be difficult for them to see the risks that are coming with this '<I>framework</I>.'
<BR>
<BR>
<B>SOURCES:</B><BR> <FONT SIZE=+2>I</FONT>s it going to take something cataclysmic? Steele says he's waiting for a major disaster and a totally new team to come in?
<BR>
<BR>
<B>SCHWARTAU:</B><BR> <FONT SIZE=+2>O</FONT>ne of two things need to happen, and I've been saying this since 1990 when my first models on infowar came out. <B>It's either going to take a computer Chernobyl, or an electronic Pearl Harbor</B>, or it's going to take a lot of lawyers doing a lot of suing.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>SOURCES:</B><BR> <FONT SIZE=+2>W</FONT>hat do you think, if we do have an electronic apocalypse, where is it going to come from? <I>Wired</I>, you know, sarcastically wondered who would pull it off? Somalia? Where is this infowar battle going to come from as far as an attack on the U.S. or on some other industrialized western nation?
<BR>
<BR>
<B>SCHWARTAU:</B><BR> <FONT SIZE=+2>W</FONT>ell, there's different levels of it. We've already been involved to a certain degree in an infowar with Somalia, and the component of the infowar was in perception management and deception that occurred right before we went in and right after we left. The media was involved in this aspect of it, and the United States had public support behind it to go in because we saw pictures on television of some starving babies; food being diverted away from the people who needed it, and a country that was essentially in chaos and was being run by independent warlords. Okay, we were going to go in and straighten things out as peacemakers. However, one dead soldier being dragged across the TV screens of America was enough to make us pull out. 
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>o a certain extent that was information warfare and psy-ops, aimed at the population's perception and at the country's management. But, that kind of thing aside, Somalia is not going to be the one, I don't believe, that's going to launch a computer Chernobyl against us. As to who's going to do it, that's what the intelligence community is supposed to figure out. They're supposed to figure out who. I avoid that purposely, except in the most general terms, in my work. I don't worry about the intentions, I don't worry about who's going to be behind it. <B>I concentrate on the capabilities angle, looking at the structure of the organization that would be required to pull it off, the kind of resources they would need to do it, the kind manpower or army they'd have to have at their disposal in order to launch a sizable attack of this nature against us.</B>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>SOURCES:</B><BR> <FONT SIZE=+2>A</FONT>side from where the intel and defense communities are on this issue, what about the commercial sector, banking for instance. I'm now looking at a <B>Federal Financial Institutions Examination Council</B>, or FFIEC, memo on the control and security risks of electronic imaging systems. It talks a great deal about internal controls and such, <B>but says nothing about the risks from Van Eck eavesdropping</B>, for instance. This seems to me to be very naive and very shortsighted. It represents, I think, the shortsightedness and naivete that exists on the part of the banking regulators -- even down to the field examiner level. There seems to be a lack of training, but more than that, a lack of understanding of state-of-the-art, cutting-edge security risks. How do you view all this?
<BR>
<BR>
<B>SCHWARTAU:</B><BR> <FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>here's a lot of issues here. Number one, the way that we're teaching people as they go through college; we're teaching them how to use computers, how to use applications, here's how to program, now go out into the world and make some money. What we're not teaching them is what the totality of the cyberworld really is, when it comes to understanding the technology and all the various aspects of it. Again, we're teaching the "sweetness and light" side of it, but we're not teaching some of the downside risks and some of the vulnerabilities. 
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>W</FONT>hen we look at the commercial world, they take an awful lot of their positions from authoritative sources, and they listen a good deal to the DOD and to the intel community. The strategy of the intel community has been to keep the nature of any threat highly classified, not to talk about it. DISA, however, has come a long way in exposing the threat. But until the DOD and the intel community realize that they and the commercial sector are on the same track, that there is a true convergence of interests, a true convergence of business models between the military and business, I think that we're going to have that perceptual separation between the two worlds.
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>N</FONT>ow, let's get into banking for a moment. In the classic world of infosecurity, there's a triad, three legs on which security stands. And these three legs are confidentiality, keeping secrets a secret, integrity, and availability. From a confidentiality standpoint and an integrity standpoint, we essentially have the technology to solve most of those problems, by using cryptographic methods, decent key management, and well-administered sites. It's not necessarily going to be easy in all cases, but we have the fundamental technology to be able to solve these two problems of the triad. 
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>H</FONT>owever, when we get into availability, the ability of systems to stay up for businesses that rely upon technology, we have not addressed that. Denial of service has typically been a military model, in a situation where one blinds the enemy, or kills the enemy, or destroys his infrastructure. In all the work I do with corporate America, I try make this point, going after whether they've got their crypto and administration and the rest of that triad taken care of yet. I mean, when it comes to attacks, they have the acts of God covered. They can deal with 
hurricanes. They can deal with tornadoes. They can deal with earthquakes and floods, but they cannot deal with the acts of man. They do not have policies or procedures to deal with assault, with a concentrated, intentional assault against their facility, especially when it comes to their being denied service. 
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>C</FONT>arrying this idea one step further, and I'm not going to go into details because we're still finishing up the research -- some associates and myself -- but we have identified a means to literally destroy the entire global economy a lot simpler than we had ever before thought possible. An associate of mine did the primary research, and we're going to be coming out with it in the next several months.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>SOURCES:</B><BR> <FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>hat's a frightening concept.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>SCHWARTAU:</B><BR> <FONT SIZE=+2>W</FONT>hen I first met this gentleman and saw the research, my jaw hit the ground. It blew me away. There's just an absolutely stunning vulnerability that's been totally overlooked.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>SOURCES:</B><BR> <FONT SIZE=+2>W</FONT>hat about any U.S. offensive infowar capabilities? Paige said at a recent conference that I shouldn't bother taking any notes because no one's going to talk about it. 
<BR>
<BR>
<B>SCHWARTAU:</B><BR> <FONT SIZE=+2>I</FONT>'m glad that you brought that up. I guess that's why I get brought into an awful lot of places, because I do talk about the offensive capability. Number one, I do not have a clearance, have never had a clearance, and have turned down opportunities to have clearances by a number of spook agencies because it would destroy my ability to work. 
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>W</FONT>e have some pretty interesting offensive capabilities. We have offensive capabilities in the software realm; remote software, viral, malicious software injection. We've got blinding capabilities [that can be applied] militarily against adversaries in theater. We've got the Van Eck remote eavesdropping capabilities. And then, of course, we've got the denial of service capabilities through magnetic weapons [directed energy weapons] and there's a whole arsenal of those, ranging from portable backpack versions up to trailer truck size. 
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>S</FONT>o we do have a wide range of offensive capabilities. We have the manufacturing capability, we have the distribution capability, we have the injection capabilities, we have the mapping and cracking capabilities.
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>I</FONT> do not know whether our cyber forces are organized in any fashion yet, though, and would doubt it because the capabilities are so distributed throughout the various services and branches of the intelligence community. What I doubt we have is the capability to launch an effective 'exclusively cyber' war, without bombs and bullets, yet.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>SOURCES:</B><BR> <FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>here is no cyber corps yet.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>SCHWARTAU:</B><BR> <FONT SIZE=+2>N</FONT>ot yet. It's still distributed, and that's one of the arguments that a lot of us are making, that we do need to examine in all seriousness the creation of a fourth force, a center of excellence for cyberwar.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>SOURCES:</B><BR> <FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>hank you for your time. 
<BR>
<BR>
<font size=-2>
<BR>
