<td valign=middle width=440>
<center><h2>

</h2>


</Center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>


<h2><Center>Warp Speed Snail Mail:</H4>
PO'Net Comes to Life<BR>
by Winn Schwartau</Center>
<BR>
The  idea is to bring the National Information Infrastructure  to everyone.  <P>

So  who do they give the job to?  The United States Post  Office: the government's answer to "Oh, you expect us to deliver?"  <P>

Everyone  means everyone, according to the government,  not  just folks who can afford a computer and a modem.  I think.  Universal access  is the USPO's job in life  No matter how far out  in  the boonies you live, a mail box means that the Feds have to  deliver "snail  mail" to your door.  They have to have a man and a  truck and a road and distribute the mail to the Mayberry RFD address on the  envelop,  no  matter how far or  distasteful  the  location.  Inner city war-slums or poverty soaked Appalachia, the USPO  says their man has to be there, letter in hand. <P>

But with the electronic superhighway gaining momentum, the  folks with  the money have been driving the ship.  Even if  getting  on board  only  costs $10-$20 per month, the Feds say,  "That's  too much."   It's gotta be, well, close to free.  <P>

I've thought about this, and there is both good and bad.  Is  the USPO going to distribute mail by wire . . . string wires to every hamlet  and  lick from Alaska to Kentucky, and  as  suggested  by recent news, build their own network to the side of the  Internet and compete with Compuserve and PSI. You have to wonder what  the poor man's electronic mail box will consist of: a TV set with  an interactive  connection to the cable company?  Not if there's  no cable.   I  wonder about their motivations:  remember,  the  Post Office  has been claiming eminent domain over the  mails,  saying that  Federal Express intrudes on their Congressionally  provided mail  monopoly.   Once in the e-mail business,  would  they  then claim  they have exclusive rights to deliver electronic  mail  as well?  <P>

Imagine  the  concept  of the  information  disenfranchised.   If you're  poor, and can't afford a real connection to the 'Net  for e-mail, you have to resort to the class of service that the  USPO will offer. (I can just see 3 trillion undelivered e-mail letters stacked  in  a Chicago warehouse next to  the  undelivered  snail mail.)   <P>

But  the  USPO has equally daunting problems  to  consider.   The current  snail-mail is secure.  Confidentiality is  offered,  and under  universal electronic access, similar concepts must  apply.  The  private sector is working towards solutions which  will  fit the private sector's needs and meet the cultural ethos of  cybernauts.  What would the feds solution look like? <P>

I fear, more than anything else, the dreaded word: Clipper. <P>

What  better way to proliferate such an abhorred  technology  and permeate the digital life of every man than by the US Post  Office adapting  a Clipper-like technology to protect the integrity  and confidentiality  of the new federal e-mail system?   "Reach  out and  touch someone" takes on new meaning if  the  Clipper-critics are even just partially correct. <P>

Clipper  is voluntary (yeah, yeah) but the IRS is reported to  be readying  an electronic filing system that must use  Clipper/Capstone/Key Escrow approaches.  Nothing else will do.  So much  for voluntary.   And if the USPO takes a similar stance?  I pity  the Federal official who has to explain this one to America.  A month of  early retirement for each day of  public abuse would  be  the minimum bonus . . .<P>

Whatever  the  approach chosen, if the United  States  government gets  into  the e-mail business, we'll end up with  two  distinct classes  of people: those who use the 'Net and those who use  the PO'Net.   Say  that:  PO'Net, and  unfortunately  that's  exactly who'll be stuck using it. <P>



<BR>

</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<br>
