<td valign=middle width=440>
<center><h3>
Statement from Permanent Subcommittee<BR>  on Investigations.
</h3>


</Center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>
23 November 1996<BR>

<BR>
William V. Roth, Jr., Chairman<BR>
Sam Nunn, Ranking Minority Member<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Contacts:  Mark Webster or John Sopko
                193 Russell Senate Office Building
                Washington, D.C.  20510
                (202) 224-9157  tel
                (202) 224-1972  fax
</PRE>

<P>Subject:  Information Systems Security Survey conducted by WarRoom Research, LLC

<P>The questionnaire was of great interest to Senator Sam Nunn, Ranking Minority Member of the U.S. Senate Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations.  This past summer, the Subcommittee expanded its series of investigations into national security issues by examing the threats and vulnerabilities of our National Information Infrastructure.  Hearings were held in May, June and July 1996 which showed how dependent our nation is on the reliability of computer networks, the integrity of the information flowing and stored on these networks, and on the accessibility of information available on these networks.  For this reason, the Subcommittee expressed interest in including WarRoom Research's survey results as part of its hearing record.  To do this, the Subcommittee promised to respect the survey's guarantee of anonymity to all respondents.  Although this survey was a collaborative effort with the Subcommittee and was developed to be independent of their work, WarRoom Research's survey results supported the Subcommittees findings.
</P>
</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
